<FIRST>r w AM-US-Pakistan 3rdLd-Writethru a0818 06-07 0907</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Pakistan, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0818,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush and Bhutto Seek Political Solution To Afghanistan Stalemate</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS grafs 18-20: ``In an,'' with Mrs. Bhuotto's nuclear
remarks in interview report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto WX15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday told visiting
Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto that the United States is
willing ``to explore any serious avenue'' to achieve a political
solution in Afghanistan.
   Mrs. Bhutto in turn said after private talks with the president
that ``we are in complete accord'' on the situation in Afghanistan,
stalemated since the pullout of the last Soviet troops in February.
   Bush said the withdrawal of the Red Army proved the effectiveness
of U.S-Pakistani support for the Afghan resistance fighting the
Marxist regime in Kabul. Pakistan shares a common border with
Afghanistan.
   ``We agreed, however, that the job is not done,'' said Bush.
``The Mujahedeen continues and their struggle for self-determination
goes on.''
   ``Prime Minister Bhutto and I discussed ways to encourage a
political solution in Afghanistan that will lead to a non-aligned,
representative government willing to live in peace with its
neighbors, to replace the illegitimate regime in Kabul,'' said Bush.
``The United States and Pakistan will continue to explore any
serious avenue towards this end.''
   U.S. officials had anticipated a rapid demise for the government
of Najibullah after the Soviet pullout, but it has not happened.
   Mrs. Bhutto said she and Bush ``have reviewed the situation in
the light of the prevailing circumstances and we are in complete
accord'' on what needs to be done.
   ``Pakistan remains committed to a political solution of the
Afghan problem, whereby the brave people of Afghanistan will have
the right to freely choose their own government without interference
from outside,'' she said.
   Mrs. Bhutto, the daughter of former Prime Minister Ali Bhutto,
said that while the Soviet pullout ``has brought a welcome change in
Afghanistan, the continued fighting and prolonged presence of over
3.5 million Afghan refugees pose serious threats to the peace and
stability of the region.''
   After a full-dress military ceremony on the White House lawn,
including a 19-gun salute, and an Oval Office meeting with Bush,
Mrs. Bhutto went to the State Department for a meeting with
Secretary of State James A. Baker III and a lunch in her honor.
   At a state dinner Tuesday evening, Bush joked during the exchange
of toasts that Mrs. Bhutto had ``refused my latest offer. She's not
going double or nothing on this year's Harvard-Yale game.''
   Keeping up the Ivy League banter, Mrs. Bhutto responded: ``Ladies
and gentlemen, I studied at Harvard and believe me, I didn't know
until tonight that Yale ever produced charming men. I'm glad I met
the only one.''
   Mrs. Bhutto is a 1973 Harvard graduate; Bush is a 1948 graduate
of arch-rival Yale.
   Pakistan has a standing request to buy 60 more F-16 fighter jets
from the United States. Bush brushed aside reporters' attempts to
ask about reports that approval of the jet sale is imminent.
   An administration official, briefing reporters at the White
House, said Bush and Mrs. Bhutto discussed the F-16 sale, but ``I
wouldn't anticipate any specific announcement from outside'' during
her visit. The official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
indicated there were no stumbling blocks to the sale, but normal
steps such as congressional notification would take more time.
   On another topic, Bush said Mrs. Bhutto ``assured me that
Pakistan's nuclear program is committed to peaceful purposes.''
   He said he underlined his commitment ``to discourage
proliferation of nuclear and chemical weapons, ballistic missiles,
in the South Asia region and around the world.''
   In an interview with editors of The Washington Post, Mrs. Bhutto
said she had ``very frank talk'' with Bush and CIA Director William
Webster, and assured them Pakistan does not intend to build nuclear
weapons.
   She said she wanted Bush to help Pakistan reach a nuclear
test-ban treay with ``other countries in the region,'' an apparent
reference to long-ti8me rival India, according to a report on the
interview in Wednesday editions.
   India exploded what it called a nuclear ``device'' in 1974.
Webster last month said Pakistan ``clearly'' was developing nuclear
capability and Indian appeared interested in developing
thermonculear weapons.
   The two leaders also discussed efforts to combat drug production
and trafficking. Bush said he ``applauded her tough stance on
eradicating the opium cultivation'' and thanked her for extraditing
an alleged drug trafficker.
   The two countries were expected to sign agreements on housing,
narcotics and education this week during Bhutto's stay. Pakistan,
the third largest recipient of U.S. aid, is slated for $380 million
in economic assistance and $240 million in military aid next year.
   Mrs. Bhutto's father was deposed by Gen. Mohammad Zia ul-Haq in
1977 and hanged two years later for a political murder. Zia remained
in power until perishing in a mysterious plane crash last year that
also claimed the life of U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel and an
American general.
   Mrs. Bhutto, who had picked up her father's fallen standard and
been jailed for a time under Zia, led her Pakistan People's Party to
victory as head of a coalition government last November.
   Mrs. Bhutto was scheduled to address a joint session of Congress
on Wednesday. She also had stops here at the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund. She will receive an honorary degree at
her alma mater, Harvard University, on Thursday and visit the United
Nations on Friday. She departs for home Saturday evening.
</TEXT>
