<FIRST>r i PM-Khomeini'sSon Bjt   06-07 0886</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Khomeini's Son, Bjt,0919</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khomeini's Son Emerges From Shadows, But Power May Elude Him</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ahmad Khomeini has emerged from the long
shadow of his father and appears to be making a bid for power
himself, a move some analysts believe is doomed to fail.
   He was making his moves even before Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini
died Saturday. But the death of Iran's revolutionary and spiritual
patriarch, before the leadership issue could be settled, has added
urgency to the son's campaign.
   ``A lot of emotions are rampant in Iran now,'' Shahram Chubin, an
Iran specialist with the Graduate Institute of International Studies
in Geneva, said in a telephone interview.
   ``Some people will be trying to take advantage of that and Ahmad
is one of them.''
   The Assembly of Experts, the body formed in 1979 to ensure a
smooth transition after Khomeini's death, on Sunday named President
Ali Khamenei as a caretaker leader until the succession is resolved.
In the meantime, rivals in Tehran are jockeying for power.
   Although Ahmad Khomeini is only a middle-ranking cleric, or
hojatoleslam, and holds no official title, he was one of his
father's closest advisers.
   As Khomeini's private secretary, he controlled access to the
reclusive patriarch and wielded considerable influence behind the
scenes.
   The younger Khomeini, 43, took an increasingly high public
profile as his father's health declined.
   He has allied himself with radical figures in the hierarchy in
the power struggle that has intensified since the Aug. 20 cease-fire
in the war with Iraq.
   Speculation rose that he sought to establish himself as his
father's political heir by engineering the March 28 dismissal of his
father's designated successor, Ayatollah Hussein-Ali Montazeri.
   Ahmad was his father's eyes and ears since their days in exile
and through the Islamic revolution that toppled the late Shah
Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
   Last month, Tehran newspapers published lengthy excerpts of a
110-page memorandum Ahmad wrote to Montazeri, lashing him for
seeking to undermine Khomeini's regime and consorting with
opposition groups.
   The document appeared to be aimed at publicly projecting Ahmad
Khomeini as a candidate to inherit his father's mantle.
   Masoud Rajavi, leader of the Mujahedeen Khalq, or People's Holy
Warriors, the main Iranian opposition movement, says Khomeini was
grooming Ahmad as his successor.
   Rajavi said in a statement that Khomeini's dismissal of Montazeri
for criticizing the regime ``prepared the ground for this
appointment.''
   He argued that Khomeini's appointment of a special committee to
amend the constitution, including downgrading the religious
qualifications of his successor from ``divinely inspired authority''
was aimed at making room for Ahmad.
   But analysts believe the black-bearded Ahmad could eventually
become a political casualty now that his father is dead.
   They believe that bereft of the ayatollah's authority, and with
no secure power base of his own, Ahmad's influence could evaporate.
   ``As Khomeini's health deteriorated, he was able to control his
father's statements and this gave him some authority,'' Chubin said.
   ``But it would be rather difficult for him to be the keeper of
the flame now that Khomeini has gone. Ahmad has neither the
religious credentials nor the administrative experience to rule and
it's not clear whether claiming dynastic credentials will be enough.
   ``He could become a pawn in the power struggle, a front man for
more powerful people following his father's death.''
   Iran specialist Shireen Hunter, of Washington's Center for
Strategic and International Studies, said in a telephone interview:
``I don't think he'll emerge as Iran's strongman.
   ``His power is really quite vicarious, stemming primarily from
his position as his father's gatekeeper. I don't believe he can fill
his father's shoes.'' With 40 days of mourning declared for
Ayatollah Khomeini, Iran has been engulfed by a wave of emotion for
its dead leader, a development Ahmad could exploit to advance his
political ambitions.
   But Ms. Hunter cautioned: ``Using Khomeini's name could be a
double-edged sword. There was already a backlash against Khomeini
and that in the end could work against Ahmad. The revolution is
against dynasties.
   ``He could well become a major player ... but he's not a person
of great convictions and he'll have to associate himself with one
group or another to stay in play.''
   From the outside, the political maneuverings in Tehran are often
opaque. But last August, Ahmad was seen as a member of an unofficial
troika with Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani and Khamenei, both
so-called ``pragmatists,'' who had effectively taken over day-to-day
control as Khomeini's health failed.
   Now he's aligned with the radicals led by Interior Minister Ali
Akbar Mohtashemi, Prosecutor-General Musavi Khoeiniha, Intelligence
Minister Mohammad Rey-Shahri and Mohammad Tavasoli, a powerful
behind-the-scenes figure in Tehran.
   Some analysts believe Ahmad could swing back to Rafsanjani again
if he sees him gaining ground.
   But for now he's lined up against Rafsanjani, who was earlier
outflanked by the radicals in the fundamentalist resurgence decreed
by his father in February.
   Rafsanjani, one of Iran's shrewdest politicians, appears to be
maneuvering his way back and could well come out on top again, as he
has done many times before.
   There is speculation Ahmad will run in presidential elections
scheduled for Aug. 18.
   So far the only announced candidate is the formidable Rafsanjani,
who won the highest ballot in last year's parliamentary elections
with more than 1.3 million votes.
</TEXT>
