<FIRST>r i PM-AIDS Bjt   06-07 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS, Bjt,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Predict More Widespread AIDS Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top U.S. health official says the time is
coming when doctors will report the names of people testing positive
for the AIDS virus and try to trace victims' sexual contacts. But
activists criticized the proposal.
   Dr. James Mason, U.S. Assistant Secretary for Health, said he
didn't know when such a system would be in place, but when it
happens ``we will have normalized HIV and will handle it like
syphilis.''
   HIV, or human immunodeficiency virus, causes AIDS.
   Mason's remarks Tuesday at the Fifth International Conference on
AIDS drew immediate criticism.
   Richard Dunne, executive director of the Gay Men's Health Crisis
in New York, opposed the proposal because he feared names would not
be kept confidential and that people known to be infected would
suffer from the stigma associated with acquired immune deficiency
syndrome.
   ``People lose their jobs, their housing and their schooling
opportunities,'' he said. ``That's not like other diseases.''
   Furthermore, he said, tracing patients' sexual contacts will not
work for AIDS as it does with syphilis because HIV patients may have
been infected for years when they are diagnosed. Tracing partners so
far back is unlikely, he said.
   The consequences of reporting would discourage many people from
submitting to testing, Dunne said. ``The only way people are going
to come forward is if there's something effective'' to help them, he
said.
   The Gay Men's Health Crisis received numerous calls Tuesday from
people who were already concerned that their names might be recorded
if they seek testing. Dr. Stephen Joseph, the New York City health
commissioner, floated a similar proposal at the AIDS meeting Monday.
   Congress has directed the U.S. Public Health Service to prepare a
report on discrimination against people with AIDS and HIV infection,
Mason said, in anticipation of moves toward reporting the names of
those tested.
   He said early identification of infected people through contact
tracing could allow them to be treated promptly with new drugs now
being tested. The cost of such treatment would run into the billions
of dollars, Mason said. He did not know where that money might come
from.
   In other conference reports:
   _ Researchers said initial studies on a new AIDS drug called CD4
showed that the medicine is safe and may reduce levels of HIV in the
body.
   The drug is a decoy intended to confuse the virus and draw it
away from the blood cells it ordinarily infects.
   In expeimental use on 18 people, Dr. Robert Yarchoan of the
National Cancer Institute found that the drug appeared to lower
virus levels in the body by about 50 percent. However, he cautioned
that this could have been a natural fluctuation instead of a result
of the drug.
   Another team found no clear evidence of virus reduction, but
researchers said they were still encouraged by the drug's potential
and said higher doses could have a greater effect.
   _In a report scheduled for presentation today, National Cancer
Institute reserachers said a recently discovered herpes virus may
accelerate the development of AIDS in people infected with HIV.
   Dr. Paulo Lusso said the virus, called HHV-6, enhanced the growth
of HIV in test tube, causing more cells to die more quickly.
   More than half of Americans, Canadians and Europeans have been
exposed to HHV-6 without any ill effects and may be capable of
passing it on, studies have shown.
   _Researchers at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore said it was
now possible to predict two years in advance which patients infected
with HIV will develop AIDS. Studies suggest that a majority of
people infected with the virus get AIDS or related illnesses.
   A similar study by researchers at the University of California,
San Francisco, found that a combination of five laboratory tests can
predict which patients will develop AIDS during a four-year period.
</TEXT>
