<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 0456EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CBSAffiliates     06-07 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CBS Affiliates,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBS Exec: CBS Is Network of 1990s With More Sports, Innovative Programming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Third-place CBS-TV plans to become the network
of the 1990s with more sports coverage and innovative programming,
the president of the CBS broadcast group told affiliates.
   Howard Stringer's comments Tuesday were enthusiastically received
by broadcasters attending the network's annual affiliates meeting.
   The mood was in contrast to the skepticism at last year's
meeting, which followed the network's first-ever third-place finish
in the A.C. Nielsen Co. prime-time ratings behind NBC and ABC.
   Referring to praise for CBS's news coverage of the weekend
massacre in Beijing, Stringer said: ``It gives me great pleasure to
see my old friend Dan Rather become the talk of the town again. When
people ask what Larry Tisch is going to get for $3 billion, this is
an example.'' Tisch is president of CBS.
   The broadcasters also heard from Rather and Connie Chung, who
talked by audio hookup to CBS correspondent Richard Roth in Beijing
and by television satellite to White House Chief of Staff John
Sununu in Washington.
   Sununu defended President Bush's cautious reaction to events in
China. ``We're pushing as hard as we can, but we can't push beyond
the point of constructive interaction,'' he said. ``We do not want
to give anyone cause to feel we are intervening or instigating
bloodshed.''
   Former First lady Nancy Reagan talked briefly following a
discussion on drugs by Rather, Chung and Robert Stutman, head of the
Drug Enforcement Administration in New York. Stutman said the only
effective way to fight drugs was a three-pronged assault of law
enforcement, treatment and education.
   ``I hear people blame other countries for our drug problem,''
Mrs. Reagan said, ``but the United States alone is responsible for
its drug problem. It's an illusion to think we can stop drugs by
sending troops to foreign countries when we can't even stop drug
sales in our own neighborhoods.''
   Stringer compared the battles between the three commercial
networks and cable television as Gulliver being chained down by the
tiny Lilliputians in Jonathan Swift's satire ``Gulliver's Travels.''
   ``I look on cable as the media's one-armed bandit. Viewers only
win when it comes up three bars, CBS, ABC and NBC. We spent $4
billion in Hollywood and they take our programs and charge people
money to watch.''
   The networks have long fought the cable industry's ability to use
network programming without paying a fee. Stringer also referred to
network efforts to overturn regulations by the Federal
Communications Commission prohibiting networks from participating in
the syndication market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
