<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 0205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Foley-Analysis Bjt   06-07 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Foley-Analysis, Bjt,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Political Blood Lust Still in Evidence on Republican Right</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the House Republican leader warned his GOP
colleagues against a French Revolution mentality in which ``evil
Democrats'' are hauled to the guillotine, some began humming the
French national anthem.
   The incident at a party meeting Tuesday illustrates the political
blood lust that persists in a chamber fractured by months of ethics
charges and countercharges, and the uphill fight new House Speaker
Thomas Foley will have in trying to restore order.
   ``The task I see for myself is to create the environment where
... debate can take place without recriminations, without the kind
of angry, hostile feelings between members'' that have dominated the
House of late, Foley told reporters.
   ``This tension which has built up over a period of many months is
going to require a little time to turn around,'' he said. ``It's not
going to be done in a day. ... But I believe it will happen.''
   Some Democrats, stung by the sacrifice of former speaker Jim
Wright in the ethics storm, have turned their sights on Rep. Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., who filed the original ethics charges against
Wright. An ethics investigation of Gingrich's book-promotion deal
could begin as early as Thursday.
   Of the ethics committee and Gingrich, Rep. Louise Slaughter,
D-N.Y., said: ``I want them to treat him fairly, but I certainly
want them to treat him.''
   The political knives remained out in the Republican camp, as
well. GOP political operatives were searching financial disclosure
reports for possible ethical shortcomings of Democrats, and Gingrich
spoke of new ethics cases yet to be filed against members of the
majority party.
   Minority Leader Robert Michel of Illinois, who warned his
colleagues against a frenzy of political executions, blamed the
atmosphere on ``35 years of uninterrupted power'' for Democrats and
said ethics abuses won't be forgotten.
   ``I am all for putting an end to bitterness,'' Michel said. ``I
am all in favor of putting our House in order, but we won't do so by
sweeping things under the rug.''
   In an acceptance speech to the House, Foley directed many of his
comments at the Republican side, promising increased consultation
and appealing to shared values of trust and public service.
   The calming style was in sharp contrast to that of Wright. Where
Wright confronted, Foley counsels; where Wright followed his own
compass, Foley seeks advice.
   Republicans will now be looking for that style to be translated
into changes that will benefit them. Foley may be able to buy some
peace by permitting more Republican amendments to be offered to
bills on the House floor, or by bringing legislation before the
House under less restrictive rules.
   ``If he does, I'll be totally and cheerfully bipartisan,'' said
Gingrich, the GOP's chief gadfly.
   But he doubted that Foley would be able to give the Republicans
much latitude on issues they want most, such as a balanced budget
amendment to the Constitution and the death penalty for drug and
other offenses. ``Those are anathema to the left wing of the
Democratic Party,'' he said.
   While he appealed for cooperation, Foley did not seek to hide his
own ideology. He openly acknowledged at a news conference that he is
a liberal, the label that Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis sought vainly to avoid last year.
   And he clearly reserved the sole right to set the House's agenda,
the prerogative of the majority.
   ``Procedurally, Tom will try to work with the Republicans to be
fair,'' said Budget Committee Chairman Leon Panetta, D-Calif. ``I
think the difference will be he will be a fighter on issues the
Democrats stand for.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Jim Drinkard covers Congress for The Associated
Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
