<FIRST>r w PM-RichcoSubsidies Bjt   06-07 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Richco Subsidies, Bjt,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Questions Raised About Company's Subsidies, Ties to Fugitive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department is reviewing a grain
company's possible links to a fugitive commodities trader in
Switzerland and its receipt of at least $65 million in government
export subsidies.
   At issue are the company's ties to Marc Rich, who fled to
Switzerland in 1983 before his indictment for criminal tax evasion,
racketeering, mail and wire fraud.
   A department official confirmed Tuesday that USDA was examining
Richco Grain Ltd., a Swiss-based company with an office in Stamford,
Conn., and payments it received through the Export Enhancement
Program, known as EEP.
   The review was started at the request of the chairman of a House
Agriculture subcommittee, Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., who raised
questions about the company at a hearing earlier this year and on
Tuesday asked the agency for a full investigation.
   Glickman, in a letter to the agency, said ``an unmistakable line
of ownership, control and profit runs from'' Richco Grain to Rich
through a series of subsidiary arrangements.
   ``While I am disturbed that a company whose main operations lie
outside of the United States can establish but a nominal onshore
presence and qualify to receive EEP bonuses, as appears to be the
case with Richco Grain, I am truly shocked that a fugitive from U.S.
justice can benefit from a program funded by taxpayer dollars,''
Glickman said in his letter to Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter.
   Under the Export Enhancement Program, private exporters can sell
U.S. commodities at lower prices to meet foreign competition and
then collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities
as bonuses, or subsidies.
   Richard Crowder, under secretary for international affairs and
commodity programs, said USDA had started ``checking through what
the connections are'' between Richco and Rich. He declined to
provide any details on the findings so far.
   An official of Richco, Al Church, declined to comment about the
USDA review and would not provide any information about the company.
   Glickman asked that USDA's Office of Inspector General determine
whether Richco qualified for the export subsidy program and whether
department eligibility guidelines need to be changed to close any
possible loopholes used by Richco.
   Richco has the same telephone number as Clarendon AG, a U.S.
subsidiary of Marc Rich &amp; Co. A.G. of Switzerland. Clarendon and the
Marc Rich company settled a federal tax evasion case in 1984 by
pleading guilty and agreeing to pay more than $200 million in back
taxes, fines and other penalties.
   Criminal charges against Rich were unaffected by the settlement.
The government alleged that Rich and his commodity-trading empire
cheated the government out of millions of dollars in taxes through a
series of illegal oil transactions among Rich-controlled companies.
   Richco has received at least $65 million worth of subsidies
through EEP, ranking it ninth among grain exporters in the program,
according to information supplied to a House committee by USDA. Most
recently, Richco picked up estimated subsidies of $250,000 for a
wheat sale to the Soviet Union.
   Last month, President Bush approved use of the subsidy program
for the sale of 1.5 million tons of wheat to the Soviets. Richco
handled at least 30,000 tons of the initial part of the wheat deal.
Subsidies averaged $8.46 per ton for Richco and four other
companies, according to USDA.
   Glickman, who met Tuesday with Yeutter and Crowder, said Congress
might need to pass legislation disqualifying Richco from the export
program unless USDA administratively barred it from receiving more
subsidies.
   ``The export enhancement program has undergone some criticism
anyway. It would be a shame to jeopardize its future because we're
providing bonus commodities to a tax fugitive,'' said Glickman.
``This is a guy of renowned international bad dealings.''
</TEXT>
