<FIRST>r w PM-AssaultWeapons     06-07 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Assault Weapons,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRA Tries to Counter Police Endorsements of Gun Bans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While several police organizations are urging
Congress to approve strict controls on semiautomatic assault-style
weapons, some 225 officers gathered on Capitol Hill to say those
groups don't speak for them.
   ``The average policeman in America right now is extremely upset
with the misrepresentations,'' said Patrolman Thomas J. Aveni Jr.,
who asked that his department be identified only as being in Camden
County, N.J.
   The notion that policemen favor ``gun bans as a solution to
violent crime'' is wrong, said Aveni, who recently organized a group
called Law Enforcement for the Preservation of the Second Amendment,
which guarantees the right to keep and bear arms.
   ``The majority of us have taken an oath to uphold the
Constitution,'' he said in an interview. ``The Second Amendment's
the cornerstone of the Constitution. If the Second Amendment goes,
there's no guarantee that the rest of the Constitution will remain
intact. ... Without arms, people are powerless to dissent against
any kind of tyranny or repression of government.''
   Aveni was one of the 225 officers flown to Washington by the
National Rifle Association to participate in a news conference
Tuesday and lobby their respective congressmen and senators. The
only state not represented by an officer was Hawaii.
   They were here to combat the impact of gun-control endorsements
by law enforcement officials such as Los Angeles Police Chief Daryl
Gates and Baltimore County Police Chief Neil Behan, who are pushing
for controls on assault-style weapons including semiautomatic
versions of the AK-47 and Uzi.
   Law enforcement groups that have taken similar stands include the
National Fraternal Order of Police, the International Association of
Chiefs of Police, the National Sheriff's Association, the National
Association of Police Organizations and the Police Executive
Research Forum.
   ``For thousands of us out there that the chiefs, the appointed
officials, do not speak for the law enforcement officers that are in
the field, in the trenches, doing the job,'' said Patrolman Ray
Maples, president of the Memphis Police Association.
   But Stephen Brown, counsel to the National Fraternal Order of
Police, countered that his organization speaks for 200,000 of those
officers, not for their bosses.
   ``The Fraternal Order of Police does speak for the cop on the
street,'' Brown said. ``There are no chiefs, there are no sheriffs.
They don't speak for anyone except for the cops on the beat.''
   The contention by some law enforcement leaders that their
officers are being ``outgunned'' by criminals wielding assault-style
weapons ``offends me,'' Officer Leroy Pyle of the San Jose, Calif.,
Police Department said at the news conference.
   Santa Monica, Calif., Officer Gary Steiner said criminals have
better firearms because they're making more money these days.
   ``Unfortunately, police departments have for many years been
forced to look at the bottom line in terms of low bid, and that
applies to our safety equipment in particular,'' Steiner said.
   Cincinnati Police Lt. Harry Thomas said many of the officers
attending were ``under direct orders from their police chiefs to
disassociate themselves from their respective police departments''
in their comments.
   ``The remarks that are made here should not be construed as the
official policy of our respective police departments,'' he said.
</TEXT>
