<FIRST>r w PM-AirlineReport     06-07 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airline Report,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transportation Department Reports Improved Airline Performance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major airlines in April flew more on-time
flights, lost less baggage and received fewer complaints, according
to the Transportation Department's monthly consumer report.
   Airlines reported the highest on-time rate in six months _ 83.4
percent, an 11 percent improvement over the previous month. Delays
due to mechanical problems were not counted in the report released
Tuesday.
   Passengers filed reports of lost baggage in April at the rate of
6.15 for every 1,000 passengers, compared with 7.53 in March. This
also was the lowest total in six months.
   Complaints against individual airlines continued a long downward
trend, with 876 filed with the government in May, down from 933 in
April. The May figure was 53 percent below the 1,859 complaints
received in May 1988.
   The department maintains a file of consumer information for more
than 20,000 flights. Airlines and travel agents have access to
performance data for specific flights.
</TEXT>
