<FIRST>r w PM-House-Color     06-07 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-House-Color,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Folks in `The People's House' Go Ceremonial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House loves to call itself ``The People's
House'' and its members like to act like folks.
   On high state occasions, like Tuesday's, when the House installed
a new speaker, it has to go ceremonial but it couldn't quite shed
its old-shoe habits.
   When Thomas S. Foley had been duly elected, the doorkeeper
bellowed out, just as he does on State of the Union night, ``Mister
Speaker!,'' introducing new Speaker Thomas S. Foley to departing
Speaker Jim Wright.
   And Foley marched the route of presidents: down the central
aisle, accompanied by an escorting committee, shaking hands all
round.
   But still, the House is the House. So some members brought their
children to work, to be there for the history of it all, and plunked
them on the plush brown leather seats. Six of the kids sat in one
row.
   One tried to figure out how his white sailor hat could be made to
fit his knee. Another tried out his sunglasses against the bright
lights. When the adults stood and applauded, so did the kids.
   To old timers in the galleries, the moment brought to mind
another occasion when a popular product of the House stood before
the chamber at the climax of a tense national drama.
   That was 1974, when Gerald R. Ford, the former House Republican
leader, arrived as president, having succeeded Richard Nixon, a
chief executive who resigned in disgrace, largely due to the House's
own impeachment process.
   ``Mister Speaker!'' the doorkeeper bellowed then, too, but Ford
showed the members that he was still a man of the House with a corny
line; he was, he said, the same old guy: ``I am a Ford, not a
Lincoln.''
   The ethical troubles which compelled Jim Wright to resign as
speaker were no Watergate, but within the House, an insular body,
the trauma was almost comparable.
   Foley had no catchy line like Ford's but he called up some
numbers to deal with something Ronald Reagan and others had been
saying about the House _ that it has become a self-perpetuating body.
   Reagan, just before leaving office, noted that 98 percent of
House members who ran for re-election won and concluded it was
easier to be re-elected to the House than to the Supreme Soviet.
   Foley's answer: ``Only 7 percent of the House's current members
were in the House when I was first elected in 1964. Eight-one
percent of the current members have been elected since 1974. More
than half of the current members _ 55 percent _ have been elected
since 1980. The constant change in membership is a source of great
strength for the House, but fundamentally, and more importantly, the
House reflects the will of the electorate.''
   Foley had another comparison. He contrasted the transfer of power
here with the awkward reaching toward democratic formulas in Moscow
and Warsaw and the bloody events in Beijing. He said congressmen can
be proud that the values which have sustained the House ``now sweep
around the world.''
   ``We are,'' he said, using that phrase again, ``proud to call
this the People's House, the fundamental institution of American
democracy.''
</TEXT>
