<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 0507EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-UN-Sudan     06-07 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Sudan,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Optimistic Sudanese Relief Supplies to Arrive in June</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. officials in charge of Sudan's famine
relief operation say an agreement between rebels and the government
to allow safe transit of emergency supplies could help save up to
100,000 Sudanese lives.
   The delivery of food and other supplies _ before the rainy season
cuts off access by dirt roads and airstrips _ is behind schedule but
recent accords between guerrillas and the government improve the
survival prospects for thousands, James P. Grant, head of Operation
Lifeline Sudan, said Tuesday.
   ``It's going to be a very difficult summer and fall, but I think
at this stage, barring a collapse of the present sort of pattern of
cooperation, I think we can say that the great majority of those
100,000 deaths that looked so likely in February and early March can
be averted,'' the U.N. official said.
   More than 60,000 tons of food has already been delivered, and the
relief operation is attempting to deliver another 20,000 to 40,000
tons before the heaviest rains hit in July and August, Grant said.
   ``For the first time in history, there is, in the middle of a
civil war, a plan of action agreed to by both parties with
`corridors of tranquility' for the passage of supplies,'' said
Grant, who returned from observing the operation last week.
   The rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) is fighting for
more autonomy in the southern provinces, where the government
generally controls only garrison towns.
   A railway route from central to southern Sudan is now open, said
Grant. One rail trip was completed in late May; another is set to
begin Saturday, and two more runs are planned later this month.
   The first train, with over 100 cars, moved south through rebel
and government-held areas, reaching war-weary Aweil on May 28.
   ``At one government garrison where the train stopped overnight,
the train was so long that the SPLA was guarding the tail end of the
train while the government was guarding the front of the train,''
Grant said.
   The government and rebels have both agreed to respect the
``corridors of tranquility'' as long as necessary, said Grant.
   In addition, both parties have agreed to meet in Addis Ababa,
Ethiopia, on Saturday to open talks aimed at reaching a
comprehensive truce.
   The SPLA has also announced it is extending its monthlong
unilateral cease-fire for another two weeks, said Grant.
   Although the rainy season has already begun, Operation Lifeline
Sudan has not yet lost the use of all dirt roads and airstrips, he
said.
   Bulldozers have been able to keep open dirt roads linking Kenya
with southern Sudan so truck convoys can pass, and the relief
operation has been able to use lighter planes to land on rain-sodden
dirt airstrips.
   However, a barge convoy planned for the Blue Nile between Kosti
and Malakal has not yet been able to start, said Grant. Negotiations
with the government, unions and barge crews are still under way.
   Despite that setback and other delays, Grant said he was ``more
optimistic for the prospects for success than at any time in the
past.''
   The United Nations estimates 250,000 Sudanese died last year from
starvation due to flood or drought, or war-induced famine.
</TEXT>
