<FIRST>r w PM-ThirdWorldDebt     06-07 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Third World Debt,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third World Falling Behind on $70 Billion Owed US Banks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal auditing agency says Third World
countries are falling behind on $70 billion in debt repayments to
U.S. banks and that American regulators should make banks put up
more reserves to protect depositors against loan losses.
   The report by the General Accounting Office, the auditing arm of
Congress, did not name the debtor countries.
   Argentina, the third largest debtor behind Brazil and Mexico, has
paid no interest on its foreign debt for more than one year and owes
U.S. banks more than $8.5 billion.
   The GAO said regulators should demand that banks put up about 12
times more reserves against loan losses than is currently required.
   ``Because banks generally respond to reserve requirements by
writing down assets by the required amounts, a decline in the book
value of their assets results,'' the GAO said in a note on figures
it sent to Rep. John J. LaFalce, D-N.Y., a member of the House
Banking Committee.
   Though the auditors' report did not say so, writing down a bank's
assets reduces the amount of business it can do and makes the
management look bad to depositors and stockholders.
   A bank is now only required to put up reserves when the
regulators declare foreign loans it has made to be either a total
loss or ``value-impaired.'' That means the debtors have not paid
interest for six months or have shown in other ways that they are in
deep trouble. Bank regulators next week are expected to discuss
behind closed doors whether to put loans to Argentina in the
``value-impaired'' pigeonhole.
   The list already contains Poland, Bolivia, Peru, Zaire, Sudan,
Nicaragua and Liberia. But their total debt is small compared with
the major debtors.
   In a letter Tuesday to Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal
Reserve Board, LaFalce joined in urging that the banks put up more
reserves. The Federal Reserve takes the lead in the U.S. regulation
process.
   ``U.S. banks maintain lower reserve levels than almost all other
industrialized countries,'' LaFalce wrote.
</TEXT>
