<FIRST>r w PM-SeawolfWarning     06-07 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seawolf Warning,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sub Designer Cites Risk of Construction Delay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A key contractor helping to design the Navy's
Seawolf nuclear attack submarine says development snags could delay
completion of the first vessel.
   The warning, issued last December by the Newport News, Va.,
Shipbuilding &amp; Drydock Co. to the Naval Sea Systems Command,
complained of a lack of progress by the Navy and another contractor,
General Electric Co., in developing the combat system of sensors and
computers needed to operate the new sub's weaponry.
   Newport News Shipbuilding said the delays could mean the Navy may
not get the first completed sub in May 1995 as planned.
   ``Continuing delays in completion of the (combat system) design
or the emergence of significant changes in the design could
seriously impact the lead ship design schedule,'' the company said.
   The Seawolf, or SSN-21, is described by the Navy as the key to
rebuilding the U.S. edge in underwater warfare _ an advantage that
has eroded over the past decade because of espionage scandals and
Soviet efforts to build quieter submarines of their own.
   The report from Newport News Shipbuilding was disclosed Tuesday
by Rep. John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., in a letter to Defense Secretary
Dick Cheney voicing ``strong concern about a high-risk acquisition
strategy being pursued by the Navy in the procurement of the $50
billion-plus SSN-21 Seawolf submarine program.''
   Newport News Shipbuilding holds the contract for designing the
Seawolf's hull and interior layout. The company concluded in its
December report that it could not keep the project on schedule
unless ``the combat system design development (is) brought in line
with the ship design development.''
   ``In essence, the ship design and the combat system design (have
become) out of phase by over a year,'' Newport News said.
   Conyers asked Cheney to review the program and give his view of
whether all operational tests should be completed on the first sub
before a full-scale production go-ahead is given.
   Each Seawolf is now expected to cost more than $1.5 billion.
   ``My concern about this matter has been reinforced by a copy of a
letter which has recently come to my attention indicating strong
concern about the design of the AN-BSY-2 fire control system ...,''
Conyers wrote.
   The congressman said would like the defense secretary to tell him
``when and how will you know whether the problems raised in the
Newport News Naval Shipyard letter will affect the planned delivery
date of the first SSN-21?''
   The Navy on Tuesday declined to discuss the substance of the
Newport News report, saying ``it would not be appropriate to comment
on what will become the substance of a reply'' to Conyers.
   The Navy did say, however, it was confident the combat system
would be delivered on time for the lead Seawolf sub.
   The SSN-21, like the current 688- or Los Angeles-class attack
sub, will be designed primarily to hunt and kill Soviet submarines.
It is supposed to feature greater speed, better sensors and
longer-range weapons than the 688 class.
   The Navy maintains the Seawolf ``is going to represent a major
advance in speed, depth, quieting, weapons capability and
supportability.''
</TEXT>
