<FIRST>r w PM-Anderson-Gun     06-07 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Anderson-Gun,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Investigating Columnist for Taking Gun to Capitol</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Anderson, the syndicated columnist, is
being investigated for carrying an unloaded gun into the U.S.
Capitol to demonstrate security lapses, congressional authorities
said.
   Anderson displayed the handgun, and a bullet, on May 24 when he
interviewed Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole in the Capitol for a
television special on terrorism, said Dole spokesman Walt Riker.
   Riker said Anderson claimed to have walked through a metal
detector with the 9mm Austrian-made pistol on his way to Dole's
office. He pulled out the gun and handed it to the Kansas Republican
after Dole said in the interview that no place was immune from
terrorists.
   ``We realized afterward that we'd been had, that it was an
on-camera stunt. ... We were taken aback, but as we thought about
it, we realized he may have committed a crime,'' said Riker.
   Dole's aides turned the bullet, which Anderson left behind, over
to Senate Sergeant at Arms Henry Giugni. Giugni said Tuesday that
the bullet and statements about the incident had been turned over to
U.S. Capitol Police and officers from that force were investigating
the incident along with the U.S. attorney's office.
   Anderson the following week broadast tape of the interview and
footage of him walking through a Capitol metal detector.
   A Capitol Police duty officer said no spokesman was available to
discuss the investigation Tuesday night. There was no answer at
Anderson's home.
   In an interview broadcast Tuesday on Washington's WUSA-TV,
Anderson was asked how he would react if he were charged with a
criminal offense.
   ``I would say that the authorities in Washington as usual are
going after the whistleblower rather than the offense,'' he said.
   Riker said the news media in general could be hurt by the
incident.
   ``The ironic thing is, Anderson through this stunt has hurt the
media people who have to go through those entrances every day,'' he
said. ``The legacy of this is the media are going to have a harder
time.''
   Giugni said screening has been tightened up at the building.
   ``Naturally they're looking more carefully at press passes and
such. We normally give a certain courtesy to reporters trying to get
through,'' he said.
</TEXT>
