<FIRST>u a AM-TurbulentFlight 1stLd-Writethru a0812 06-07 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turbulent Flight, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0812,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Turbulence Injures About 30 on United Jet</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf, `The flight ...,' to UPDATE
with passenger comment, flight picked up Americans fleeing Beijing; picks
up 5th graf, `Figures on ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air turbulence bounced a United Airlines jumbo jet
at 37,000 feet Tuesday, injuring about 30 passengers bound for
Chicago, officials said.
   United Flight 90, a non-stop flight from Los Angeles carrying 232
passengers and 11 crew members, landed at O'Hare International
Airport around 7 p.m. without further incident, said airline
spokesman Joe Hopkins.
   ``We've been told the plane was over Garden City, Kan., when it
encountered clear-air turbulence ... which means the pilot couldn't
see it,'' Hopkins said.
   ``The flight attendants said it lasted less than a minute, but
apparently the turbulence was pretty severe,'' he added.
`Fortunately, the seat-belt light was on at the time.''
   ``It was like being in one of those roller coasters,'' said
passenger Loretta Pasquesi.
   United Flight 90 originated in Manila, Philippines, and in Tokyo
picked up a handful of American tourists fleeing the unrest in
Beijing before continuing to Los Angeles and Chicago, said airline
spokesman Rob Doughty. It was not known if any of those travelers
were among the injured.
   Figures on the number injured varied. Officials at hospitals said
20 victims were brought in, but the Federal Aviation Administration
put the number at 35.
   Ten people were removed from the DC-10 on stretchers, said Fire
Department spokesman Stanley Span.
   Seven of the injured taken to Resurrection Hospital were treated
for head and neck injuries, but none appeared serious, said
spokeswoman Sister Bonaventure.
   ``Most are bumped and bruised,'' she said. ``It appears people
who weren't wearing belts may have hit the ceiling.''
   Other hospitals apparently were not expecting any serious
injuries, said another spokeswoman, Janice Youngwith.
</TEXT>
