<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 0518EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ContraceptionPills     06-07 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contraception Pills,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Research: Risk From Pill Low for Relatives of Breast Cancer Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Birth control pills pose no increased breast
cancer risk even for women with a family member who developed the
disease.
   That's the finding of a new study of oral contraceptive use among
women who have a family history of breast cancer, one of the major
concerns in the medical community about long-term use of th pill.
   ``These data suggest you don't need to be nearly as concerned as
some people thought previously if you have a very strong family
history (of breast cancer),'' said Dr. Bruce V. Stadel, co-author of
the study and a researcher at the Uniformed Services University of
the Health Sciences in Bethesda, Md.
   Stadel said that women whose mothers, sisters, daughters, aunts,
or grandmothers had breast cancer are known to be at higher risk of
developing the disease. As a result, doctors for years have
recommended that women with such a family history not take birth
control pills. The perception, he said, was that oral contraceptives
would aggravate an existing risk.
   But the new study relieves this concern, said Stadel, and shows
``oral contraceptive use does not appreciably alter risk of breast
cancer as far as we have been able to study.''
   The research, published in the journal of the American College of
Obstetricians and Gynecologists, involved an analysis of data
collected from eight areas of the country by two federal agencies
for what is called the Cancer and Steroid Hormone Study, or CASH.
   The CASH research examined the medical histories of 4,730 women
with cancer and 4,646 who did not have cancer. From these groups,
the new study analyzed the relative risk of breast cancer among oral
contraceptives users who had a family history of breast cancer in
comparison with those pill takers who had no family history of
breast cancer. The length of time that oral contraceptives were used
also was analyzed.
   ``We looked to see if there was a different effect for women with
a strong family history compared to women with no family history,''
said Stadel. ``We found no adverse effect (from the pill). Our data
suggests that oral contraceptive use does not increase the risk of
breast cancer in women with a family history.''
   Though the research seemed to give definite results, Stadel said
there is a need for confirming studies.
   ``This is the largest study of this issue, but it is one study,''
he said ``In this sort of research, we always like to see the
building over time of a consensus based on more and more data. But
this is certainly a strong piece in that direction.''
   Steven G. Silverberg of the Georgetown University Medical Center,
a medical school professor who has researched any connection between
birth control pills and cancer, said the findings confirm a
continuing sense of confidence in the safety of oral contraceptives.
   ``This is not unexpected,'' he said. ``I would have expected oral
contraceptives to not be associated with increased risks, even for
women with a family history of breast cancer. The birth control
pills now being prescribed shouldn't pose a high risk of breast
cancer at all.''
   Other co-authors of the study were Pamela P. Murray and James J.
Schlesselman of the Uniformed Services University of the Health
Sciences in Bethesda.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
