<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 0520EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls     06-07 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rules Panel Says Only a Few Bailout Bill Amendments to be Considered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the House Rules Committee are
telling colleagues the panel is unlikely to permit the full House to
consider more than a few of the 100-plus proposed amendments to
savings and loan bailout legislation.
   However, it is clear from panel members' comments that the
committee will clear at least one or perhaps a combination of
several of the 10 proposed amendments that would blunt the tougher
capital requirements that the Bush administration says is the
cornerstone of its plan to reform the industry.
   ``There seems to be great sympathy throughout the Congress to do
something with this'' capital rule, said Rep. Gerald Solomon, R-N.Y.
   The committee, which decides the rules for debate of legislation
in the full House, heard in a 4{-hour session Tuesday from 12 House
members seeking to reshape parts of the S&amp;L bill written in the
Banking, Ways and Means and Judiciary committees.
   Forty-seven members remain on the witness list and the Rules
panel scheduled another session this afternoon and may have to hold
a third on Thursday.
   Panel members conceded that the flood of amendments means there's
little hope of meeting House Speaker Thomas Foley's request to move
the bill to the full House this week. They predicted House action
next week.
   That would set the stage for a conference to reconcile the House
bill with a version passed by the Senate in April and send finished
legislation to President Bush's desk in July.
   Bush administration officials are insisting that the House
require all S&amp;L owners to risk more of their own capital _ $3 for
every $100 in lending _ as a buffer against losses to the government
deposit insurance fund.
   However, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and others are arguing that 732
of the nation's 2,949 S&amp;Ls should keep an accounting break known as
``supervisory goodwill,'' which in some cases allows S&amp;L owners to
operate without risking any of their own money.
   According to Hyde, 241 of the 732 will fail to meet the new
capital requirements unless they keep the goodwill, which regulators
permitted in the early 1980s as an inducement for merging with
failing S&amp;Ls.
   Hyde wants S&amp;Ls to have the right to appeal to regulators to keep
their supervisory goodwill, but critics say that could delay the
imposition of tougher standards for as long as 18 months.
   Reps. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill., chairman of the House Banking
subcommittee on financial institutions; John LaFalce, D-N.Y., a
member of the banking panel, and two members of the Rules committee,
Rep. James H. Quillen, R-Tenn., and Solomon, are proposing other
accommodations on goodwill, arguing that it's unfair for the
government to renege on previous commitments.
   ``I think it's really a bad day in the history of this country
when we as legislators agree to do away with written agreements the
government has made,'' Quillen said.
   However, Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, pleaded with the Rules Committee
to permit consideration of at least one amendment to strengthen
capital requirements even further from the 3 percent standard
favored by the administration. Leach wants S&amp;L owners to hold 4
percent tangible capital within two years and five percent after
five years.
   In addition to the capital standards, the Rules panel was
expected to approve floor consideration of an amendment by the Ways
and Means Committee to add $50 billion in government borrowing for
the bailout to the federal budget deficit. The administration favors
a mechanism for keeping it out of the budget deficit.
</TEXT>
