<FIRST>r w PM-SpendingBill     06-07 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spending Bill,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Tidying Up Bill With Money for Veterans, Pet Projects</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Debate resumes at noon EDT; top planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate is trying to finish crafting a bill
funneling $3.3 billion to veterans, college students and other
groups, with some lawmakers hoping to use the measure to block a
surtax on the elderly.
   Legislators planned their fourth day of debate on the legislation
today, hoping to complete work on a bill that has garnered a slew of
provisions on Capitol Hill since President Bush first sought the
measure in March.
   Discussion was continuing today on an amendment by Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., postponing implementation of much of the new
catastrophic care program for the elderly under Medicare, including
a cap on doctors' bills.
   McCain's proposal also would delay for a year the surtax on
people 65 or older that is designed to pay for the program. That
levy can reach a maximum of $800 this year for the wealthiest senior
citizens, and some of them have complained that the tax is excessive.
   ``We're laying an incredible cost on them for coverage they do
not want or need at that cost,'' McCain said.
   But opposition to McCain came even from his own political party.
   ``I think I know where the crux of the problem comes from ... ,''
said Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., ranking Republican on the Senate
Finance Committee. ``They all live in Sun City, and they all have
incomes of $30,000 to $40,000 a year.''
   Sun City is a retirement community in Arizona.
   Democrats said the size of the surtax should be reconsidered
instead in future legislation.
   On Wednesday, the Senate rejected 69-29 a proposal by Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., allowing the Transportation Department to withhold
aid from communities refusing to let transit projects to companies
doing business with the pro-apartheid government of South Africa.
   Lawmakers also adopted by voice vote an amendment by Senate
Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, urging Congress to revamp
a tax law that business considers burdensome.
   That followed a 50-49 defeat for Sen. Robert Kasten, R-Wis., who
instead wanted the Senate to repeal the tax law, which forces
companies to prove their health benefits are as generous to low-paid
workers as they are to executives. For technical reasons, Kasten
would have needed 60 votes to prevail.
   The overall spending bill is designed to provide federal agencies
with enough money to see them through the Sept. 30 end of fiscal
1989.
   It would pump $1.2 billion to veterans programs, $892 million for
Guaranteed Student Loans for college students, and $225 million for
food stamps. It would finance other costs including those for Soviet
refugees moving to this country, last year's forest fires, foster
care, and United Nations peacekeeping efforts.
   The measure also is studded with provisions directing federal
resources at projects important to individual lawmakers.
   Thus, it would prevent a school district in Sumter County, S.C.,
from losing about $700,000 in federal education aid this year it
would otherwise forfeit. The provision was sponsored by Sen. Ernest
Hollings, D-S.C., a member of the Appropriations Committee.
   Other clauses would order the Army to spend $50 million this year
on cold weather clothes manufactured in 10 states; provide Puerto
Rican political parties with $1.5 million to conduct a referendum on
the island's future political status; and distribute $6.6 million in
subsidies to airlines that serve small communities in 39 states.
   The House passed a $3.7 billion version of the bill on May 24,
two months after Bush sought legislation totaling $2.2 billion.
   The two chambers will have to agree to a compromise before
sending a bill to the White House for Bush's signature.
</TEXT>
