<FIRST>u p AM-FremontChild-Care 2ndLd-Writethru a0427 06-07 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fremont Child-Care, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0427,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cities Nationwide Look To Fremont Child-Care Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE vote.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-NJ Governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landmark measure to create a direct tax
on households and businesses to support child care was failing in
early returns Tuesday as cities and child-care advocates nationwide
watched.
   With 27 of 84 precincts reporting, the vote was 3,218 against the
measure to 858 for.
   The measure, which faced an uphill battle to win passage by a
two-thirds majority, would raise $1.8 million a year from residents,
businesses, developers and the city's own coffers to open care
centers at 30 elementary schools.
   The program in this city of 165,000 on the east side of San
Francisco Bay also would help sick kids and subsidize poor parents
for baby-sitting costs.
   ``Cities around the country are looking to the Fremont example to
see whether taxpayers are willing to pay for child care,'' said John
Kyle, director of the Children and Families and Cities Project of
the National League of Cities in Washington.
   ``People in 80 percent of all cities are saying child care is the
most pressing need for children from birth to 9 years old,'' he
said. ``Cities are looking for ways to handle that need, and
resources are the biggest barrier to providing good services.''
   About 100 cities offer some kind of support for child care, Kyle
said. Some simply coordinate programs or offer training; others
spend money through general funds, federal community block grants or
developer fees.
   ``Fremont's measure is the only example I know about of a
dedicated tax for any services having to do with children,'' Kyle
said. ``This is on the forefront of things to come in the future.''
   The measure would impose a $12 annual tax on every homeowner,
with renters exempt, and a 20 percent business tax surcharge. It
would expire in 15 years.
   The vote in Fremont will indicate ``how deep public support is
for child care,'' said Abby Cohen, managing attorney for the Child
Care Law Center in San Francisco.
   ``We all have magnifying glasses and we're watching it very
carefully,'' said Deborah Simon, coordinator of San Jose's office on
child care.
   The National League of Cities, which has 1,400 member cities and
49 state and municipal members representing an additional 14,000
cities, said many cities are watching closely.
   ``Advocacy groups see Fremont as an example of what can be done
to deal with a need that is felt in all cities,'' Kyle said. ``It's
not just something for the rich or poor. Lots of people need it.
This measure will make city governments think about this problem.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
