<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Marcos out of surgery, statement
from spokesman; picks up 4th graf, `Marcos, 71 ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Marcos Rushed Into Emergency Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos
underwent emergency surgery Tuesday, but hospital officials declined
to give any immediate details.
   Marcos, who has been listed in very critical condition since May
18, underwent 3{ hours of surgery at St. Francis Medical Center
beginning at 3:30 p.m., said Gemmo Trinidad, a family spokesman.
   ``He's very much alive,'' Trinidad said, ``They didn't tell us
yet what the surgery was for.''
   Hospital spokeswoman Norma Kop said a statement on the operation
would be released soon.
   Marcos, 71, has been suffering from a variety of serious
ailments, including kidney and heart failure, pneumonia and
bacterial infections. He has been unable to breathe on his own and
has been undergoing constant kidney dialysis.
   Marcos, who has lived here since his ouster in a popular revolt
in February 1986, has been hospitalized since Jan. 15.
   On May 23, his doctors said it was a miracle he was still alive.
   ``I think if you asked any one of us, we'd all say he has a low
probability of long-term surivival,'' transplant surgeon Dr.
Livingston Wong said then.
   Although the prognosis for Marcos remained poor at the time,
doctors would not rule out the possibility of recovery.
   The former leader's illness has prevented him from traveling to
New York to face racketeering charges alleging he plundered his
homeland of more than $100 million and used the money to buy real
estate and art in the United States.
   His wife, Imelda, who also is charged, last month appealed to
Philippine President Corazon Aquino to allow her husband to die in
his homeland. The request was denied.
</TEXT>
