<HEAD>New England Governors Duo Back Bipartisan Federal Housing Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Compromise federal housing legislation that
Senate authors hope will promote participation of developers,
community groups and local officials in the creation of new
affordable homes has won the backing of two Northeast governors.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis said Tuesday the $4.1
billion bipartisan measure ``has all the pieces we need to address
the housing needs of our country.''
   ``It reaches out to the states and local communities. It
recognizes that there is a strong and eager network of people in the
housing community ready and anxious to work with you and the new
administration,'' the Democratic governor told the Senate Banking
subcommittee on housing and urban affairs.
   Rhode Island Gov. Edward D. DiPrete, a Republican representing
the National Governors' Association, also endorsed the measure by
Sens. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., and Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., to
create affordable housing.
   The Cranston-D'Amato legislation, the product of two years of
negotiations, would require state and local governments to match the
federal funds with 25 percent contributions.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___ ^Boston-Washington Corridor Is Home to One in Six Americans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One in six Americans live in the massive
Boston-Washington urban corridor, according to the U.S. Census
Bureau.
   Data from a new census study reported Tuesday also show that the
corridor contains almost one in four of the Americans who reside in
metropolitan areas.
   The data, for 1987, showed 43.5 million people residing in the
East Coast corridor which includes 25 contiguous metropolitan
statistical areas.
   With a national population of 243,396,000 people as of July 1,
1987, that means about 17 percent of the nation lived in the
megalopolis.
   And the bureau reports that 187,072,000 Americans lived in
metropolitan areas, nearly 23 percent of them in the
Boston-Washington region.
   There are four major clusters within the Boston-Washington
region: New York-Philadelphia, 27.8 million; Boston-Providence,
R.I., 6.2 million; Washington-Baltimore, 6.1 million and
Harrisburg-York, Pa., 1 million.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Station Not Required to Tell Viewers Toy Maker Providing Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission says a
Los Angeles television station was not required to tell viewers that
a toy maker was providing a children's program in exchange for
advertising space.
   The commission, in a ruling upholding the common industry
practice of ``barter'' sales, on Tuesday denied a complaint that
KCOP-TV should have identified Mattel Inc. and TV syndicator Group W
Productions as sponsors of the cartoon show, ``He-Man and the
Masters of the Universe.''
   The Los-Angeles based National Association of Better Broadcasting
had characterized the children's fantasy show as a non-stop
depiction of the ``He-Man'' logo and ``He-Man'' toy products made by
Mattel.
   The FCC in 1985 denied the complaint, which had been joined by
Action for Children's Television. NABB appealed to the U.S. Court of
Appeals in Washington, which in September 1987 remanded the case to
the commission which denied the complaint again Tuesday.
</TEXT>
