<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-China     06-07 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-China,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carnage In China Stuns Filipinos, Whose Uprising Ended Bloodlessly</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Filipinos, the bloody attacks on
pro-democracy demonstrators in China have served as a shocking
vision of what could have happened to their own ``People Power''
revolution three years ago.
   Commentators and officials have also taken advantage of the
massacre of hundreds and possibly thousands of Chinese to discredit
Filipino Communists, who have have patterned their 20-year
insurgency on the Chinese ``people's war'' that brought the late Mao
Tse-tung to power 40 years ago.
   Newspaper and broadcast commentators have drawn parallels between
the turmoil in Beijing and the events of February 1986, when
hundreds of thousands of Filipinos poured into the streets to
protect military officers who had mutineed against President
Ferdinand Marcos.
   Marcos ordered his troops to suppress the mutiny. But Marcos'
troops refused to fire on civilians who included nuns, priests and
students. On Feb. 25, 1986, Marcos fled Manila for exile in Hawaii.
   The only casualties were three pro-Marcos soldiers slain
defending the government television station against mutineers.
   ``There, but for the grace of God, we might have gone in February
1986, when that glorious buzzword `People Power' was invented,''
wrote columnist Max Soliven in The Philippine Star of the carnage in
Beijing.
   ``In that crucial moment, that crossroads of history, the
(Philippine) Armed Forces chose to side with the people rather than
with our tyrant.''
   In the years since Marcos fled, President Corazon Aquino and
other Filipino leaders have attributed the success of their
``revolution'' to factors ranging from the ``power of the people''
to intercession by the Virgin Mary.
   ``In (1986), we were all praying because we are all Christians,''
said Cardinal Jaime L. Sin, who called civilians into the streets
three years ago. ``To us, a man is indeed very valuable. Even
soldiers loyal to Marcos felt that their obligation is toward their
country.''
   Some Filipino commentators also believe the key was American
diplomatic pressure. After supporting Marcos for years, U.S.
diplomats warned him not to use force and finally offered him safe
haven in Hawaii.
   No foreign government has such leverage with the Chinese.
   Meanwhile, the military has already begun using the events in
Beijing as a propaganda weapon against the underground Communist
Party of the Philippines.
   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos said Tuesday that the events in
China prove that Communism is a discredited philosophy.
   In a statement Monday, Cardinal Sin said the savagery in Beijing
should serve as a warning to Filipinos who support the rebels.
   ``Please open your eyes to the reality that Communism can only
make our lives more miserable,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
