<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 0633EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Politics     06-07 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Politics,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Foreigners Among Leading Political Contributors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an unprecedented report submitted to
parliament, the government has revealed that many of the major
contributors to Israel's political parties in last year's national
elections were foreigners.
   The report only gave the first initial, last name and sum
contributed for the 20 largest givers, but the list included figures
from the United States, Canada, France and Spain, State Comptroller
Miriam Ben Porat said.
   She would not elaborate on the contributors' identities.
   The report, submitted Tuesday by Mrs. Ben Porat, publicly
revealed for the first time the names of political contributors.
   Israel's two major political parties, the left-leaning Labor
Party and the right-wing Likud, have long opposed any efforts to
disclose the names of large contributors, saying it would inhibit
contributions.
   The report named Charles Bronfman of Canada as the largest single
contributor. He gave $1.3 million to Labor. The second largest
donor, Jean Friedman of France, gave $415,000, also to the Labor
party.
   Although corporate contributions are outlawed, there is no
ceiling on private donations.
   Speaking before the report was formally issued, former Labor
party Secretary-General Uzi Baram said: ``To my knowledge there is
no other example in the world where most of the donations that are
made to political parties don't come from the same nation where the
elections are held.''
   Mrs. Ben Porat said she released the report to prevent large
contributors from trying to influence Israeli politics.
   ``If we know about these contributors and, God forbid, one of
them sees it as an investment, and wants it to be realized, the
public can come and help me so it doesn't happen,'' Mrs. Ben Porat
said.
   The report listed the names of all contributors who donated more
than $31,000 to political parties after August 20. Ms. Ben Porat
first notified parties that the names of contributors would be
published on that date.
   The election was held Nov. 1.
   The report lists 14 contributors who together gave $2.8 million
to Labor and five who together gave $405,000 to the Likud.
   One contributor, from Austria, gave $100,000 to the left-wing
Citizens Rights Movement.
   The report did not include the names of three donators. One gave
$250,000 to the Likud, and two gave a total of $470,000 to Labor.
   Ms. Ben Porat agreed to withhold publication of their names when
leaders from Labor and Likud said they were in sensitive positions
in foreign countries and publication of their names could endanger
their lives.
   The report said Israel's 17 political parties raised a total of
$41.8 million, with Likud and Labor both gathering almost $15
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890607-0045 </DOCNO>
