<FIRST>r a PM-RockyFlatsProbe     06-07 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rocky Flats Probe,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Launches Criminal Investigation Of Rocky Flats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB KERR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scores of federal agents seized records at the
Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant as the government announced a
criminal investigation of possible environmental violations at the
facility.
   Investigators were checking allegations that employees treated,
stored and disposed of hazardous wastes without permits, falsely
certified federal environmental reports and concealed environmental
contamination, said U.S. Attorney Mike Norton in Denver.
   Norton said 75 agents from the FBI and the Environmental
Protection Agency's office of criminal investigations began
searching the plant Tuesday morning. The probe is expected to last
six months to a year.
   Federal officials declined to say what prompted the search at the
plant, identified last year by the Department of Energy as the most
environmentally hazardous site in the nuclear weapons industry
because of contamination of an underground reservoir.
   Officials stressed that no new dangers existed at the plant,
which processes plutonium for nuclear weapons.
   ``It is absolutely essential that the public understand that this
investigation does not signal any major new environmental safety or
health concern,'' Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said in a
statement issued in Washington.
   Rep. David Skaggs, D-Colo., whose district encompasses Rocky
Flats, said the implications of the swarm of investigators at the
plant ``is the Department of Justice had some reason to believe they
would be risking destruction of evidence if they didn't act in that
fashion.''
   He told The Associated Press he has heard ``there were several
informants that became the basis for the FBI-Department of Justice
investigation and that's been going on for the better part of a
year.''
   The plant 16 miles northwest of Denver is operated for the DOE by
Rockwell International Corp.
   Investigators are examining actions by both government and
Rockwell employees, The New York Times reported.
   A spokesman for Rockwell said the company had advised employees
to cooperate with investigators but declined to comment further.
   Rocky Flats has been dogged by environmental problems. DOE
inspectors closed the plant's main plutonium reprocessing building
last October for four months because of safety violations. The DOE
also issued a report last December that revealed 32 new safety
problems.
   Thornburgh said he authorized disclosure of the investigation
because the search was a matter of public record.
   Skaggs, a staunch critic of Rocky Flats' operations, said there
was apparent ``reason to believe a number of individuals at the
plant were involved in concert in the effort to falsify and mislead
with regard to environmental compliance issues.''
   Energy Secretary Admiral James D. Watkins, in a statement, said
his department will perform an independent analysis of Rocky Flats
operations ``and ensure that continued operations, regardless of
past practices, are conducted in a safe and environmentally sound
manner.''
   He also said part of the plant would be shut down as a result of
the investigation, but he offered no specifics in the statement.
   Watkins said he was suspending ``those operations for which
safety could be adversely affected by the presence and functioning
of the Department of Justice investigating team.''
   Gov. Roy Romer, a Democrat who has prodded federal officials to
deal with Rocky Flats' radioactive waste disposal problems, was
informed of the investigation only an hour before it was announced.
Romer said he was assured he would be notified immediately of any
new dangers.
   ``I'm outraged by the possibility that some criminal action may
have occurred at Rocky Flats,'' Romer told a news conference shortly
after the federal announcement.
   ``I have been trying to say to people this is an operation that
we're monitoring closely and it's not endangering your health. Today
I have to say to people, `Wait a minute. I don't know yet,''' Romer
said.
   The investigation involves alleged violations of the Resource
Conservation and Recovery Act, the Clean Water Act and the federal
false statement law, Norton said.
</TEXT>
