<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 0557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-China-Leaders     06-07 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-Leaders,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thumbnail Sketches of Chinese Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are sketches of China's top leaders:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   DENG XIAOPING, 84, who ordered troops to march on the capital to
suppress pro-democracy unrest, is the most powerful leader in China
even though the highest ranking position he holds is chairman of the
Central Military Commission of the ruling Communist Party. The
commission, not the Defense Ministry, has the final say on military
matters.
   Deng was purged twice by radicals during the 1966-76 Cultural
Revolution and then staged a comeback that transformed China from a
country dominated by ideological battles into one with pragmatic,
market-oriented economic policies. Living standards have improved
for millions of Chinese but the modernization drive has led to
serious problems of inflation and corruption.
   Deng has been out of sight since May 16. Chinese sources say he
has been hospitalized for treatment of prostate cancer. The
government denied a report Tuesday that Deng had died, calling it a
``fabrication designed to make people uneasy and create chaos.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ZHAO ZIYANG, 69, reportedly purged for sympathizing with the
students, was general secretary of the Chinese Communist Party since
1987 and had been the nation's leading advocate of rapid economic
reforms.
   As governor of Sichuan province in the late 1970's, he led the
country in successful experiments in restoring family farming.
   In 1980, Deng brought him to Beijing and he was quickly named
premier. He became party chief in 1987 following the ouster of
fellow reformist Hu Yaobang, who was blamed for student unrest.
   Zhao was last seen on May 19 when he went to Tiananmen Square to
meet student hunger strikers. He is said to be under house arrest.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LI PENG, 60, who declared martial law in Beijing on May 20, has
been premier since April 1988. Li studied in the Soviet Union in the
1950's and represents the technocrats now filling many government
offices.
   He opposed Zhao's moves in market-oriented reforms, saying he
supports the plan but prefers a more cautious pace.
   One Hong Kong newspaper reported that Li was shot Sunday by a
police officer in the Great Hall of the People and wounded in the
thigh. It said Li was not seriously injured and the officer was
immediately shot to death.
   Li has not been seen in public since he met three new ambassadors
May 25 and said the government was ``stable.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   YANG SHANGKUN, 82, who supported Li's declaration of martial law
and led the hardliners demanding a tough stand against the students,
became China's president, or head of state, in April 1988.
   The post of president is largely ceremonial but Yang has close
ties to Deng and holds a seat on the 17-member party Politburo.
   A career military man who was active in Red Army campaigns in the
1930's and 1940's, Yang was appointed permanent vice chairman of the
Central Military Commission in 1982. Yang's power in that post
reportedly has grown and some say he has been running the commission.
   More important, Yang is widely believed to have family
connections within the hierarchy of the armed forces, particularly
the 27th Army that marched on the city last weekend.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   QIN JIWEI, the defense minister may have been ousted from office
for opposing martial law. Qin is the former head of Beijing Military
Region, which was said to be unenthusiastic about martial law.
   Qin has links with the 38th Army from the Beijing region that may
have refused orders to move against the students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
