<DOCNO> AP890607-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 0448EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     06-07 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Soar, Dollar Edges Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose sharply in Tokyo today, while the
dollar edged up against the Japanese yen amid uncertainties over
turmoil in China, dealers said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
which slipped 5.07 points Tuesday, rose 174.88 points, or 0.52
percent, closing at 33,626.89. The index had fallen four straight
days since Thursday.
   The dollar ended trading at 142.80 yen, up 0.17 yen from
Tuesday's 142.63-yen finish. After opening at 142.45 yen, the
currency ranged between 142.40 and 143.00 yen.
   Toru Kanai, foreign exchange analyst with New Japan Securities
Co., said the unstable Chinese situation encouraged dollar buying,
but speculation that the U.S. Federal Reserve Board might cut
interest rates also gave participants a reason to sell the U.S.
currency.
   ``We had a lot of dollar buying because many investors believe
the U.S. money is a safe investment in time of emergencies,'' he
said. ``But they didn't want to hold too many dollars either because
of expectations the Fed might cut its interest rates soon.''
   Investors speculate the Federal Reserve may ease its monetary
policy following the cut in the prime lending rate on Monday by
major U.S. banks.
   Kanai said there were unconfirmed rumors that the Bank of Japan
intervened in the market to support the yen when the dollar hit the
143-yen mark. ``It had no impact on the market,'' he said.
   The central bank usually does not comment officially on its
market interventions.
   On the stock market, dealers said the Nikkei index began to rise
as investors picked up cheap issues following the four days of
losses.
   But trading was basically directionless because of uncertainties
over political unrest in China, which made many institutional
investors remain on the sidelines, said a trader with a major
securities firm.
   Speculative buying pushed up the index, he said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Trading was moderate, with volume on the market's first section
estimated at 600 million shares, up from Tuesday's 550 million
shares. Among the winners were steel and construction issues.
</TEXT>
