<FIRST>r a PM-MiniSub     06-07 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mini Sub,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>MIT Hoping `Icarus' Brings Home Mini-Sub Prize</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT W. TROTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's no periscope and there is water
inside, but a two-man submarine built by students is MIT's bet to
crack the eight-minute kilometer and win the First International
Submarine Race.
   After months of planning and production, the cigar-shaped Icarus
was launched Tuesday on its first voyage _ in the Alumni Pool of the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
   They didn't go very fast: swimmers lapped them.
   Cliff Goudey, MIT Sea Grant College Program project director,
said the $5,000 top prize was a major incentive to enter the
one-kilometer race off Florida later this month.
   ``When the prize was announced, the idea of winning, combined
with the reputation MIT has in doing well in these kinds of things,
was motivation enough to get us involved,'' Goudey said. ``We all
want to be heroes.''
   The two-person submarine's trial run didn't get off to a flying
start.
   Students in the project _ Evan Mead, Al Cangahuala, and Anthony
Joseph, all 23; Patrick Nee, 22; and Russell Cohn, 18 _ added and
removed small floats to the submarine to balance it under water. The
craft's nose was too light, then too heavy, then too light.
   After about 30 minutes of tinkering, the crew began slowly
propelling the Icarus back and forth with Mead providing the legwork
for the pedal-powered craft.
   Swimmers on the other side of the pool easily lapped the
submarine during its first efforts. But as navigator Cangahuala and
Mead hit their stride, the Icarus began picked up speed.
   The three-day race, beginning June 23 off West Palm Beach, is
sponsored by the H.A. Perry Foundation, a non-profit scientific
foundation created to inspire development of undersea technology
through education, research and experimentation.
   The MIT entry will be up against 18 other submarines from 16
colleges or engineering firms.
   Mead said the MIT crew will use ``ringers,'' or athletes, to
pedal the submarine. The subs are ``wet,'' or water-filled, meaning
the pilot and first mate will have to wear SCUBA equipment.
   If Greek mythology has anything to do with it, the MIT entry
could be the favorite to win the competition. According to legend,
Icarus and his father, Daedalus, attempted human-powered flight.
While Daedalus stayed aloft, Icarus plunged into the sea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
