<FIRST>u p PM-NJGovernor Bjt   06-07 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NJ Governor, Bjt,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Primary Pits Two Congressman in Race for Governor's Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NR1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Democratic congressman seeking to avenge a
narrow defeat eight years ago and a Republican who vanquished seven
rivals in the primary won the right to battle for governor.
   Democrats on Tuesday overwhelmingly nominated Rep. James Florio,
while his congressional colleague James Courter won the GOP
nomination in a far closer race.
   Elsewhere, voters for the first time decided to shut down an
operating nuclear power plant. A measure that would have kept open
the troubled Rancho Seco plant in Sacramento, Calif., was rejected
by 53.4 percent to 46.6 percent.
   The vote was not binding on the Sacramento Municipal Utility
District, but the plant operators said they would begin shutting
down the plant today.
   Looming budget problems, soaring auto insurance rates and high
property taxes promise to dominate campaigning for New Jersey's Nov.
7 gubernatorial election.
   Florio is making his third try at the governor's office. He lost
to Republican Gov. Thomas H. Kean in 1981 by a heartbreaking 1,797
votes out of 2.3 million cast. Florio ran third in the 1977
Democratic primary.
   Courter emerged from a tight four-way primary battle to score a
surprisingly decisive victory, winning by nearly 27,000 votes.
   The State Republican Committee already has targeted Florio with
statewide mailings of news clippings that describe his role as a
political powerbroker in his district in Camden, across the state
line from Philadelphia.
   Courter said he is optimistic and wasted no time in jabbing at
his opponent's longtime ambitions.
   ``Jim Florio has been running for governor nearly 14 years now,''
Courter said.
   Florio said he did not care which Republican won Tuesday.
   ``I am looking forward to taking charge of an out-of-control
state government. We need someone who knows the answer is not new
taxes, but the courage and willingness to make hard decisions. ...
We will ease the crushing burden of outrageous property taxes on the
citizens of this state,'' he said.
   Since losing to Kean, Florio has carefully built solid support
among Democrats and has softened his image. He was perceived as
brusque and aloof in the 1981 race.
   Florio and Courter ran on anti-tax platforms and attacked the
rapid growth of the state budget, which doubled during the Kean
administration.
   In Washington, Courter supported President Reagan's Strategic
Defense Initiative and distinguished himself on the Armed Services
Committee, while Florio gained a national reputation as a fighter
for the environment and author of the Superfund cleanup law.
   In the GOP primary, Courter was attacked by one opponent for his
dismal attendance record in Congress this year, and most of his
Republican foes charged he knows little about state issues.
   Former Attorney General Cary Edwards, Assembly Speaker Chuck
Hardwick and state Sen. William Gormley were in a close battle for
second place. Sen. Gerald Cardinale ran a distant fifth, while three
other Republicans shared about 3 percent of the vote.
   With 5,817 of 5,845 precincts, or 99 percent, reporting, Courter
had 110,852 votes, or 29 percent; Edwards had 84,124 votes, or 22
percent; Hardwick had 81,193 votes, or 21 percent; Gormley had
65,684 votes, or 17 percent, and Cardinale had 32,159 votes, or 8
percent.
   Florio beat his challengers in all 21 counties, scoring the most
decisive Democratic primary win since 1965. He maintained a low
profile during the campaign against Princeton Mayor Barbara Sigmund
and Assemblyman Alan Karcher.
   With 5,818 of 5,845 precincts reporting, or 99 percent, Florio
had 248,059 votes, or 68 percent; Sigmund had 60,470 votes, or 17
percent; and, Karcher had 55,929 votes, or 15 percent.
   Kean by law was not allowed to seek a third consecutive four-year
term.
</TEXT>
