<FIRST>r a PM-DuckWars     06-07 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Duck Wars,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Bans Ducks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. AUGUSTINE BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ducks have been dumped and
their supporters are crying foul.
   The few Muscovy ducks that have survived a 17-month-old feud over
their presence in this north Florida coastal community were exiled
by commissioners at a late-night session Monday unattended by most
pro-duck forces.
   On a 3-2 vote, the city commission banished the half dozen
remaining Muscovies and disbanded a committee that had been formed
to resolve the dispute.
   No destination or departure date has been decided for the ducks,
which once numbered near 150 but dwindled after some residents
complained the large fowls defecated profusely and harassed other
animals.
   The duck debate became a cause celebre in January 1988, when the
commission voted to reduce the Muscovy population from 150 to 20.
The ducks were caught and taken to farms or residences outside the
city and eggs were destroyed.
   In late August, a Muscovy swooped down and attacked a city
commissioner and his family.
   In December, pro-duckers accused anti-duckers of running over the
birds with their cars. One duck was found with its legs chopped off.
   Commissioner Tom Wilson didn't present his resolution to oust the
Muscovies until shortly before midnight Monday because the
commission had a two-hour public hearing on a new veterinary clinic.
   ``The ducks have to go,'' said Wilson.
   ``Loud mouths and money have talked against the ducks, and we
can't match that,'' said Jim Vanairsdale, the only pro-duck
committee member to witness the vote. ``I'm really taken aback.''
   ``Some people are mad as hell about it,'' said Commissioner Pete
Dodson, who also backed the birds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
