<FIRST>r i PM-France-Nuclear 1stLd-Writethru   06-07 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Nuclear, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0510,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>France Announces Cuts in Nuclear Tests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS graf 5 to show that defense cuts planned over next
two years. Picks up graf 6 pvs, `Rocard's statement ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France will cut back its nuclear test program in a
move to limit rising defense costs, Premier Michel Rocard told a
parliamentary committee.
   In a written statement released Tuesday, Rocard told the National
Assembly's Defense Committee of the reduction plan but no details
were given. France conducts nuclear tests at its Pacific center at
Mururoa Atoll.
   New Zealand reported that France exploded a 20-kiloton nuclear
device Sunday at an underground site in French Polynesia believed to
be Muraroa. It was the third French nuclear test this year and the
106th in France's underground series.
   The government's policy is to neither confirm nor deny reports of
its nuclear tests. Rocard's statement did not say how many tests the
French had planned to carry out or how great the reduction would be.
   President Francois Mitterrand announced May 24 that the defense
budget would be cut $2.5 billion over the next two years. But the
defense budget still will increase by about 3 percent next year and
4 percent in 1991.
   Rocard's statement also said:
   The launching of a new generation of missile-launching submarines
would be set back about six months. Work on the new Rafale fighter
will be delayed for about two years and a battlefield radar
surveillance system called Orchidee will be delayed a year.
   In other reductions the statement said the number of fighter
planes destined for the armed forces would be cut from 33 to 28
units and the number of light transport vehicles to be delivered to
the army would be lowered.
   To avoid ``price drifts and financial approximations'' on major
programs a new external auditing system will be in place in the
autumn, Rocard said.
   It will be jointly directed by an army controller and an
inspector of finance and will be able to call on private auditing
agencies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
