<FIRST>r a PM-PoisonedOak     06-07 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poisoned Oak,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>600-Year-Old Oak Intentionally Poisoned, Say Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 600-year-old landmark oak was
intentionally poisoned with a tree-killing herbicide, officials said.
   ``It's obviously not an accident,'' said John Giedraitis, a city
forester who has been directing efforts to save the Treaty Oak,
under whose branches legend has it Stephen F. Austin, the father of
Texas, signed a treaty with the Indians in the 1800s.
   The oak, with a branch spread of more than 100 feet, lost most of
its spring leaves but is putting out new leaves.
   The Texas Department of Agriculture, which has been investigating
the incident, said initial test results pointed to a strong
herbicide.
   ``It's pretty nasty. This chemical is used to kill trees. It's
not used to kill weeds. They knew what they were doing,'' Giedraitis
said. ``It's a pretty senseless act.''
   Treatment of the tree last week consisted of replacing
contaminated soil and injecting charcoal and bacteria into the
ground to neutralize the chemical.
   No more treatment is planned unless the oak, situated in a park,
loses its second set of leaves.
</TEXT>
