<FIRST>r a PM-Defectors-Asylum     06-07 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defectors-Asylum,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Grants Soviet Journalists Asylum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Soviet journalists who defected
while in Alaska for the signing of a protocol easing East-West
travel restrictions have been granted asylum and are looking for
jobs in their profession.
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service on Monday granted
asylum to Anatoly Tkachenko, 24, and Alexander Genkin, 25, who
defected on Little Diomede Island in the Bering Sea in April.
   ``I was surprised that it came so soon,'' Tkachenko said Tuesday.
``It was a very happy thing for us to know.''
   The men have been staying with a family in Anchorage.
   Tkachenko and Genkin were part of a Soviet delegation that went
to Alaska for the signing by Gov. Steve Cowper and his counterpart
from the Soviet region of Magadan of a protocol allowing travel
across the Bering Strait.
   Because of bad weather, however, Cowper handled his part by
telephone from Nome.
   For decades, natives with a common heritage had been restricted
from traveling across the Bering Strait to visit each other.
   Norbert Lague, INS deputy district director in Anchorage,
announced the agency's decision on asylum.
   Tkachenko said both men want to become U.S. citizens.
   He said he will remain in Anchorage for at least the next few
weeks while awaiting a decision about employment as a broadcast
journalist in Atlanta.
   Tkachenko said Genkin, who is learning English, is being
considered for broadcast employment on the East Coast.
   Shortly after the defections, Tkachenko cited a lack of freedom
in explaining why the men did not want to return.
</TEXT>
