<FIRST>r a PM-HelmsleyOut     06-07 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helmsley Out,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harry Helmsley Out of Tax Case for Mental Impairment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Real estate tycoon Harry B. Helmsley is mentally
incompetent to stand trial on tax evasion charges, a judge ruled.
   U.S. District Judge John Walker on Tuesday severed Helmsley from
the trial of his wife and two others after finding that the
80-year-old hotel magnate cannot assist in his defense because of
memory lapses and reasoning difficulties.
   The judge did not dismiss the 47-count indictment against
Helmsley, only delayed his trial indefinitely.
   But noting that medical experts expect Helmsley's mental
deterioration to continue, the judge said, ``For all practical
purposes, today's order will remain the final ruling in the
government's case against this defendant.''
   Citing several doctors, including a court-appointed
neuropsychologist, Walker said Helmsley's condition had been
aggravated by a series of slight strokes.
   Helmsley and his 68-year-old wife, Leona, were indicted in April
on charges they evaded personal income taxes by disguising about $4
million in renovations to their Greenwich, Conn., mansion as
business expenses.
   The couple head a $5 billion hotel and real-estate empire.
   ``Just as no man by position of wealth stands above the law,''
Walker said, ``so too will no man, who is unfit to stand trial, be
subjected to a trial simply because the public's interest in his
case is great, or simply because some people may erroneously
conclude that the system enables a wealthy man to avoid the
consequences of his conduct.''
   Helmsley declined to comment after the ruling and was ushered by
aides from the courthouse to a limousine. His wife did not attend
the hearing.
   Jury selection for the trial of Mrs. Helmsley and two former
aides begins June 26.
</TEXT>
