<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 0938EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLead-Writethru a0530 06-07 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Lead-Writethru, a0530,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Collaborator Hacked to Death, Arab Homes Destroyed</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout to UPDATE with identity of women beaten, two Arab
homes destroyed, Israeli air attack in Lebanon; EDITS to conform; No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian suspected of collaborating with
Israel was hacked to death with a hatchet and hanged naked by chains
from a utility pole in the occupied West Bank today, Arab news
reports said.
   Masked youths also seriously injured a Palestinian woman and her
teen-age daughter, who were accused of aiding the Israelis, beating
them with clubs and chains and stabbing them.
   The army confirmed the Arab man was slain in the city of Nablus.
It said the victim had a criminal background and that police were
investigating.
   Also today, soldiers maintained a curfew for a fourth day in the
occupied Gaza Strip, confining more than 700,000 people indoors.
   The restrictions have prevented nine of an Arab hospital's 12
doctors from reaching work because the physicians lacked special
curfew passes, said Jorgen Rosendal, director of the Ahli Arab
Hospital in Gaza City.
   Palestinian doctors said a 75-year-old Gaza man was hospitalized
after being struck in the head with a bullet when troops opened fire
on stone-throwing demonstrators at the Shati refugee camp.
   Also in Gaza, soldiers blew up the home of a 17-year-old
Palestinian convicted in a military court of leading
Molotov-cocktail attacks on Israeli patrols. The home in the town of
Beit Lahia belonged to the family of Basam Shaaban Ibrahim Makusi
and housed at least 13 people, neighbors said.
   A second home in Beit Lahia that belonged to the family Akilan
Suleiman Bamilat was bulldozed. Bamilat also was convicted of
anti-Israeli activities, the army said.
   The United States and international human rights groups have
strongly opposed Israel's use of home demolitions as a punitive
measure, saying it constitutes unfair collective punishment that
often is carried out before Palestinians are tried in court.
   In the West Bank village of Beita three Palestinians were wounded
in a clash between troops and stone-throwers that broke out as
soldiers conducted a search-and-arrest raid, Arab reports said.
   During the raid, soldiers also reportedly demolished two
illegally built homes in the village.
   The Israeli Maariv daily, meanwhile, quoted U.S. intelligence
experts as telling Israeli officials they expected an escalation in
the Palestinian uprising, as well as increased efforts by
Palestinian rebels to obtain firearms.
   Participants in the 18-month-old uprising so far have mainly used
stones and firebombs in their attacks.
   The death of the suspected collaborator, Ziad Abu Ras, 30, raised
to 509 the number of Palestinians killed in the uprising, which has
also claimed the lives of 22 Israelis since beginning on Dec. 8,
1987.
   In all, 48 Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs on
charges of collaborating with Israelis during the uprising.
   The women accused of collaborating and beaten were in the West
Bank town of Qalqilya. Arab reports identified them as Najeeha
Kudruj, 45 and her daugher Lina, 17.
   In Israel, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's spokesman said Shamir
has rejected numerous appeals from the PLO for him to meet with the
organization's chairman, Yasser Arafat.
   Israel rejects any contacts with the Palestine Liberation
Organization, claiming it is a terrorist organization bent on
Israel's destruction.
   In southern Lebanon today, an Israeli helicopter gunship fired
three rockets at positions manned by Iranian-backed Hezbollah
guerrillas, injuring at least three, police in Sidon said. It was
the seventh Israeli air attack in Lebanon this year.
</TEXT>
