<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 0956EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LATraffic     06-07 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LA Traffic,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Construction Industry Agrees to Traffic Management Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal to get heavy trucks off the street
during rush hour has gotten the green light from major construction
unions and businesses, Mayor Tom Bradley said.
   Following long negotiations, city officials exempted trucks and
other equipment required to pour concrete, lay hot asphalt and erect
structural steel from the traffic- and smog-control plan, the mayor
announced Tuesday.
   In return, the construction industry agreed to shift its work
hours _ without premium pay _ to 6 a.m. to 3 p.m. instead of the
current 7 a.m. to 4 p.m. to reduce truck and automobile traffic,
Bradley said.
   ``Compromises such as these will ensure cleaner air and provide
free-flowing streets and highways for all in the city of Los Angeles
and Southern California area,'' Bradley said.
   The plan is expected to go before the City Council next month.
   However, Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky, whose Finance and Revenue
Committee later in the day approved spending $250,000 to help
develop the plan, said much work remains.
   ``There are a lot of flaws to any program which deals with city
streets and doesn't deal with freeways,'' he said. ``And I don't
think you can deal with one city and not deal with surrounding
cities.''
   The plan's one-hour shift would remove about 125,000 construction
workers from city streets during the morning and afternoon
rush-hour, the mayor said.
   The altered work schedule involves 83 union locals, including
boiler makers, brick layers, carpenters, operating engineers,
Teamsters, general contractors, pipe trade workers and painters.
   The proposal, developed by the city with a regional air quality
control agency, would require truck operators to pay a surcharge to
use city streets during rush hour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
