<FIRST>r a PM-ConArtistCandidate     06-07 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Con Artist Candidate,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Con Artist Who Successfully Posed as Astronaut Now Runs for Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REVERE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who has passed himself off as an
astronaut, senator, pro athlete and gynecologist says he's going
straight. He's entering politics.
   Robert J. Hunt, 27, is collecting signatures to run as himself
against Mayor George Colella. He said he made up his mind during a
three-month stint in jail.
   ``I will be the next mayor of Revere, I have no doubt,'' the man
of many disguises said Tuesday. ``I am honest. I think the people
are saying that if this guy can do what he did, maybe he can do
something for this community.''
   In his heyday, Hunt's favorite guise was that of an astronaut.
Wearing a uniform and aviation wings ordered from NASA, Hunt
lectured on aviation to pilots, went to the Marine Corps Ball and
drank tea with the lord mayor of Dublin.
   ``People like me,'' said Hunt, who trained as a plumber. ``I know
how to talk to people. I'll make a great politician.''
   Hunt shows little remorse about his past.
   ``I went to the White House, I was made citizens of countries, I
was an impersonator and there's no law against that,'' said Hunt.
``I had fun. I'm a thrill seeker.''
   According to information that surfaced after his arrest in
February on charges of swindling a couple out of $4,000, Hunt also
masqueraded as a fighter pilot, building contractor, baseball player
and Marine captain.
   Earlier this year, he was ordered to pay restitution to the
couple and placed on a year's probation. He was also convicted of
credit card fraud and put in jail.
   Hunt said his ``impersonations'' led to friendships with such
Vice President George Bush and Atlantis shuttle pilot Rick Hauck.
   During his years of posing as others, Hunt said he was never
tripped up by anyone. He said he reads voraciously on subjects like
aviation and nuclear war and picked up other knowledge from ``my
friends in high places.''
   The only time Hunt recalls faltering was during a lecture to
pilots when someone asked the ``climb rate'' of a F-18 fighter and
he was off by 2,000 feet.
   ``They just thought I was tired,'' he said.
</TEXT>
