<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Riots     06-07 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Riots,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say Uzbekistan Unrest Out of Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops in the Soviet republic of Uzbekistan have
not been able to halt bloody ethnic riots that have left 67 people
dead and prompted thousands to flee, officials and a newspaper
reported today.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev told the Congress of People's
Deputies the situation was under control but not stable, and said
there were still incidents of arson and killing.
   ``It has not changed for the better,'' Gorbachev said. ``It
concerns us very much.''
   The Congress joined him in appealing to ethnic Uzbeks and Meshki
Turks to halt the bloodshed.
   Interior Minister Vadim Bakatin, in an interview published today
in the communist youth newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda, said, ``It is
now difficult to maintain stability in areas where Uzbeks and Meshki
Turks live together.''
   He told the newspaper 11,000 of the 15,000 ethnic Turks living
among the 2 million Uzbeks in the Fergana region of Central Asia
have been evacuated to temporary refugee camps.
   The unrest, which broke out on May 23, has mainly involved Uzbeks
and the Turkish minority.
   The newspaper said 67 people have died and 417 homes were burned
in the rioting. Most who lost their homes were ethnic Turks, it said.
   It also said 87 soldiers have been injured.
   The Communist Party daily, Pravda, said 9,000 Interior Ministry
soldiers were trying to maintain order in the Fergana Valley, a
cotton- and grape-growing region of eastern Uzbekistan near
Afghanistan.
   Soviet dictator Josef Stalin exiled about 300,000 ethnic Turks to
Uzebekistan in the 1940s. The Turkish minority, who are Moslems,
have pressed recently to return to their homeland in Soviet Georgia,
near the Turkish border.
   The violence is the latest ethnic dispute in the southern Soviet
Union, where unrest in the Caucasus area and Central Asia has killed
scores of people and left thousands homeless.
   Nishanov said the violence in Uzbekistan began with a dispute
over the price of strawberries in a market.
   Uzbeki sources said it started between an ethnic Turk and a
Tadzhik and Kirghizian, two other local ethnic groups. But Uzbekis
resentful of the Turks joined the fray.
   The youth newspaper said soldiers trying to end the violence had
``honestly fulfilled their duty.''
   There was national outcry after soldiers in Soviet Georgia used
chemicals, shovels and clubs to break up a pro-independence protest
on April 9. Nineteen civilians were killed, and one was shot by
soldiers for violating a curfew.
   Bakatin said arson, robbery, and looting attempts persisted in
Uzbekistan despite the heavy military and police presence. He said
315 people were arrested for violating curfew.
   Soldiers guarded streets, squares, government buildings and fire
stations, the interior minister was quoted as saying.
   Chronic local unemployment and economic downturn has also added
to tension in the region.
   The Meskhi were the principal labor force used to build an
irrigation system in barren north-central Uzbekistan, which became a
flourishing farm district. Emigre sources say many were overworked
and died.
</TEXT>
