<FIRST>r p PM-NYCMayoral     06-07 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYC Mayoral,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Giuliani, Under Fire, Takes Early Leave from Law Firm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayoral candidate Rudolph W. Giuliani is taking
an earlier-than-planned leave from his law firm to avert further
attacks over its work for the Panamanian government.
   The former chief federal prosecutor in Manhattan said through a
spokesman Tuesday that he will leave the payroll of White &amp; Case on
June 15 and close out his work there by June 30. Giuliani had
planned to leave later this summer.
   He moved now to devote more time to campaigning and defuse
criticism over his affiliation with the firm, said spokesman Charles
Perkins.
   Giuliani's opponents have suggested the Republican tainted
himself by joining a firm with links to Panamanian dictator Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, who is under indictment in the United States
on drug smuggling charges.
   ``The people scared by his candidacy have been able to divert
attention from the real issues facing this city,'' Perkins said. By
leaving the firm, he said, Giuliani hoped to refocus on crime,
corruption and drugs.
   Giuliani joined White &amp; Case in February, a month after he
resigned as U.S. attorney. The firm has been a registered agent of
Panama since 1981 and reportedly has worked for a government-owned
bank there. Giuliani has said he did not know of the representation
until news reports disclosed it.
   Cosmetics heir Ronald Lauder, Giuliani's rival for the GOP
nomination, has attacked him for the Panama connection in his
campaign ads.
   Giuliani asked White &amp; Case to sever its relationship with Panama
with the exception of work approved by the U.S. or
Panamanian-opposition governments, and the firm complied, Perkins
said.
</TEXT>
