<SECOND>PM-Chelsea Schools, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0570,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approved Boston University Takeover of Chelsea Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 5th graf pvs, `Dukakis has ...' with
press secretary giving no indication of what the governor will do.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A first-in-the-nation plan under which Boston
University will take over Chelsea's troubled school system is headed
for Gov. Michael S. Dukakis' desk, where its fate was unclear.
   The Senate gave the plan final approval in a voice vote late
Tuesday. House endorsement came earlier in a 122-24 vote after a
sometimes personal debate that had some lawmakers near tears.
   Under the plan, BU would run the 3,500-student system for 10
years and pump in money from private donors and foundations for a
variety of new programs, including early childhood education,
counseling and nutritional services.
   Legislators and teachers, however, have raised concerns about
provisions exempting BU from open-meeting and public-records laws.
Teachers fear BU may make key personnel and salary decisions behind
closed doors.
   Dukakis has said he supports the concept but would not back the
measure unless such concerns were addressed. The Legislature added
no such amendments.
   Press secretary Mindy Lubber said Dukakis was reviewing the
legislation this morning and ``will do something today'' without
indicating what action that would be.
   Chelsea schools have been woefully underfunded, according to
officials, and the school system in the largely working-class,
Spanish-speaking city outside Boston has one of the highest dropout
rates in the state.
   Rep. Marie Louise Kehoe of Dedham, though a supporter of the
concept, said Tuesday she was concerned about the public-scrutiny
provisions.
   Shouting at times, Rep. Richard Voke of Chelsea replied, ``These
are kids that deserve a shot. Who do you think is going to appear if
BU walks away?''
   In an oblique reference to Kehoe's husband, who is a car dealer,
Voke said, ``People who own car dealerships and people who own banks
don't live in Chelsea.''
</TEXT>
