<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Khomeini     06-07 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Khomeini,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mourners Chant Support for Khomeini Successor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of mourners today chanted
support for Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's interim successor, Ali
Khamenei, at a memorial service for the revolutionary patriarch at
Tehran University.
   Iranian new reports said almost 11,000 had been injured during
the demonstrations of national grief since Khomeini died on Saturday
night.
   Tehran radio quoted an unidentified health official as saying
``many died,'' but no number was given. Eight deaths were reported
on Monday.
   News reports said 438 people had been taken to hospitals.
   Carrying black flags and portraits of the imam, or spiritual
leader, today's crowds at Tehran University chanted ``The imam is in
heaven today'' and ``Better we were dead and you were here with us.''
   The 86-year-old Khomeini, who turned Iran into a fundamentalist
Islamic state after the overthrow of a 2,500-year-old monarchy in
1979, died of a heart attack on Saturday. He had undergone
intestinal surgery 11 days earlier.
   Today's memorial service was held at the site of a weekly prayer
service. Attending were Parliament speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani, Prime
Minister Hussein Musavi, Chief Justice Musavi Ardebili, Khomeini's
son Ahmad, and Khamenei.
   Khamenei, Iran's president, was named caretaker leader on Sunday,
winning 60 of 74 votes cast by the Assembly of Experts. Khomeini had
formed the group to handle his succession.
   ``Obedience to Khamenei is obedience to the imam of Ummah (The
Islamic nation),'' the crowd chanted.
   After the ceremony, many people beat themselves rhythmically on
the head in a traditional gesture of grief by Shiite Moslems.
   Many fainted in the heat. They were lifted above the crowd and
passed overhead to stretchers that took them to first-aid stations.
   However, life was gradually returning to normal a day after the
city was convulsed with grief during the funeral of Khomeini.
   Shops reopened today with long lines for bread and other
supplies. Heavy traffic also reappeared on the streets; private cars
carried black flags and portraits of Khomeini on their windshields.
   Also today, the official Islamic Republic news agency reported
that Ayatollah Hussein Ali Montazeri, whom Khomeini removed as his
designated successor in March, visited his grave in Beheshte Zehra
cemetery.
   The news agency said the cemetery was still mobbed with people
paying their respects at the grave.
   On Tuesday, mourners blocked a van carrying the body in an open
coffin from the square where it laid in state for 24 hours in an
air-conditioned glass cubicle.
   Scrambling for mementos, they grabbed the white burial shroud and
tore it to shreds. The body, which fell to the ground, was taken
away in an ambulance and lifted by helicopter to the gravesite.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
