<HEAD>Senate Finance Committee Approves Nomination for Assistant Treasury
Secretary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenneth W. Gideon, a former chief counsel to
the Internal Revenue Service, was approved by the Senate Finance
Commitee today to be assistant secretary of the treasury for tax
policy.
   Three other of President Bush's nominees for key sub-Cabinet jobs
also were approved by the committee without dissent. They are:
   _Bryce L. Harlow, to be a deputy undersecretary of the treasury,
which would make him chief liaison between the department and
Congress. His father, Bryce N. Harlow, was a close adviser to
Presidents Eisenhower, Nixon and Ford.
   _J. Michael Farren, a former deputy undersecretary of commerce,
to be undersecretary with a leading role in U.S. trade policy.
   _Gerald L. Olson, a vice president of the Pillsbury Co., to be an
assistant secretary of health and human services, with
responsibilities as policymaker and liaison with Congress.
   The nominations now go to the Senate for final consideration.
</TEXT>
