<HEAD>UNDATED: them all.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   June 2
   The Union Leader, Manchester, N.H., on congressional ethics:
   The apologists for congressional wrongdoing now have the gall to
insist we must stop attacking it or we shall destroy the institution
itself.
   They're busy blaming everybody but the wrongdoers for their
troubles.
   The only cure for a cancer is to expose it and remove it.
   If we return to apathy, if we re-elect the wrongdoers, then the
cancer will grow and destroy.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 1
   Watertown (S.D.) Public Opinion on Jim Wright's resignation:
   Historians will probably try to interpret (the resignation of Jim
Wright as House speaker) in various ways, but the bottom line here
is that even the most respected, best liked, can fall from grace
when the nation's business gets mixed up with his personal business.
   And from the 69 documented charges against him, Wright's personal
business wasn't ethical by any standard.
   He is entitled to stay in Congress, at least for as long as his
constituents back in Texas want him there. ...
   But whatever happens, his credibility as the leader in the House
is no longer there. His effectiveness is gone.
   The people of this nation have a right to have confidence in
their political leaders.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 1
   The Hays (Kan.) Daily News on Jim Wright's resignation:
   There is no reason to pity Jim Wright, or to mourn his loss to
the House.
   Wright may blame his troubles on politics, and on the media, and
on Republicans.
   Like so many others _ from Oliver North to John Tower to Gary
Hart _ he too refuses to take responsibility for himself. His
glories are his, but his failures are someone else's fault.
   That is not leadership, or statesmanship, or even accountable
government. It is politics at its worst.
   That is what Jim Wright practiced, and it is why he is leaving
his post as Speaker and his job as a U.S. congressman.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 3
   News-Press, Fort Myers, Fla. on the Wright-Coelho resignations:
   With Reps. Jim Wright and Tony Coelho resigning under pressure,
lawmakers have some incentive to write clearer, stricter rules of
conduct for members of Congress. ...
   Not all are crooked, but in general we surely have the most
immoral, corrupt bunch of politcians in history.
   If they don't take this opportunity to write tough, straight
forward rules of ethical conduct, which cannot be misinterpreted or
misunderstood, then it will be clear that they have learned nothing
from this episode, and that most of them deserve to be booted out.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 2
   Post-Bulletin, Rochester, Minn., on Bush-Soviets:
   President Bush has responded effectively to recent policy
initiatives by Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   The president acted decisively in his visit to West Germany,
particularly with his statement on arms reduction and his call for
the East Bloc to tear down the Berlin Wall and to ``bury'' the Cold
War.
   Bush's more assertive approach not only scored points in the
public relations war with the Soviet Union. It also was
well-received in this country, where public opinion has tended to
believe that Gorbachev's reforms and less bellicose attitude are
genuine and hopeful signs.
   There is no assurance that reforms now under way in the Soviet
Union, the East Bloc countries or in China will succeed. Repression
may return.
   But whatever happens, the people in communist-dominated countries
never again will be as docile or submissive as they have been for
the past 70 years in the USSR and the past 40 years in China.
   Bush is right in encouraging these reforms. He is right in
challenging Soviet leaders to reduce armaments to a level that makes
sense for defense, but drastically reduces offensive capability.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 2
   Herald-Dispatch, Huntington, W.Va., on the Berlin Wall:
   President Kennedy was the first to issue the call. That was in
1963.
   President Carter repeated the message in 1978 and President
Reagan in 1987. Now President Bush, as he should, has added his
voice.
   Speaking in West Germany, Bush called on the Soviet Union to tear
down the Berlin Wall: ``The wall stands as a monument to the failure
of communism. It must come down. Make all Berlin a center of
commerce between East and West _ a place of cooperation, not
confrontation.''
   Bush thus has managed to put a bit of political pressure on
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev, who visits West Germany in mid-June.
   Europeans in general and the West Germans in particualr have
welcomed the apparent conciliation and cooperation that have been
Gorbachev's hallmark since he took power in Moscow. But the blunt
reality is that ``glasnost'' will be little more than a pretty word
as long as the Berlin Wall stands.
   The Soviets should back up their words with deeds _ and start by
dismantling the Berlin Wall.
</TEXT>
