<DOCNO> AP890607-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-China-Chicago 1stLd-Writethru a0482 06-07 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Chicago, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinatown Shaken by Beijing Massacre</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS 3rd graf pvs, `Like in ...' to fix grammar.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRIS CHANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The butcher raised his cleaver and slammed it into
the neck of a duck at a Chinatown grocery store.
   ``Killers,'' he spat out as he chopped the duck and listened with
two other men to a Chinese-language radio broadcast on the weekend
massacre in Beijing.
   Anguish pervades this Chinese enclave south of downtown Chicago,
as it does in other Chinatowns around the country.
   Groups of people _ mostly men _ squat on street corners or sit in
restaurants. Newspapers in hand, they talk about the military
suppression of the China's student-led, pro-democracy movement.
   ``The tanks,'' said James Yuan, pointing at a newspaper picture
of the scene in Beijing's Tiananmen Square. ``Students were in a
tent. The tanks, they crush them, over and over! Until all bodies be
a mess! A mess!''
   Yuan's face twisted in pain and he took off his glasses to wipe
the corners of his eyes. A pastor at the Chinese Christian Union
Church, Yuan was handing out fliers advertising a prayer service.
   ``The only thing we can do is pray,'' he said.
   About 16,000 people live in the 15-square-block Chinatown. The
district's commercial strip is a tourist attraction with its
welcoming green and red gate and blocks of restaurants and gift
stores.
   After the massacre, residents of Chinatowns in San Francisco, New
York, Los Angeles and elsewhere held demonstrations against China's
hard-line leader Deng Xiaoping.
   In Chicago, Chinatown residents grab for the World Journal and
other Chinese-language newspapers every morning, said Esther Ti-yu
Hsiao, a reporter for the World Journal's Chicago bureau. Some wait
for an hour by news stands for delivery trucks that arrive at 10 a.m.
   Advertisements in the World Journal announced a meeting planned
for Sunday to raise money to buy facsimile machines to get news out
of China and medical supplies and airline tickets for students who
want to go to China to demonstrate.
   ``It's going to be very dangerous,'' Ms. Hsiao said, nodding.
``There are rumors that doctors who treat the wounded in Beijing are
executed.''
   Rumors seemed to be as prevalent as hard news along the
commercial strip.
   ``I heard that Deng Xiaoping is dead,'' a bartender said in the
Three Happiness restaurant. The Chinese government on Tuesday denied
the rumor.
   At Mabel Lee Moy's Four Seasons Travel and Services Inc., Ms. Moy
has been counseling people not to return to China.
   ``I tell them they better think it over before they go,'' Ms. Moy
said. ``Everyone in Chinatown knows each other and I'm not going to
put anyone's life in danger just to sell a ticket.''
   Many people in Chinatown, like the butcher, would not talk with a
reporter, and some who did would not give their names.
   ``I don't even feel like eating,'' said a Chinese student who
declined to give her name. She works part time in a gift shop packed
with paper fans and miniature Buddhas.
   Her family, including her husband, are still in Beijing. She
talked with them by telephone on Monday.
   ``My brother and my husband spent the whole night at Tiananmen
Square the time they started shooting,'' she said.
   ``I'm lonely here,'' she said, adding she had planned to return
to China next year. ``Now I don't know when I can see my family.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890607-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1159EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a BC-WorstCrashes     06-07 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Worst Crashes,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>List of Worst Airline Crashes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Suriname Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of the worst commercial aviation disasters
worldwide:
   1. March 27, 1977: 582 killed in a collision of two Boeing 747s
operated by Pan American and KLM at the airport on Tenerife in
Spain's Canary Islands.
   2. Aug. 12, 1985: 520 killed when a Japan Airlines Boeing 747
crashed into a mountain on a domestic flight.
   3. March 3, 1974: 346 killed in when a Turkish DC-10 crashed 26
miles northeast of Paris.
   4. June 23, 1985: 329 killed when an Air India Boeing 747 crashed
off the coast of Ireland.
   5. Aug. 19, 1980: 301 killed in a fiery emergency landing of a
Saudi Arabian L-1011 jet at the airport in the Saudi capital of
Riyadh.
   6. July 3, 1988: 290 killed when Iran Air A300 Airbus is shot
down by USS Vincennes over the Persian Gulf.
   7. May 25, 1979: 275 killed when an American Airlines DC-10
crashed on takeoff in Chicago.
   8. Sept. 1, 1983: 269 killed when a Korean Air Lines 747 was shot
down by a Soviet fighter after flying through Soviet airspace near
Sakhalin Island.
   9. Dec. 21, 1988: 259 aboard killed when a Pan Am Boeing 747
crashed in Lockerbie, Scotland. Eleven more people killed on the
ground. A terrorist bomb was blamed.
   10. Nov. 28, 1979: 257 killed when an Air New Zealand DC-10
taking tourists to the South Pole struck a mountain in Antarctica.
   11. Dec. 12, 1985: 256 killed when an chartered Arrow Air DC-8
carrying members of the 101st Airborne Division crashed on takeoff
at Gander, Newfoundland.
   12. Jan. 1, 1978: 213 killed when an Air Indian 747 en route to
the Middle East kingdom of Dubai crashed less than two minutes after
taking off from Bombay.
   13. Dec. 4, 1974: 191 killed when a chartered Dutch DC-8
returning Indonesian Moslems from Saudi Arabia went down in Sri
Lanka.
   14. Aug. 3, 1975: 188 killed when a chartered Moroccan Boeing 707
crashed near Agadir, Morocco.
   15. May 9, 1987: 183 killed when a Polish LOT airliner crashed
near Warsaw.
   16. Nov. 15, 1978: 183 killed when a chartered Icelandic Airlines
DC-8 crashed short of an airport in Colombo, Sri Lanka. On Nov. 27,
1983, 183 people were killed when an Avianca Boeing 747 crashed near
Madrid's Barajas airport.
   17. Dec. 1, 1981: 180 killed when a chartered Yugoslavian
Inex-Adria Airways DC-9 slammed into a fog-shrouded mountain near
Ajaccio, Corsica.
   Three separate crashes each killed 176 people: A Soviet Aeroflot
crash near Moscow in October 1972; the collision of a British
Airways Trident and a Yugoslav DC-9 near Zagreb, Yugoslavia, in
September 1976; and the crash of a Jordanian Boeing 707 at Nigeria's
Kano airport in January 1973.
   Other recent crashes include a South African Airways 747 that
crashed off the island of Mauritius in the Indian Ocean last Nov.
28, killing 159; a Korean Air Lines 707 downed by a terrorist bomb
on the border between Burma and Thailand last Nov. 29, killing 115;
and a Northwest Airlines MD-80 that crashed after taking off from
Detroit Metropolitan Airport last August 16, killing 155.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890607-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Pakistan 1stLd-Writethru a0447 06-07 0804</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Pakistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0447,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ms. Bhutto Says Pakistan Does Not Possess Nuclear Device</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material, editing throughout with address to Congress.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto of Pakistan told
a joint meeting of Congress today that Pakistan does not possess a
nuclear weapon, will not build one and ``will not provoke a nuclear
arms race'' on the Indian subcontinent.
   Ms. Bhutto made her pledge in an address in which she said
democracy is on the rise in her region and dictators are in retreat
around the world.
   She said the United State and Pakistan represent a partnership
for democracy that must redouble its efforts to bring a broad-based,
democratic government to war-scarred Afghanistan.
   ``Pakistan and the United States have traveled a long road with
Afghanistan in quest of self determination,'' the Pakistani prime
minister said.
   She said that now that Soviet forces have withdrawn, ``let us not
leave with indifference, we must not abandon the cause.''
   Turning to the most active concern voiced in the United States
about her country's conduct, Ms. Bhutto said Pakistan has no
intention of becoming a nuclear weapons power.
   ``I can declare that we do not possess nor do we intend to make a
nuclear device,'' the Pakistani prime minister said.
   She said her government is ready to accept international
safeguards on its nuclear materials and reactors ``on a
non-discriminatory regional basis.''
   Pakistan has long advocated a nuclear-free zone in the region,
Ms. Bhutto said, adding that her country is prepared to conclude a
nuclear test ban with neighbors in South Asia.
   She mentioned no other country. Pakistan's regional rival, India,
has resisted such proposals unless they include China which already
has nuclear weapons.
   Ms. Bhutto told her audience gathered in the chamber of the House
of Representatives: ``We will not provoke a nuclear arms race on the
subcontinent.''
   Earlier, a senior administration official told reporters that the
United States has agreed to sell Pakistan 60 more F-16 fighter jets,
meeting a longstanding request by the Moslem nation.
   Brent Scowcroft, the president's national security adviser, said
Tuesday night that the deal, which was not officially announced, was
complete except for congressional notification. He spoke with
reporters after a state dinner in honor of Ms. Bhutto.
   The F-16 deal reportedly is worth about $1.4 billion.
   President Bush and Ms. Bhutto's talks Tuesday focused on the
bloody conflict in Afghanistan, Pakistan's defense needs, its
nuclear program, and the international battle against illicit drugs,
officials said afterwards.
   The United States and Pakistan, which has given refuge to 3.6
million Afghan refugees, have cooperated for years in the effort to
support the Afghan rebels seeking to topple Kabul's Marxist
government.
   With a glittering dinner and a full-dress military review, Bush
orchestrated a warm White House welcome for the 35-year-old Ms.
Bhutto, who is the first woman to lead a Moslem nation and is the
world's youngest prime minister.
   In his formal farewell remarks, Bush said he and Ms. Bhutto had
``discussed ways to encourage a political solution in Afghanistan''
that would replace the ``illegitimate regime in Kabul'' with a
peaceful and non-aligned representative government.
   ``The United States and Pakistan will continue to explore any
serious avenue towards this end,'' Bush said.
   Ms. Bhutto replied: ``We are in complete accord'' on the course
of policy in regards to Afghanistan. She added that Pakistan
``remains committed to a political solution of the Afghan problem.''
   The late President Mohammed Zia Ul-Haq, Ms. Bhutoo's predecessor,
had rejected the idea of a political settlement in neighboring
Afghanistan.
   Ms. Bhutto's father was by deposed Zia in 1977 and hanged two
years later. Zia remained in power until perishing in a mysterious
plane crash last year that also claimed the life of U.S. Ambassador
Arnold Raphel and an American general.
   Bush brushed aside reporters' attempts to ask about earlier
reports of the F-16 deal.
   An administration official, briefing reporters at the White
House, said Bush and Ms. Bhutto discussed the F-16 sale, but added
that he did not anticipate any specific announcement during her
visit. The official, speaking under condition of anonymity,
indicated there were no stumbling blocks to the sale.
   The two leaders also discussed efforts to combat drug production
and trafficking. Bush said he applauded Ms. Bhutto's ``tough stance
on eradicating the opium cultivation'' and thanked her for
extraditing an alleged drug trafficker.
   After a luncheon in her honor at the State Department, Mrs.
Bhutto and Secretary of State James A. Baker III witnessed the
signing of agreeements providing for $465 million to help Pakistan
finance housing, narcotics and education programs.
   The agreements are part of a $2.28 billion, six-year aid package
designed to support Pakistan's economic development, according to
the Agency for International Development. Pakistan is the third
largest recipient of U.S. aid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
