<HEAD>Two Cuban-Born Republicans Enter Race for Pepper's Seat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with second Republican entering
the race; PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `Ros-Lehtinen pledged ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Cuban-born Republicans today entered the race
for the congressional seat left vacant by the death of Claude
Pepper, the liberal Democrat whose district came to be dominated by
conservative Hispanics.
   State Sen. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen and conservative businessman
Carlos Perez announced bids to become the first Cuban-American in
Congress. The Miami Herald reported today that Democratic state Sen.
Jack Gordon also will run.
   The special election will be held Aug. 29.
   Ros-Lehtinen pledged to continue the district's tradition of ``a
leadership which has been based on a caring conscience and
conservative convictions. Claude Pepper's passing has left a void
that is nearly impossible to fill.''
   She said her priorities are bridging the ethnic and social
differences in the district, protecting Social Security, waging war
on drugs, taking a tough stand on Cuba and Nicaragua and strongly
supporting Israel.
   Gov. Bob Martinez called the special election on Tuesday, a day
after the 88-year-old congressman was buried in Tallahassee after a
week of mourning.
   ``Claude Pepper will be difficult, if not impossible, to replace
in Congress. But it's vitally important that we move as quickly as
possible so that the people of Florida's 18th congressional district
can be represented,'' Martinez said.
   Primaries were set for Aug. 1, with runoffs, if needed, on Aug.
15.
   Pepper was elected to the seat after its creation in 1962 and won
re-election by large margins every two years. He drew no opposition
last year.
   In his absence, Republicans are hoping to control the district,
whose registration is 54 percent Democrat, down from 72 percent a
decade ago. Hispanics are estimated to comprise nearly half the
district.
   ``I think the chances are pretty good for a Cuban-American to be
elected,'' said Sergio Bendixen, a Democratic strategist. ``Without
a doubt, that person would be the most powerful Cuban-American in
the country.''
   The Miami area is home for many of the 1 million Cubans who have
come to the United States since Fidel Castro's revolution 30 years
ago.
   Miami Mayor Xavier Suarez, an independent elected in 1985 as the
city's first Cuban-born mayor, has indicated he will support
Ros-Lehtinen.
   Ros-Lehtinen, a 36-year-old educator, is married to popular U.S.
Attorney Dexter Lehtinen, who has said he is happy in his current
high-profile position.
   Perez, a millionaire banana importer, is a staunch supporter of
former President Reagan and Oliver North.
   Republican State Rep. Al Gutman, whose Cuban-Jewish heritage fits
two large ethnic groups in the district, also was mulling over a
candidacy.
   On the Democratic side, state Sen. Jack Gordon said he would
decide by Friday whether to run. Gordon, 67, shares much of Pepper's
constituency and liberalism, but may have problems with Hispanic
voters because of his opposition to Nicaraguan Contra aid.
   Hialeah Mayor Raul Martinez, also Cuban-born, was a possible
Democratic contender as were Commissioner Rosario Kennedy, Miami
Beach Mayor Alex Daoud, Dade County Commissioner Joe Gersten, State
Attorney Janet Reno and former school board chairman Paul Cejas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
