<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Africa-Locusts     06-07 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Africa-Locusts,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Agency Reports Wave of Locusts in West Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swarms of desert locusts have been spotted
in the West African nations of Mali, Mauritania and Niger, the U.N.
Food and Agriculture Organization said Wednesday.
   In a report from its Rome headquarters, the agency said the
swarms were rapidly moving east and may reach Chad or even as far as
western Sudan. The report said there might be extensive breeding
later in the year.
   The agency said most swarms were small, but one was reported to
cover an area of 60 square miles.
   Swarms of locusts emerged in West Africa at the end of last year
but have not been reported in past months. The report said the
locusts' flight activity was limited until about three weeks ago. It
was not immediately known what caused the change.
   The agency said it was monitoring the swarms and conducting
aerial insecticide spraying where possible.
</TEXT>
