<FIRST>r a PM-ToxicSettlement     06-07 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Toxic Settlement,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Company To Pay Families $2.75 Million In Toxic Waste Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gas producer has agreed to pay $2 million
to eight families forced from their homes by toxic waste, The Boston
Globe reported today.
   Colonial Gas Co. acknowledged dumping coal-gasification
byproducts decades ago where the homes were later built, the
newspaper reported.
   Under the settlement, to be announced today, Colonial will buy
the homes, pay damages and finance the continuing cleanup of the
site near the Concord River.
   The Globe quoted unidentified sources as saying the company, in
addition to paying each family $250,000, agreed to pay $750,000 to
the Department of Environmental Quality Engineering for testing,
fencing the site and cleaning it.
   Residents had claimed their homes were rendered worthless and the
land was so contaminated that sections turned blue from cyanide and
other pollutants. They were moved to condominiums last year, with
the state paying their rent.
   ``We're greatly relieved and very happy,'' said Timothy Keeley,
who moved with his wife and three children last year. ``It's like
being a bird in a cage and suddenly having the door sprung open.''
   The families' attorney, Jan Schlitchmann, told the Globe the
settlement is believed to be the first environmental case between a
company and homeowners to be resolved through mediation rather than
a lawsuit.
   Mediation took six months, Schlitchmann said.
</TEXT>
