<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Census-Review     06-07 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Census-Review,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Local Officials Urged to Review Census Efforts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Census Bureau launched an effort Wednesday
to get local government officials involved in making sure everyone
is counted in 1990.
   The agency said it is sending technical guides to 39,000 local
governments, encouraging them to review census maps to make sure all
housing units are included.
   More than 100 million census forms will be sent to American
households at the end of March 1990 to be used in completing the
national head count April 1.
   The bureau said it will hold 470 training sessions for local
officials across the nation.
   Then, later this summer, census maps will be sent to the local
governments for comparison with local tax records, occupancy and
demolition permits, utility hookups and other records to make sure
no home has been overlooked.
   Once that is completed the Census Bureau will compile
block-by-block housing counts and send them back to local officials
in November for yet another check prior to the actual census.
   Census counts are vital to city, state and other local
governments because those numbers are used to determine
representation in Congress and in the distribution of billions of
dollars in state and federal funds to communities.
</TEXT>
