<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Recalls-Warning     06-07 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Recalls-Warning,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recalls, Warnings Issued for Children's Products</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A toy boat and three types of baby strollers
are being recalled because of the danger of choking children,
according to a government agency which also issued a warning about a
type of crib toy.
   No reports of injuries have been received involving any of the
products, the Consumer Product Safety Commission said.
   Toys ``R'' Us of Paramus, N.J., is recalling the ``Toot Toot
Tug'' toy boat because a metal rod could become detached from the
toy and possibly pose a choking hazard, the commission reported.
   About 5,200 of the toys were sold nationwide for about $4.99, and
they can be returned for a refund, the commission said. The boats
can be identified by the name ``Primex-Shyf 4768.''
   The second recall involves baby strollers sold by McCrory Stores,
Inc., which has its headquarters in York, Pa.
   Plastic plugs sealing the tube ends on the strollers could come
loose and pose a choking hazard, officials said.
   The strollers were sold nationally in McCrory stores as well as
by Britt's, Elmore, H.L. Green, Kittinger, Kress, McClellan,
Newberry, Silver, TG&amp;Y and some independent stores, according to the
commission.
   Imported from Taiwan, the strollers involved are Model AT410 Item
129088 umbrella stroller; Model PHT438 item 128942 umbrella with
canopy stroller, and Model PHT417, item 129007 canopy stroller.
   Owners of the strollers should discontinue using them and contact
McCrory for details of a free modification kit. Write, including the
stroller's item number and style, to McCrory Stores, Dept. 06-Mail
Stop 0512, 2955 E. Market St., York, Pa., 17402.
   In addition to the recalls, the commission issued a warning about
a crib toy called Crib Kickers made by Red Calliope of Los Angeles.
   These toys consist of a series of polyester-filled figures such
as animals and flowers, attached to a ribbon for tying them across
the top of a crib or playpen.
   Such toys can pose a danger of strangling to children once the
infant is old enough to push itself up and possibly get caught in
the ribbon.
   A warning is supposed to accompany such toys urging parents to
remove them when children reach that stage of development. The
commission said a warning was included in the box of the crib
kicker, but was not attached to the toy, so it issued a public
reminder of the danger.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
