<FIRST>u a PM-Time-Paramount 2ndLd-Writethru a0595 06-07 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Paramount, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0595,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramount Launches $10.7 Billion Bid for Time</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with stock prices and judge
denying request. PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `The Paramount ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. shares rocketed in early trading today
in a runup sparked by a $10.7 billion takeover offer from Paramount
Communications Inc. The offer rivals a merger agreement Time has
with Warner Communications Inc.
   Time jumped $43.50 to $169.50 a share on the New York Stock
Exchange. After a delayed opening, Warner was up $1.37{ to $53.12{
and Paramount slipped 87{ cents to $53.12{.
   Paramount, the entertainment and media company formerly known as
Gulf &amp; Western Inc., announced late Tuesday a tender offer of $175 a
share cash for Time.
   The company also filed a lawsuit in Delaware, where Time is
incorporated, to block provisions of the Time-Warner agreement that
Paramount said were aimed at thwarting competing offers. But a judge
declined to immediately grant Paramount's request.
   The Paramount offer comes 2{ weeks before Time shareholders are
to vote on whether to approve the merger with Warner, a stock swap
combination that would create the world's biggest media and
entertainment company with $10 billion in annual revenue.
   Harold Vogel, who follows the entertainment industry for Merrill
Lynch &amp; Co., said the Paramount bid would provoke ``a much lengthier
battle than Time and Warner had anticipated.''
   Paramount's bid is 60 percent above where Time stock was trading
before the publishing and cable giant announced in March it had
reached an agreement with Warner.
   It's also 39 percent above Time's closing price Tuesday of $126 a
share, up $2.75 from Monday's close.
   Paramount is the owner of Paramount Pictures, whose films include
the ``Crocodile Dundee,'' ``Beverly Hills Cop'' and ``Indiana
Jones'' series. Its TV programs include ``Cheers'' and ``Family
Ties.'' Paramount also owns publishers Simon &amp; Schuster and Pocket
Books.
   Martin S. Davis, Paramount chairman and chief executive, said a
marriage of his company and Time would create ``the foremost
American communications company, capable of competing on a global
scale against foreign media giants.''
   That's also a goal of the Time-Warner merger plan. Warner also
owns a movie and TV production companies.
   In a statement, Time said its board would review the proposal
``as required by law'' and urged its shareholders ``not to do
anything until they hear from Time.''
   A Warner spokesman said the company had no immediate comment.
   Davis said Paramount would make ``a superb business fit'' with
Time, the nation's biggest publishing company.
   ``We will have unequaled strength in quality magazine and book
publishing, as well as in motion picture and television production
and distribution, cable systems and cable programming'' he said.
   Davis said Time had essentially put itself up for sale by
agreeing to merge with Warner in a deal that would wind up giving
Warner's shareholders 60 percent of the new company. Nevertheless,
Paramount said it would withdraw its offer if Time shareholders
approve the Warner transaction on June 23.
   Until Tuesday, the planned Time-Warner merger had sailed past
every potential hurdle, but speculation had persisted that a bidder
would emerge for Time, long a target of takeover rumors.
   Paramount's offer is subject to several conditions, including
obtaining financing, the elimination of Time's ``poison pill''
takeover defense, required regulatory approvals and ending a
proposed lock-up stock swap between Time and Warner.
   Paramount Communications earned $384.7 million, or $3.21 a share,
on revenue of $5.1 billion in its fiscal 1988, which ended Oct. 31.
The company also owns Madison Square Garden in New York, the New
York Knicks basketball team and New York Rangers hockey team, the
MSG cable network.
   Time earned $289 million, or $5.01 a share, on revenue of $4.5
billion in its fiscal 1988 that ended Dec. 31.
   Time publishes such titles as Time, People, Sports Illustrated
amd Fortune. It owns the book companies Scott, Foresman and Co. and
Little Brown and Co. and controls the cable programmer Home Box
Office Inc.
</TEXT>
