<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Suriname-Crash 7thLd-Writethru a0619 06-07 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Suriname-Crash, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0619,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>168 Reported Dead in Suriname Plane Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, ``The Suriname...'' to CORRECT name of army chief
of staff; Pickup 5th pvs, ``The plane...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARAMARIBO, Suriname (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Suriname Airways jetliner flying
from the Netherlands with 182 people aboard crashed and tore apart
today near the capital's international airport, killing 168 people,
the airline said.
   The Suriname News Agency said the DC-8 went down about 4:30 a.m.
(3:30 a.m. EDT) about two miles from Zanderij International Airport.
   Airline spokesman Robbi Lachmising told reporters in Amsterdam
that the plane crashed in dense fog. The airport has no radar,
Lachmising said.
   The Suriname News Agency said three of the nation's top military
officers were on the flight and identified them as army chief of
staff Maj. Raymond Lieuw Yen Tai, air force commander Maj. Eddy Djoe
and army chief of operations Capt. Armand Salomons. All were
presumed dead, it said.
   The plane had been carrying 173 passengers and nine crewmembers,
Lachmising said. He said 168 people died.
   He said the 14 survivors were rushed to Paramaribo's university
hospital, but their identities and condition were not immediately
known.
   The airline said the plane was flown by Americans and identified
them as Capt. Will Rogers, pilot Glyn Tobias and engineer Rose
Warren, all full-time employees of Suriname Airways. Their hometowns
and fates were not immediately known.
   The 20-year-old plane, which was registered in the United States,
broke into four pieces but did not explode, and no fire broke out,
Lachmising said.
   But Suriname radio reports quoted nearby residents as saying they
heard an explosion shortly before the plane hit the ground. A U.S.
pilot in another airplane, who was not identified, was quoted as
saying he saw a ball of fire.
   Reporters who visited the scene saw burned bodies and wreckage
scattered over a wide area.
   Lachmising said ``the accident was not caused by the plane's
technical condition.'' There were no immediate reports on what
caused the crash.
   The airline spokesman said the jetliner, leased by Suriname
Airways from an unidentified U.S. company, was extensively
overhauled in Luxembourg about 10 days ago.
   Flight PY764, which took off late Tuesday from Amsterdam's
Schiphol Airport, tried three times to land at Suriname's airport,
about 15 miles south of the capital, airline spokesman Leo Marapin
said in Amsterdam. The weather was ``extremely bad'' and on the
third attempt the jet hit a treetop, he said.
   At least three passengers were top Dutch soccer players of
Surinamese origin, according to Inter Football, a Dutch organization
for professional soccer players. They were to participate in a
national tournament in Suriname, a former Dutch colony on the
northern coast of South America.
   Inter Football spokesman Nico Snijders identified the three as
Orwin Linger, Lloyd Doesburg and Fred Patrick _ all of the
Netherlands. He said initially there were four players on the
airplane but later corrected the number.
   A passenger list was not immediately available, but airline
spokesman Glenn Jie in Amsterdam said most of those on board were
Surinamese people living in the Netherlands.
   At Suriname Airways' downtown office in Amsterdam, dozens of
weeping relatives gathered to wait for news.
   Suriname, a nation of about 300,000, gained independence from the
Netherlands in 1975. About 200,000 Surinamese live in the
Netherlands.
   Wet terrain from recent rains hampered rescue efforts, the
Suriname agency said.
   Lachmising said a Surinamese army unit on maneuvers near the
crash site administered first aid to the survivors.
   Police, soldiers, and medical personnel went to the crash site,
which was sealed off to civilians. State radio said victims were
brought to hospitals in Paramaribo throughout the morning.
</TEXT>
