<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1344EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HUD-Subpoena     06-07 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Subpoena,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Votes to Subpoena Pierce Aide Deborah Dean</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee voted Wednesday to
subpoena a Reagan administration housing official who has refused to
help in an investigation of alleged contracting irregularities in
the Department of Housing and Urban Development.
   The House Government Operations subcommittee on employment and
housing voted unanimously to subpoena Deborah Dean, who was
executive assistant to then-HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce in 1982-87.
   The position of assistant secretary of housing turned over
frequently during the Pierce years, but Ms. Dean was there through
most of his term, said Celia Boddington, staff member for the
subcommittee headed by Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif.
   The subcommittee is investigating allegations that well-connected
Republicans were favored in a federal subsidy program for low-income
housing construction.
   James Watt, who served as interior secretary under President
Reagan, has agreed to testify Friday about his role, after leaving
office, as a consultant to a developer who got one of the subsidy
contracts.
   The developer, Judith Siegel, president of Landex Corp., has
testified that Watt helped her get a contract for a 312-unit project
in Essex, Md., under the federal government's Moderate
Rehabilitation Program.
   The subcommittee said Watt was paid $300,000 for his services.
   HUD said June 1 it was resuming subsidies, under new rules, for
the rehabilitation of privately owned housing used by low-income and
moderate-income families.
   HUD Secretary Jack Kemp had suspended the program in April after
the department's inspector general reported it had been mismanaged
and riddled with favortism for former high-ranking Republicans
serving as consultants to developers.
   On May 25, Pierce, who headed HUD through the Reagan presidency,
defended his role in the subsidy program, saying he tried to kill it.
   Pierce told the subcommittee that department officials used their
discretion in awarding subsidies to selected developers but that was
because Congress in 1984 waived requirements specifying fair-share
allocation practices.
</TEXT>
