<HEAD>President to Visit Wyoming Parks, Nebraska Next Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will visit Yellowstone National
Park and the Grand Tetons in Wyoming on Monday after announcing his
legislation to overhaul the Clean Air Act, his spokesman announced
today.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Bush would also stop
in Lincoln, Neb., on the way home Tuesday to deliver a speech on
alternative fuels, also part of the environmental package to be
unveiled Monday.
   While at Yellowstone, the president will visit some of the areas
charred from the fires last summer that are now undergoing
revegetation, Fitzwater said.
   He will spend the night in a lodge near Jackson Hole, Wyo., and
speak Tuesday morning at the Teton Science School.
   The trip is designed to showcase Bush's clean air package.
   His measure, still in the final stages of preparation, is
expected to propose tighter standards for emissions that cause acid
rain and for more strictly controlling auto exhaust emissions.
