<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1359EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-AvtexResident Bjt   06-07 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Avtex Resident, Bjt,0778</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Resident Left in Subdivision Contaminated by Rayon Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRONT ROYAL, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before toxic chemicals from the Avtex
Fibers plant seeped into the wells of homes across the Shenandoah
River, William Poland's house was part of a neighborhood.
   The neighbors are gone.
   Poland and his wife are the only residents left in the Rivermont
Acres subdivision, living alone on a dirt road that cuts through
fields between cement blocks where other houses once stood.
   At the entrance to the road, a home-made sign reads ``Entering
Water Pollution Area.''
   The Polands' ranch house was one of a dozen small homes with back
yards slanting down to the river, lined with trees that in
summertime blocked the view of the 65-acre rayon plant on the
opposite bank.
   Avtex Fibers Inc. bought up most of the subdivision five years
ago, when tests showed that groundwater had been contaminated by
viscose and sulfate bases from the plant's holding ponds. But the
purchases stopped short of Poland's house, the furthest upstream
from the plant, because it is outside the contaminated zone, the
company says.
   Poland said many of the former residents of the subdivision have
died of cancer, and he is worried about his and his wife's health.
He'd like to sell the house and move, he said, but most real estate
agents won't touch the property.
   ``I'm stuck and I know it,'' he said. ``They don't have to do
anything about it. What makes me so mad is they knowingly endangered
the lives of everyone down here. They don't do anything unless
they're forced to do it.''
   The Avtex holding ponds haven't been used since the contamination
was discovered and the Environmental Protection Agency declared the
area a cleanup site in 1984 under the industry-financed Superfund
law, said Avtex spokesman Nick Nichols. But pollution of the
groundwater and the river has continued, state officials say.
   At a hearing last week on the plant's violations of state water
pollution limits, state and Avtex officials alike described the
50-year-old plant as leaking chemicals through its floors and
deteriorated sewer systems.
   Richmond Circuit Judge T.J. Markow is considering a state
proposal to fine Avtex $140,000 for violating its agreement to
comply with state water discharge limits.
   From the other side of the river, few of the aging plant's
problems are visible, except an occasional patch of white gleaming
on the river bottom and a cloudy brown plume of water spewing into
the green river further downstream.
   Poland, 49, worked for Avtex for 17 years until quitting in 1981.
He says the first sign of a problem in Rivermont Acres came in 1968,
when a neighbor dug a well and found a smelly green substance at the
bottom.
   The discovery led to more than a decade of official inquiries and
tests of water in the subdivision.
   Meanwhile, Poland started bringing in his own drinking water in
1972, when his water started tasting bad.
   ``It smelled like sulfur,'' he said. At the same time, he started
itching and having skin problems.
   ``The dog scratched for a week after a bath,'' he added. ``He
don't imagine things.''
   In October 1981, the county health department advised residents
that ``the well water in this area could be potentially hazardous to
your health and you should not drink it.''
   Wells in the area had been found to be contaminated with
chromium, arsenic, cadmium, carbon disulfide and phenols, the
department said.
   After the area was declared a Superfund site in 1984, Avtex
offered to purchase all the plots in the subdivision except Poland's.
   ``Mr. Poland's property is not within the contamination area,''
Nichols said. ``In July 1984 Avtex did an analysis of his well that
proved to be standard for the area.''
   After Poland complained to the company of itching after showers,
Nichols said Avtex agreed to provide him with water ``as a matter of
courtesy.''
   Poland said Avtex built him a 6,000 gallon reservoir at a cost of
$8,000 and refills it each month.
   Tests have showed trace amounts of various chemicals in his
groundwater, but Poland says officials have told him it's not
Avtex-related.
   Poland says he's resigned to staying at Rivermont Acres. And if
the Avtex plant closes, as he expects it will, he'll go back to
buying his own drinking water.
   ``I'm just fed up with the area,'' he said. ``It's peaceful in
the summertime, but it's lonely as hell down here in the wintertime.
You don't see nobody.''
</TEXT>
