<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-ICBM     06-07 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-ICBM,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rice Says Don't Hike Midgetman Funds By Cutting Money for Other Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air Force Secretary Donald B. Rice cautioned
members of Congress Wednesday against increasing funds for the
land-based Midgetman missile by cutting money for other military
programs.
   ``It's simply unnecessary. There is no reason for an increase in
1990 funds,'' Rice told the Senate Appropriations defense
subcommittee. He responded to questions from subcommittee Chairman
Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, about congressional opposition to spending
levels for land-based nuclear weapons.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has proposed a fiscal 1990 defense
budget that includes $1.2 billion for the multiple-warhead MX
missile, with the existing 50 missiles to be moved from silos to
railroad cars by 1992, and $100 million for research and development
of the single-warhead Midgetman.
   Democrats who favor the Midgetman have criticized the small
amount of money earmarked for it while Republicans who support the
MX missile believe the $100 million for the smaller ICBM is a waste
of funds.
   Last month, some lawmakers said they would introduce an amendment
to the defense authorization bill to eliminate money for the
Midgetman, and Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., estimated that ``upward
of 250'' House members would back the plan.
   ``How strongly would you object if Congress increases the funds
for the smaller ICBM at the expense of other Air Force programs?''
Inouye asked Rice.
   ``There is no reason,'' said the Air Force secretary, describing
the planned budget amount for the Midgetman as adequate.
   On another Air Force program, Rice was pleased by Cheney's recent
assessment of the B-2 stealth bomber. The defense secretary had said
he needed more time to study the bomber before deciding on whether
it was worth buying. But after a visit last week to the Northrop
plant in Palmdale, Calif., where the bomber is built, Cheney said
that despite the increasing costs, the bomber is worth purchasing.
   Robert Costello, the Pentagon's former undersecretary for
acquisition, had recommended canceling the bomber which recent
estimates indicate will cost more than $500 million apiece.
   Inouye said his colleagues in Congress have used the total price
tag for the fleet of B-2s _ estimated at more than $15 billion _ as
``raw meat for political speeches.''
   Gen. Larry D. Welch, the Air Force's chief of staff, responded
that the bomber is ``uniquely qualified to cover a wide range of
targets'' and its development will make it a prototype for future
generations of aircraft.
   Welch also argued that the bomber is a good buy, noting that the
B-1 bomber was 160 percent more than the B-52 while the B-2 is only
a 22 percent increase over the B-1.
   On another topic, Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., a member of the
panel, questioned Welch about the quality of the South Korean Air
Force and whether U.S. forces estimated at more than 40,000 troops
and a handful of Air Force squadrons could be withdrawn as a
cost-saving measure.
   ``Our presence there is not worth the $2 billion we're spending
to stay there,'' said Bumpers, who argued that South Korea's high
gross national product and strong armed forces makes the nation
qualified to take care of itself.
   ``We are still an important part of the stability,'' Welch said.
   Rice urged lawmakers to be careful about the cost issue, saying
it cost less to keep the U.S. forces in South Korea than to bring
them back to the United States.
</TEXT>
