<DOCNO> AP890607-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1410EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-AIDS-Needles Bjt   06-07 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Needles, Bjt,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Free Needles Essential to Stop AIDS in Addicts, Expert Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Giving clean needles and syringes to drug addicts
does not promote drug use and is essential for stopping the
explosive spread of AIDS among narcotics abusers, a researcher said
Wednesday.
   And, in a strikingly upbeat assessment, a leading U.S. health
official who pioneered the first anti-AIDS drugs predicted that a
cure for AIDS will be found.
   ``In the early 50s and 60s, there were many people who predicted
there would be no progress against childhood leukemia. They were as
wrong then as they are about AIDS now,'' said Dr. Samuel Broder,
director of the National Cancer Institute.
   In an address at the Fifth International Conference on AIDS,
Broder noted that AZT, the first approved anti-AIDS drug, has
extended the lives of people with AIDS.
   A study of homosexual men showed that they had a 30 percent
chance of surviving for 18 months with AIDS in 1982, but a 60
percent chance by 1987.
   ``I believe the widespread introduction of AZT is one factor that
contributed to this,'' Broder said. He directed the development of
AZT, also known as zidovudine.
   In another report Wednesday, researchers at Johns Hopkins
University said they eliminated any trace of the AIDS virus in a
single AIDS patient who was given AZT and a transplant of bone
marrow from a sister whose bone marrow type matched his.
   The experiment showed that bone marrow transplants could work in
AIDS patients. Such treatment is unlikely ever to become widely
available, however, because matching bone marrow can not always be
found and because transplants are too expensive to be done on a
large number of patients.
   Despite being cleansed of the AIDS virus, the patient died of
cancer six weeks after the transplant.
   The study on drug addicts was reported by Dr. Roel Coutinho of
the public health service in Amsterdam, The Netherlands.
   Amsterdam began providing needles to its addicts in 1984. Addicts
spread AIDS by sharing needles and syringes, either because that is
a customary practice or because needles and syringes are in short
supply.
   Needle exchanges _ in which clean needles and syringes would be
swapped for used needles and syringes _ were proposed to help stop
sharing. Critics feared that such programs would encourage drug
abuse.
   ``There is no evidence that the needle exchange increased
intravenous drug use,'' Coutinho said. Sharing of needles among some
addicts dropped from 56 percent of addicts to 16 percent in one
study, Coutinho said.
   ``Apparely intravenous drug users are able to change their
behavior,'' he said, if needles are available and if the addicts are
given intensive counselling about AIDS and how it can be prevented.
   ``I think that providing needles and syringes is absolutely
necessary,'' he said.
   Amsterdam has only about 8,000 intravenous drug abusers, Coutinho
said, making it much different from New York City, for example,
where there are about 200,000. It is not clear, therefore, whether
the lessons learned in Amsterdam would apply in New York.
   Preliminary results from a study of a recently begun needle
exchange program in New York showed that drug abusers were less
likely to share their needles and syringes and were more likely to
clean them with bleach, which kills the AIDS virus.
   Don Des Jarlais of the New York State Division of Substance Abuse
Services concluded that the program was substantially reducing the
risk of AIDS spread among addicts.
   A study in London showed, however, that needle sharing fell when
needles were provided, but that some addicts also stopped using
condoms to prevent sexual spread of AIDS, and the incidence of AIDS
infection among the addicts increased.
   In San Francisco, needle sharing declined after an exchange
program was started but 30 percent of the study's participants
continued to share needles despite the best efforts of the program's
organizers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
