<SECOND>PM-Tank Death,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Killed in National Guard Tank Collision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two National Guard M-1 tanks collided at
Fort Harrison today, killing one driver and seriously injuring the
other, officials said.
   Sheriff Chuck O'Reilly said one of the 60-ton Abrams battle tanks
ended up on top of the other, causing severe damage to both.
   Authorities said the drivers were National Guard employees
performing technical checks on the recently arrived $1.8 million
tanks. The accident occurred before 9 a.m. on a flat, open training
ground, O'Reilly said.
   The cause was under investigation.
   The injured man was hospitalized in Helena, O'Reilly said.
   The M-1 has been used by the active Army since 1982. It has a
four-person crew and a top speed of 45 mph and fires a 105mm cannon.
   The Montana Army National Guard received 120 of the tanks during
the winter as part of the reorganization of Montana's 163rd Armored
Cavalry Regiment into a brigade, a larger unit with different duties.
   Guard units in North Carolina, South Carolina and Georgia also
use the M-1.
