<DOCNO> AP890607-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1421EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-PentagonProbe     06-07 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon Probe,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Defendants Sentenced Get Short Halfway-House Terms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Wednesday gave short
sentences in halfway houses to the first two defendants convicted in
the Pentagon corruption investigation and said their trial had
revealed purchasing practices that let consultants ``live a
parasitic life off the government.''
   ``I can't believe our government, the Congress and executive,
lets a system like this endure,'' U.S. District Judge Richard L.
Williams said in passing sentence on George H. Kaub and Eugene R.
Sullivan, vice presidents of Teledyne Electronics of San Diego.
   Kaub was given concurrent sentences of one year each on eight
counts of conspiracy, wire fraud and false statements. All but six
months of the term was suspended.
   Sullivan drew concurrent sentences of one year each on one count
of conspiracy and three counts of wire fraud, with all but three
months of the sentence suspended.
   The judge directed that the two serve their time in halfway
houses so that both men can continue to work. They have been on
leave from their jobs.
   Berkeley Baker, assistant to the president for public relations
at Teledyne Industries Inc., the parent company of the electronics
subsidiary, said by telephone from Los Angeles that he understood
federal law prevented a defense contractor from employing a
convicted felon. However, he said, the company ``will want to do the
humanistic thing'' and would study the judge's ruling.
   After completing their time, Kaub and Sullivan will be on
probation for two years with orders to do 200 hours of unspecified
community service.
   Kaub was fined $30,000.
   Sullivan was not fined. His lawyer told the court that Sullivan
had no assets except a small equity in a house he bought last year
with a Veterans Administration loan.
   Kaub could have been sentenced to 40 years in prison and fined $2
million; Sullivan, 20 years and $1 million.
   ``This trial was a window to Defense Department procurement
procedures,'' Williams said. ``Those procedures are so outrageous
that a world of so-called consultants, and as far as I am concerned
that is another word for rogue, are permitted to live a parasitic
life off the government,'' the judge said.
   A jury found the two guilty in April of participating in a scheme
to hire defense consultant William L. Parkin, who, in turn, bribed a
Navy official to obtain inside information that would help Teledyne
get a $24 million contract for hand-held radar-detection kits.
   Parkin pleaded guilty to bribery charges. Both he and Stuart E.
Berlin, a former Navy engineer who pleaded guilty to receiving
nearly $5,000 in bribes from Parkin, were sentenced to 26 months in
prison last week.
   Williams said a halfway house in the San Diego area is expected
to have an opening within 30 days and the men will remain free until
then. He gave Sullivan until Aug. 2 to surrender so that he could
attend his daughter's wedding July 29.
   Charges against a third Teledyne defendant who stood trial, Dale
Schnittjer, were dismissed after jurors were unable to reach a
verdict in his case.
   A dozen other individuals and two corporations, including
Teledyne Industries Inc., have pleaded guilty in connection with the
Justice Department's ``Operation Ill Wind'' investigation of
military purchasing fraud.
   Teledyne pleaded guilty to conspiracy and making false
statements. The company, based in Newbury Park, Calif., has paid
$4.3 million in penalties and fines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
