<FIRST>u w PM-Frank-GOP 8thLd-Writethru a0641 06-07 0981</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Frank-GOP, 8th Ld-Writethru, a0641,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush `Disgusted' by Document on Foley Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 6th graf, Fitzwater said, and INSERTS 3 new grafs after
7th graf, ``He was,'' with new Foley, Michel quotes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush was ``disgusted'' by a
Republican document that labeled House Speaker Tom Foley a closet
liberal, Bush's spokesman said today. The author of the memo,
meantime, resigned his party post.
   Bush called Lee Atwater, chairman of the Republican National
Committee, to complain about the incident and Atwater apologized to
Foley, said presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater.
   ``We consider the matter closed,'' he added.
   Meanwhile, Mark Goodin, the author of the memo that equated
Foley's voting record with that of Rep. Barney Frank, an
acknowledged homosexual, resigned today as RNC communications
director.
   Goodin was a press assistant in Bush's 1988 presidential campaign.
   Fitzwater said Bush, who had a 90-minute lunch today with Foley
and House Republican Leader Bob Michel, had no advance knowledge of
the Goodin memo.
   ``He was disgusted by this entire incident,'' the spokesman said.
He said the memo seeking to discredit Foley, D-Wash., violated the
spirit of bipartisan cooperation that Bush has advocated since
taking office.
   ``The issue is closed,'' Foley said outside the White House.
   Michel, R-Ill., told reporters, ``There wasn't all the kind of
oversight there probably should have been'' at the RNC. ``It was a
mistake obviously from the national committee's point of view.''
   Michel said he did not know if Goodin had been asked to resign.
Asked what advice he gave Atwater, he said: ``I just said, `There's
got to be some remedy for what took place, and Lee, it's your shot.
Do whatever you think is appropriate.''
   Fitzwater said the circulation of the GOP memo on Foley was ``to
be deplored.'' However, he said the president retains confidence in
Atwater, his former campaign chairman whom he handpicked for the
party post.
   ``I deeply regret my decision on the Foley memorandum,'' Goodin
said in a resignation letter to Atwater. But, he added: ``At no time
did I ever intend to damage anyone's reputation ... the purpose of
the memorandum has been misconstrued. And in that regard, I have no
one to blame but myself.''
   He said the memo was sent out without Atwater's ``knowledge or
approval.''
   Foley said at his first daily news conference as speaker today
that Atwater telephoned him late Tuesday and was ``deeply apologetic
for any inferences of personal character,''
   ``He repudiated the statement and apologized ... I accepted
that,'' said Foley. ``It's regrettable, and entirely untrue of
course. I think the matter is now at an end.''
   Foley said Atwater promised such attacks would not be repeated
and added, ``I know of no reason why he won't keep that promise.''
   Foley, sworn in as speaker on Tuesday in place of a
scandal-scarred Jim Wright, also quoted Atwater as saying he
regretted any inference that the political attack was ``personal.''
   Michel, who had expressed dismay over the attack on Tuesday,
called Bush today to voice concern, and the president was angry
about the document, according to a Michel aide.
   One Democratic leader, Rep. Tony Coelho of California, said Bush
should get involved and see that those responsible for the document
are fired if Republicans want to persuade Democrats of their
sincerity.
   ``They're playing good cop, bad cop,'' Coelho said before the
resignation was announced. ``Here's a a guy sent in by Bush to do
the dirty deeds, and he calls and apologizes after the fact. If
they're really upset about these tactics, all they have to do is
fire somebody.''
   In the statement circulated Monday, the committee said Foley was
anything but the political moderate some have portrayed him as
being. The document was headlined ``Tom Foley. Out of the Liberal
Closet'' and said Foley's voting record was as liberal as that of
Frank, D-Mass.
   While Foley initially refused to respond to the political
broadside, some Democrats in Congress expressed fury and Michel, the
top Republican in the House, swiftly moved to distance himself from
it.
   Frank accused the GOP of spreading ``extraordinarily scurrilous''
rumors about Foley. He said Tuesday that the Republicans had smeared
the speaker with ``a sleazy headline.''
   Frank implied to reporters that he thought the RNC's decision to
focus on him was a not-so-subtle effort to portray Foley as gay.
   ``They put my name on it,'' Frank said. ``It was despicable. They
could have picked other liberals and put someone else in the
headline.'' Frank said he might reveal the identity of gay
congressional Republicans if the attacks on Democrats continued.
   He added: ``The ludicrous part is that effort to make Tom Foley
look like an unreasoning partisan. It's kind of like trying to make
a snowman dance.''
   Foley initially shrugged off the attack, saying, ``I'm not
concerned about political action committees. I want to work with the
president, work with the leadership of Congress.''
   At a breakfast with reporters a few hours before Goodin quit,
Edward Rollins, chairman of the National Republican Congressional
Committee, said Goodin had erred seriously.
   ``Sometimes you get a little too cute and obviously this is
something that blew up in his face,'' Rollins said. ``If I thought
it had gone on in my own committee, I would fire the person.''
   Goodin earlier defended his work. ``It was not a smear,'' he
said. ``It has to do with his (Foley's) liberal voting record.''
   But Michel said staffers ``do not speak for the Republican
Party,'' and ``on occasion they deal in excesses.''
   Frank also referred to a column in the New York Daily News that
quoted an unnamed aide to the House Republican Whip, Rep. Newt
Gingrich of Georgia, as spreading rumors about Foley.
   Said Frank, ``It's part of a pattern where they don't have
anything of any substance to use against people to try and use
innuendo and rumor.''
</TEXT>
