<FIRST>r a AM-BibleSpeaks     06-07 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bible Speaks,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bible Speaks Appeals to Supreme Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for the Bible Speaks Church
cited principles of religious freedom in asking the U.S. Supreme
Court to overturn a multimillion-dollar award to an heiress who
claimed she was duped into donating money to the fundamentalist sect.
   The church contended in its request for review, filed Monday,
that the issues raised by the case posed a threat to all religious
communities, especially those whose ``non-mainstream character
renders them particularly vulnerable to bias and misunderstanding,
both conscious and unconscious.''
   ``You can't unscramble so-called `possible secular components'
(for making a donation) from a combination of reasons, most of which
are religous, without offending the Constitution,'' said Norman Roy
Grutman, a church attorney.
   Elizabeth Dovydenas of Lenox maintained the Lenox-based church's
leader, Carl H. Stevens, conned her into donating $6.6 million to
the church in 1984 and 1985. She left the church in 1985.
   A federal appeals court found in March that her first donations
had been freely given and should not be returned. But it upheld
lower court rulings ordering the return of $5.5 million in
subsequent gifts.
   ``Those who run (the church) may freely exercise their religion,
but they cannot use the cloak of religion to exert undue influence
of a non-religious nature with impunity,'' Justice Hugh Bownes wrote
in the 1st Circuit Court of Appeals decision.
   The case was first heard in U.S. Bankruptcy Court after the
church petitioned for Chapter 11 protection, maintaining that Mrs.
Dovydenas' claim could force it into insolvency. After a judge ruled
in her behalf and a trustee was appointed to oversee the church's
headquarters, church leaders and dozens of followers abruptly moved
out of the former prep school in Lenox. Many have since settled in
the Baltimore area.
   The property eventually was sold to Mrs. Dovydenas for $3.5
million at a bankruptcy auction. She has told town officials that
she plans to turn part of it into a community center.
</TEXT>
