<FIRST>r w AM-Governors-Energy     06-07 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Governors-Energy,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governors Urge Long-Term Energy Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's governors urged Congress Wednesday
to try anew to forge a long-term national energy policy, and said it
should include tax and price incentives for the development of
domestic resources, even in currently restricted wilderness and
offshore areas.
   Democratic Gov. Steve Cowper of Alaska, presenting
recommendations of the National Governors' Association after an
18-month study, declared ``the nation simply may not be able to
afford to permanently remove prospectively valuable (oil and gas)
areas off its shores, in vast areas of the West and in the Arctic.''
   ``As a personal note,'' he added, ``it is my belief that we
cannot afford to foreclose development in the Arctic National
Wildlife Refuge,'' even in the wake of the environmental furor over
the damage caused by the massive spill of the Exxon Valdez oil
tanker. ``Any development in currently restricted areas can and must
comply with the strictest environmental safeguards, including
standards for tanker safety,'' he said.
   Cowper noted the governors also recommended the export of Alaskan
oil on a barrel-for-barrel trade basis with other nations. He said
the current prohibition against such exports ``reflects the
political situation at the time the Alaska pipeline legislation was
passed, not the real workings of the oil markets or the economic
realities of oil trade.''
   ``I am convinced that such trades would be economically
beneficial, given the high transport cost of moving Alaskan oil to
Gulf Coast refineries, where much of it goes today,'' Cowper told
the House Banking subcommittee on economic stabilization. ``The
nation would not lose oil supplies as the result of these
transactions.''
   Cowper, who was joined by representatives of the governors of
Pennsylvania, Oklahoma, New York and Montana, acknowledged that
``energy issues are not a central concern to most people today,''
despite memories of the oil shocks of the 1970s. ``However,'' he
said, ``I come before you ... to say that complacency is both
unwarranted and dangerous.''
   The trends are ``in the wrong direction,'' he said. ``Domestic
oil production is down, oil production in other stable and
`friendly' nations is down as a percentage of world oil production,
the concentration of oil productive capacity in the Persian Gulf is
up, and domestic oil consumption is up. In the transportation sector
alone, the nation now uses more oil than it produces.''
   Cowper noted the United States imported more than 43 percent of
the oil it consumed last year, and the bill accounted for more than
one-fourth of the U.S. trade deficit. ``What is more,'' he said,
``after nearly 15 years of improvement in our efficiency of energy
use, the most recent figures from the Department of Energy indicate
that our energy efficiency has started to decline. We use twice as
much energy per unit of GNP as Japan, and nearly twice that of our
European trading partners.''
   He said the governors want Congress to take a hard look at a
variety of incentives for domestic oil and gas exploration and for
coal, including standard investment tax credits on exploration and
the deregulation of natural gas wellhead prices.
   In 1977, Congress passed a law requiring the president to develop
and send to the Senate and House comprehensive 5- and 10-year energy
plans, and to update them every two years.
   Despite that law, said Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, head of the
subcommittee, ``this country has no national energy policy plan
worthy of the name.'' The last plan submitted by President Reagan,
in 1986, totaled a mere two pages, she pointed out.
   Ms. Oakar said ``the nation has been asleep on energy security
for the past eight years, and that is why the Alaska oil spill was a
wakeup call for America.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890607-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1446EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Military     06-07 0800</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Military,0832</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massacre Blackens Name of People's Army</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>A version of this report moved for PMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six days into a bloody crackdown to suppress a
peaceful movement for freedom, the Chinese army has failed to pacify
Beijing.
   There are numerous reports of clashes between units of the army
that may be loyal to different political factions.
   The massacre Saturday and Sunday of hundreds of people blackened
the name of an army onced famed for its bravery and selflessness.
   Troops once affectionately called ``brother of the people'' and
``Uncle PLA-man'' quickly were termed ``running dogs'' and
``fascists'' by citizens enraged at the killings of relatives and
friends by their own army.
   The events in Beijing have raised some questions about the
discipline and readiness of the People's Liberation Army, the
world's largest army with an active force of more than 2 million
soldiers.
   Simple barricades of metal fencing stopped tanks and other heavy
equipment, breaking the drive trains of the vehicles, copies of
1950's Soviet models. Other trucks broke down in the road.
   The government announced Tuesday that 364 military vehicles,
mostly tanks and armored personnel carriers, were burned by unarmed
citizens.
   Tear gas used against the tens of thousands of people who came
out to stop the troops had little effect. One canister that landed
near an Associated Press reporter briefly made his eyes sting and
head spin. The effects soon wore off.
   Communications among military units also appeared poor.
   On Wednesday, troops on one Beijing bridge scurried behind trees,
concrete fences and trucks as if an attack were imminent. The
assault never came.
   On at least two occasions, armored personnel carriers, driven at
high-rates of speed, crushed foot soldiers.
   Reports of dissension among commanders is adding to the chaos.
   On Tuesday, armies supporting rival factions clashed in front of
the downtown Military Museum. On Wednesday, thousands of troops
moved onto an intersection then retreated, as if preparing for urban
warfare.
   Troops show a lack of discipline by firing randomly into crowds
of unarmed citizens.
   Shots in the air have killed people in high-rise apartment
buildings. The windows of one compound housing foreigners was
riddled by 27 bullet holes Wednesday. An armored personnel carrier
crushed at least seven students in a group of thousands that
retreated peacefully from Tiananmen Square.
   The army's violence has shocked Beijing residents.
   Until the weekend, the People's Liberation Army held an important
position in the hearts of many citizens in this capital.
   Formed in 1927, the army was famed not only for its fighting
prowess but for its rescue work during disasters and the critical
help it provided to peasants harvesting crops.
   ``The army goes with the people like fish swims through water,''
was a popular proverb.
   The PLA played a key role in the revolution. Heeding closely the
order of Marshal Zhu De ``not to steal a pin from the people,'' the
army gained the affection of China's peasantry as it battled the
corrupt Nationalists, or Koumintang, and invading Japanese.
   Communist China's founder, Mao Tse-tung, recognized this role in
his famous saying: ``Political power grows out of the barrel of a
gun.''
   But now the gun has been aimed on the common people.
   ``I lived through the Japanese occupation and the Kuomintang
corruption,'' said a 65-year-old man. ``Never have I seen anything
like this. The army comes from the people. How can it kill the
people?``
   Li Tieguo, a soldier until last year, said he had been proud to
be a veteran of the army, but that turned to horror when he saw
troops kick a 12-year-old girl in the chest and crush her heart.
   ``When I saw these hooligans kill that girl I was disgusted with
myself,'' he said. ``Can these people be my comrades ever again?``
   The army was one of the four pillars of China's modernization
program started by Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping more than a decade
ago.
   So important is the military to Deng's planning that the only
title he has retained is chairman of the Central Military Commission.
   Under Deng's policies, the army has undergone a massive reform
designed to turn it into a professional fighting force. It has
decommissioned more than 1 million troops and purchased vast
quantities of materiel from the West.
   But problems remain.
   Clashes among units of the army in Beijing indicate the army has
failed to end the factionalism that has plagued the Chinese military
since the warlord period 80 years ago. Its seven regional armies are
clearly not all loyal to the same political commanders.
   The quality of its soldiers also remains suspect. Official media
reports quotes random surveys as saying about one-third of the
troops are illiterate and say deaf mutes and mental cases have been
accepted as conscripts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
