<HEAD>Precede KANKAKEE, Ill.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Two Children, Missing 9{ Years, Found in Vermont</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with reunion; PICKS UP 8th graf
pvs, `Ms. Frye ...'; ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDDLESEX, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Illinois man who hadn't seen his two
sons since they were toddlers was reunited with the boys today, 9{
years after their mother allegedly abducted them and fled along with
a religious group.
   Gerald Gromer, 34, of Bourbonnais, Ill., said afterward that the
reunion with sons Mark, 14, and Luke, 12, was ``not the happiest.''
   ``They can't understand why they have to go back to Illinois and
why I can't come to Vermont to join their church,'' Gromer said. He
described the religious group as a cult and said his children had
been ``somewhat brainwashed.''
   The reunion was held behind closed doors at a State Police
barracks. The boys did not comment.
   ``We have lots of things to work out in the next couple of
months. But we're going to make it,'' Gromer said.
   Loretta Gromer Frye picked up the boys for a Christmas party and
fled with them in 1979 after their father was awarded custody,
authorities said. She was arrested in Woodbury on Tuesday on
child-abduction and unlawful-flight charges.
   The religious group with which she fled settled in Vermont, said
State Police Sgt. Jean Lessard.
   Gromer learned Tuesday that his children had been found unharmed
near their Woodbury home, ending a search in which he said he spent
more than $20,000 and traveled to 11 states.
   ``We didn't know how to break the news to him, so when he came
into the office, we simply said `Merry Christmas, 1979,''' said Lt.
William Willis of the Illinois Division of Criminal Investigation.
``He got quite emotional. He broke down.''
   A lawyer appointed for Ms. Frye did not return a telephone call
today.
   Ms. Frye, 34, is a member of His Community, a religious group
founded by Roman Catholics in Kankakee in the 1970s, Willis said.
   His Community was started as a Bible study group but evolved into
a cult with strong leadership, said the Rev. James McDermott of St.
James the Apostle Church in Irwin, who worked with the group at its
early meetings.
   Willis said several women and children left the area when the
cult moved in 1979. ``They were going to be the new exodus from
Egypt,'' McDermott said.
   Ms. Frye used four aliases as the cult moved frequently around
the country, settling several months ago in Vermont, Willis said.
   ``In March we got a serious lead and have been in contact with
Vermont State Police and the FBI there,'' he said.
</TEXT>
