<FIRST>u w PM-US-China 5thLd-Writethru a0645 06-07 0905</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-China, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0645,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Orders Evacuation of Diplomatic Dependents</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 10 grafs new with Tutwiler comments; picks up 6th graf pvs,
The embassy. Removes last 5 grafs pvs to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has ordered the evacuation
from China of all 258 U.S. diplomatic dependents and non-essential
government personnel and is urging all other Americans ``to leave at
once,'' it was announced today.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said U.S.
Ambassador James Lilley had protested to Vice Foreign Minister Xhu
Qizhan about several instances of rifle fire that broke windows at
apartments occupied by U.S. government employees. She said there
were no injuries.
   ``The situation in Beijing, and in China, is volatile, uncertain
and increasingly dangerous,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   Therefore, Secretary of State James A. Baker III and U.S.
Ambassador James Lilley ``are strongly urging all American citizens
to leave China,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   On Tuesday, the U.S. government had only urged U.S. citizens to
leave the capital city of Beijing.
   Ms. Tutwiler said no U.S. diplomats had been ordered to leave and
they were attempting to aid other U.S. citizens to get out of the
country.
   The spokesowman said the United States is chartering commercial
aircraft to fly to Beijing and Shanghai. Two wide-bodied aircraft
will arrive in Beijing on Thursday, and one will stop in Shanghai on
the way out, she said.
   The State Department's best estimate is that there are fewer than
1,000 Americans remaining in Beijing, she said. The U.S. embassy was
trying to arrange transportation from hotels and other locations to
the airport for U.S. citizens trying to leave.
   At the White House, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said,
``We have urged all other Americans in China to leave at once.''
   Ms. Tutwiler said the U.S. government had no evidence that any
threats had been made directly against American citizens or other
foreigners, but given the increasingly chaotic situation, it was
``prudent and wise'' to order the evacuation.
   The embassy in Beijing had recommended the evacuation of
dependents and non-essential diplomatic personnel to Secretary of
State James A. Baker III early Wednesday, said Evans Gerakas, a
spokesman for the task force on China.
   Gerakas said the embassy reported that Chinese soldiers had
surrounded an apartment complex housing U.S. diplomats and prevented
them from leaving the area for some time.
   ``The Chinese troops outside the residence of the staff had
prevented them from getting out but that situation had been cleared
up and the people were let out and had gone back,'' said Gerakas.
   ``As far as I know our people had gone back into the compound to
pack and get their things.''
   ``I can confirm that they (the soldiers) have left,'' he added.
   Although most firing appeared to be warning shots into the air,
dozens of bullets struck windows facing the street in a compound for
diplomats and other foreign residents about 2{ miles east of
Tiananmen Square.
   The U.S. embassy's chief of security said bullets flew through
the window into a room where his two children were watching
television.
   A senior official in Washington said the bullets appeared to come
from ``the indiscriminate firing of troops who were attempting to
clear Chinese civilians from the streets.''
   U.S. officials had said Tuesday they could no longer tell who is
in charge of China and they told Americans in Beijing to leave as
quickly as possible.
   ``There's been no communication from the leadership. There's no
indication who the leadership is,'' said Fitzwater.
   U.S. officials have mounted a wide-ranging effort _ using spy
satellites, embassy intelligence and interviews with Americans
leaving China _ in an attempt to determine what is going on in the
strife-torn nation. But so far the chaos enveloping China has defied
simple answers.
   ``You can't make judgments based on the situation at the
moment,'' President Bush said after a state dinner Tuesday night.
   John Sununu, his chief of staff, said the president must be
careful in his pronouncements about the struggle between
pro-democracy Chinese and hard-line government officials.
   ``You don't want to give them the excuse, if the president says
something strong, of saying, `See, it's being driven externally,'''
said Sununu, who also attended the state dinner.
   Fitzwater said Tuesday that China's senior leaders appeared to
have left the capital. He said the U.S. embassy has been in contact
with mid-level Chinese officials but has had ``no contact with the
top-level people _ and we've tried.''
   Meanwhile, U.S. intelligence reports indicate that the number of
dead in the weekend attack on pro-democracy protesters in Beijing
had reached 3,000, said a U.S. official.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, added that the
intelligence reports caution that ``hard evidence'' about the actual
number of dead is difficult to obtain in the confused situation, and
that the estimates could go higher.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Baker gave
the families of the 428 American diplomats and workers at the U.S.
embassy and the four consulates permission to depart, but the
facilities themselves would stay open.
   A State Department official said discussions were under way with
United Airlines and Northwest Airlines to supplement regular China
service so that one flight a day could carry out Americans.
   But United spokesman Joe Hopkins said in Chicago that his airline
had no plans to add flights.
   ``We're just operating our regular schedule'' of three flights a
week, he said.
</TEXT>
