<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reggie Jackson, who hit 563 home runs in
his 21 years in major league baseball, has struck out at selling
Chevrolets in his hometown.
   Jackson last week abruptly closed the dealership he bought last
year in hopes of profiting from his life-long love of automobiles.
   On Tuesday, a smiling caricature of Jackson and a sign promising
``World Championship Service'' still decorated the showroom full of
new cars, but the doors were locked.
   Jackson continues to operate a Nissan-Volkswagen dealership in
Palo Alto and a Ford outlet in the Sierra town of Quincy, but he
could not be reached for comment. Calls to his Berkeley dealership
and home in Oakland were met with operators' messages that both
numbers had been disconnected.
   Employees and other car dealers speculated that Jackson's lack of
success resulted from sparse demand for American-made cars in
Berkeley, where parking is limited and foreign cars are popular.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former astronaut Neil Armstrong will appear on a
French television special next month celebrating the 20th
anniversary of his historic walk on the moon, the producers
announced Wednesday.
   ``It's the only television program where Armstrong will appear in
person,'' Claude Atcher, president of Telemundi, which is putting on
the program, told a news conference.
   The program is to be taped on July 7 in Toulouse, the capital of
the French space industry, and broadcast on July 19, by Antenne 2, a
state-run network.
   Armstrong will be joined by fellow Americans John Glenn, Buzz
Aldrin, James Lovell, William Anders and David Scott, as well as
Alexis Leonov and Valery Koubassov of the Soviet Union and French
astronauts Patrick Baudry and Jean-Loup Chretien.
   The show will focus on the men who landed on the moon on July 20,
1969, and on the progress in telecommunications, meteorology and
medicine that resulted from space exploration.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cinematographer John Bailey has been
fired as director of ``The Long Walk Home,'' a civil rights-era
movie being filmed in Montgomery, and replaced by Richard Pearce.
   Film publicist Chappy Hardy on Tuesday cited creative differences
for the decision by New Vision Pictures to remove Bailey. Hardy said
he could not elaborate, but confirmed that Bailey was ``a few days
behind schedule'' on the relatively low-budget $6 million film.
   The movie, about a black woman and a white woman during the
Montgomery bus boycott of 1955-56, stars Sissy Spacek and Whoopi
Goldberg.
   Bailey, who had won acclaim as cinematographer for ``The
Accidental Tourist,'' ``The Big Chill'' and ``Ordinary People,'' was
making his directorial debut.
   Pearce has directed ``Country,'' ``Heartland'' and ``No Mercy.''
He also photographed four Academy Award-winning documentaries:
``Woodstock,'' ``Marjoe,'' ``Interviews With My Lai Veterans'' and
``Hearts and Minds.''
