<FIRST>r a AM-HolocaustPennies     06-07 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holocaust Pennies,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Gestapo Prisoner Raising a Penny for Each of 6 Million Slain
Jews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Polish immigrant who escaped the World War II
Holocaust is directing a one-man effort to collect a penny of
remembrance for each of the 6 million Jews killed by the Nazis.
   ``During the war,'' said Adam Starkopf, ``a Jewish life wasn't
worth a penny.''
   In the past two years, he has gathered $24,000 toward his goal of
$60,000 in pennies, which will be donated to the proposed U.S.
Holocaust Memorial Museum in Washington, D.C.
   While Starkopf, 75, and his wife and daughter survived, he said
it's important to remember the millions who did not.
   ``Not only to perpetuate the memory, but to alert the present and
future generations who think this can never happen again,'' he said
Wednesday.
   As vice president of the museum's Illinois chapter, Starkopf also
is helping direct a $10 million fund-raising effort in the Chicago
area.
   But pennies make it easy to donate, even for children, he said.
   ``From mouth to mouth, we let our friends know about the
project,'' Starkopf said.
   ``One woman called me to say she had 50 pounds of pennies. ...
When I go down to the store with my wife and they give me change,
maybe 50 cents, I say, `Will you be so kind to give me the change in
pennies?'''
   The donations, still in pennies, are delivered from time to time
to the museum committee in Washington.
   Starkopf and Pela, his wife of 53 years, were born and educated
in Warsaw, Poland.
   His father and in-laws were killed at the Treblinka concentration
camp, and he said about 150 members of his extended family lost
their lives in the Holocaust.
   For a while, Starkopf said, he and his wife escaped capture.
   ``I looked very Aryan _ blond-haired, blue-eyed,'' he said.
   But in February 1942, his luck ran out and he spent five months
in prison before he escaped.
   Later, he smuggled his 18-month-old daughter out of Warsaw by
drugging her with the help of a physician and placing her in a tiny
casket.
   His wife accompanied the casket to a Jewish cemetery outside
Warsaw, while Starkopf left the city by another route.
   The family reunited at a prearranged spot and with forged
identity papers were able to live as non-Jewish Poles outside Warsaw.
   ``It's the only case in the Holocaust when a child was saved as a
dead child,'' said Starkopf.
   When they came to this country in 1948, Starkopf said he had $3
in his pocket. Eight years ago, he retired from the sporting
goods-import company he started.
   The daughter, Joanna Brainin, 47, is married with two children
and lives in suburban Highland Park.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890607-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1519EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Evacuations 1stLd-Writethru   06-07 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Evacuations, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0667,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embassies Arrange Evacuation of Dependents, Nationals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `He said...' to restore dropped words; picks
up 7th pvs: Chinese troops...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign embassies were arranging special flights
Wednesday to evacuate the families of diplomats and other nationals
from China, which the French foreign minister said was ``on the
verge of civil war.''
   The U.S. Embassy ordered dependents of its diplomats to leave the
country. The embassies of Austria, Britain, Canada, the Philippines,
Switzerland and West Germany were arranging to get diplomatic and
civilian evacuees out by Friday.
   French, Italian and Soviet diplomats said they had no plans to
evacuate citizens, but the French and Italians said many had left
voluntarily.
   Roland Dumas, the French foreign minister, said in Paris the
French Embassy staff would be reduced ``to the indispensable
minimum'' because ``this grand and vast country is on the verge of
civil war.''
   An embassy spokesman, who would not let his name be used, said no
evacuation was planned because ``we don't think it is wise to create
a panic by rushing people out when we don't feel there is an acute
danger.''
   He said several wives and children of embassy staff members have
left voluntarily.
   Chinese troops ordered into central Beijing on Saturday to quell
a pro-democracy movement killed or wounded thousands of civilians.
Indiscriminate firing by soldiers continued Wednesday.
   ``Due to the unstable situation in China, the security situation
is deteriorating,'' U.S. Embassy spokesman Andy Koss said in
announcing the evacuation order.
   About 125 of 185 embassy dependents in Beijing would leave on a
special commercial flight to Tokyo and the others already had gone,
he said.
   Koss said 73 dependents from four U.S. consulates in China would
leave as soon as possible but all diplomatic personnel would remain.
   In Washington, White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said
fewer than 1,000 Americans remained in Beijing.
   A British official said privately the embassy arranged at least
four flights to Hong Kong for embassy staff members, families of
nationals and others.
   ``We decided it was prudent to reduce our staff,'' he said, but
added that most of the passengers were Chinese from Hong Kong, the
British colony scheduled to be returned to China in 1997.
   About 60 British citizens left Wednesday and 61, most of them
students, departed Tuesday, he said.
   Roland Hauser of the Austrian Embassy said: ``We gave the
recommendation to leave the country because there is no guarantee of
safety. I was not even allowed out of my diplomatic residence
compound today.''
   Chinese soldiers sealed off a foreign diplomatic and residential
area for two hours Wednesday in what they said was a search for a
sniper.
   Dozens of embassy cars drove out when the compound reopened,
their occupants clutching cardboard boxes, suitcases and food
supplies.
   Hauser said the 40 Austrian students, teachers and businessmen in
Beijing were urged to leave, and those who chose to do so would join
Swiss evacuees Thursday on a flight to Geneva.
   Non-essential Canadian diplomatic personnel and all dependents
were to take a Canadian Airlines flight to Tokyo on Thursday, said
Sgt. Michel Riberdy, assistant military attache.
   ``There is a situation in Beijing which seems to be worsening and
we have been thinking that we might not be able to get people out
later,'' Riberdy said.
   He said only about 15 of the embassy's 45 staff members would
remain.
   Japanese Embassy staff members telephoned nationals in Beijing
urging them to leave by commercial flights or on Japanese airliners
scheduled to arrive Thursday.
   A West German diplomat said his embassy was trying to arrange a
special special flight to evacuate Germans on Friday.
   Corazon Tatarata, vice consul of the Philippines, said Filipinos
would be flown out thursday.
   Eugenio Campo of the Italian Embassy said it was urging Italians
to leave but would not send any diplomats home. He estimated 30
percent of about 220 Italians in China had left or were planning to
do so.
   A duty officer at the Soviet Embassy said there were no plans for
personnel to leave. The Soviet complement of 77 registered diplomats
is second only to the Americans, with 120.
</TEXT>
