<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--Elks-Racism     06-07 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Elks-Racism,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Severs Ties With Elks Lodge Over Racism Controversy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council has voted to sever
ties with the local Elks Lodge, a major contributor to its youth
programs, following the group's recent rejection of two black
applicants.
   The council voted 6-0 Tuesday to support Mayor Sheila Lodge's
call to block donations from the 1,800-member lodge to
city-sponsored youth programs. The lodge donated $24,000 last year
for disabled children.
   ``Let the Elks know that if the financial contributions are
tainted with racism, the city doesn't accept it,'' said Isaac
Garrett, president of the local chapter of the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People.
   Elks leaders said the lodge does not condone racism, blaming the
rejections of the black applicants last month on a small minority of
members. It only takes three votes from the entire membership to
turn down an applicant.
   Woody Wodarczak, the local group's exalted ruler, noted that the
Santa Barbara lodge has joined other central coast lodges in urging
the national Elks organization to change voting rules to admit more
minority members.
</TEXT>
