<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     06-07 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As luck would have it, the student who won
a car at a post-prom party was the one who couldn't take it home.
   Stephan Metzger is an exchange student from St. Gallen,
Switzerland. He won the 1981 Dodge Aries at an all-night, post-prom
party sponsored by Wilson High School's chapter of Students Against
Driving Drunk.
   The party last month featured music by a disc jockey, volleyball,
baketball and swimming. A car dealership in Wilson donated the car
as an incentive for students to attend the party, an alternative to
drinking and driving after the prom.
   ``It was very early in the morning and I was very tired, but I of
course was very happy. I never won a car before,'' said Metzger, 18.
   He said he would have to sell the car because he doesn't have a
driver's license, his stay in the United States is almost over and
it would be too expensive to ship home and convert to use with
European gasoline.
   Also, Metzger, who speaks his native Swiss-German dialect as well
as fluent English, German, French and some Italian, said he won't
really need a car when he goes back to finish high school in St.
Gallen, a city of 76,000 in northeast Switzerland.
   ``You could get around with public transportation and a little
bit of walking,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neither sleet nor rain, snow nor heat nor
dead of night will stop the U.S. Mail. But dive-bombing sparrows?
Now that's a different story.
   The Postal Service has discontinued deliveries to the Morse
family home because the carrier considers birds nesting above it a
hazard.
   Mark J. Morse said the nest is in the rafters of the porch, about
four feet above the mail box. And the carrier reportedly told his
superiors the bird ``dive bombs'' him when he attempts to deliver
the mail.
   ``I really can't understand the reasoning,'' Morse said. ``The
nest was built by a sparrow and most people don't consider sparrows
to be dangerous birds.''
   Morse said he and other family members have called postal
officials, but were told if carriers feel there is a hazardous
situation they must deal with, they do not have to deliver the mail
to a home.
   Postmaster Jake Zaleski said he was informed of the problem
Tuesday and will take steps to rectify the situation.
   ``I will contact the family,'' Zaleski said, ``and see if we
can't work out an alternate delivery plan. I have to consider the
safety of the carrier and if he thinks there is a hazard I have to
respect his thoughts.''
</TEXT>
