<HEAD>With AM-US-Pakistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bhutto Speaks for Youth, Women, a Compassionate Islam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto of Pakistan,
described as a leader of many firsts, addressed her own uniqueness
in a speech to Congress Wednesday.
   During her first official visit to Washington, the 35-year-old
Ms. Bhutto has been called the youngest prime minister in the world
and the only woman leader of a Moslem country in modern times.
   ``As a representative of the young, let me be viewed as one of a
new generation of leaders, unshackled by the constraint and
irrational hatreds of the past,'' said the U.S.- and
British-educated prime minister.
   ``As a representative of women, let my message be, `Yes, you
can,'' she continued, drawing applause.
   ``And as a believer of Islam, in this august chamber, let my
message be about a compassionate and tolerant religion, teaching
hard work and family values under a merciful God,'' Ms. Bhutto said.
   ``That is the Islam I know and that is the Islam we must all come
to understand,'' she said, seeking to project moderation as opposed
to the image of militance applied by some Americans to Moslem groups
accused of terrorism and of holding U.S. hostages.
