<HEAD>Central Park Rape Victim Admitted to Connecticut Rehab Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WALLINGFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment banker who was beaten and
raped in New York's Central Park in April was admitted to Gaylord
Hospital on Wednesday to begin an intensive rehabilitation program,
the hospital said.
   The 28-year-old woman, whose name has not been released, was
brought to Gaylord by ambulance from Metropolitan Hospital in New
York City, where she had been a patient since the April 19 attack.
   ``She was admitted to the 16-bed unit for traumatic brain injured
patient and will undergo a period of evaluation during which a
complete treatment plan will be developed,'' said Lori Ann Brass,
the hospital's spokeswoman.
   The average length of a stay for traumatic brain injury patients
is 60 days, but Brass said that varies, depending on the patient.
   ``The purpose of rehabilitation is to restore function. We help
people to get back to as productive a life as possible,'' Brass said.
