<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1607EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Pope     06-07 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Urges World Leaders To Promote Freedom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK POWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OEM, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Wednesday called on
world leaders to seize this ``moment of extraordinary awakening''
and push ahead with efforts to promote freedom and human rights.
   Later, he warned Roman Catholics in affluent Denmark against the
dangers of ``slavery to self under the guise of freedom'' and the
indiscriminate pursuit of material goods.
   John Paul, on the seventh day of a Scandinavian tour, addressed
diplomats in Copenhagen and then flew to Oem, a tourist center on
the Jutland Peninsula. There, he celebrated Mass for 10,000 people
on the ruins of a medieval monastary.
   Speaking of what he said were worldwide winds of change, the pope
told diplomats:
   ``Mine is an invitation to you, to all men and women with
responsibility for the public life of nations, to do everything
possible to encourage this moral awakening,'' the pope said.
   He called on his audience ``to further the peaceful processes
which seek to implement freedom, respect for human dignity and human
rights throughout the world.''
   The pope said despite this century's wars and political tensions,
as well as the afflictions of international drug trafficking and
AIDS, there was reason for hope.
   ``The world is living through a moment of extraordinary
awakening. The old problems remain, and new ones arise,'' the pope
said. ``But there is also a growing awareness of an opportunity
being offered to give birth to a new and better era.''
   John Paul didn't mention specific countries, but he has
previously expressed his approval of political reforms in his native
Poland and elsewhere. A Maronite Christian woman holding up a
Lebanese flag and a group of Polish folk dancers were among those at
Oem. About 20 Asian children pressed around the pope for blessings
as he arrived.
   Immigrants, mostly from Poland and from Catholic countries in
South America, have flocked to John Paul's appearances throughout
Scandinavia, an overwhelmingly Lutheran region. Danish Catholics
number only 28,000.
   The pope also met priests, nuns and representatives of Denmark's
Catholic community. To them he spoke of the sexual and family mores
in this liberal society.
   He said church teaching called for ``lifelong fidelity in
marriage, responsible parenthood ... reverence for every human
person from the moment of conception until natural death, the equal
and complementary dignity of women and men.''
   John Paul, who has also visited Norway, Iceland and Finland on
his Scandinavian tour, travels to Sweden on Thursday. He returns to
Rome Saturday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
