<FIRST>u i AM-China-HongKong     06-07 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Hong Kong,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Residents Demand That Chinese Leaders Quit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry residents on Wednesday honked horns,
planted Chinese nationalist flags and demanded that Chinese leaders
resign during spontaneous protests of the military crackdown in
Beijing.
   The protests broke out even though organizers cancelled planned
demonstrations for fear of more violence after rioters stormed
Chinese banks earlier in the day. Police said five officers were
injured and 15 protesters arrested.
   From dawn until nearly midnight, a stream of protesters converged
Wednesday on China's official Xinhua News Agency, the mainland
government's de facto embassy in this British colony. They shouted
abuses at the Chinese leadership and placed flowers for slain
demonstrators.
   Police said they had no estimate of the number of protesters, who
walked six abreast and stretched down several streets.
   Most wore black or white clothes, traditional Chinese funeral
attire, and many carried banners denouncing Chinese leaders and
praising the pro-democracy demonstrators ousted by soldiers from a
central square in Beijing nine days ago. Hundreds of people died in
the Beijing crackdown.
   Outside the Xinhua office Wednesday, at an altar across the
street, protesters placed flowers for those victims.
   A middle-aged man helped plant several flags of the rival Chinese
nationalist government on Taiwan and lamented: ``I had hopes for the
Communists with their 10 years of open-door policies. But now I am
disappointed.''
   Meanwhile, a convoy of taxis, cars and trucks, estimated at
between 2,000 and 3,000 by police, cruised past the building,
honking their horns. Many had black flags tied to their radio
antennas.
   Some groups had called for a general strike on Wednesday, and
many shops in this bustling British territory were closed. Many
displayed anti-Communist posters on their shutters.
   Sir David Wilson, the colony's governor, left Wednesday night for
London to meet with Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and members of
Parliament to discuss the future of the territory, where anxieties
about future Chinese rule have increased since the Beijing violence.
   Hong Kong is to revert to Chinese rule in 1997, when a
territorial lease expires. Some British lawmakers are now demanding
that the accord be reconsidered.
   Organized protests were called off Wednesday after police fired
tear gas to disperse about 7,000 rioters who hurled rocks and
bottles at police in Kowloon, Hong Kong's twin city within the
colony.
   Police said the clashes developed after a crowd drove through the
area honking their car horns to protest the Chinese military moves
and then attacked several mainland Chinese banks.
   About 98 percent of Hong Kong's population of 5.7 million are
Chinese, and two-thirds of them are refugees from mainland China or
their descendants.
   People who fled to this coastal colony from the mainland,
meanwhile, reacted to reports of the violence with grief and shock.
Official Chinese reports have blamed the violence on rioters and
talked mainly of attacks on soldiers.
   ``One of my colleagues received a fax describing the massacre in
Beijing and started crying. But the manager came in, tore the paper,
and said it was all rumor,'' said a Hong Kong resident who had just
returned from Zhanjian in southern Guangdong province.
   Australian tourist John Flitcroft, who was at Tiananmen Square in
Beijing when the troops swept out student protesters, said he hid in
a dormitory facing the square that night.
   ``They (tanks) crushed the whole square,'' he said. ``They just
ran across like a lawnmower, crushing the tents with students in.''
</TEXT>
