<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Zambia     06-07 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Zambia,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Tells Kaunda He Won't End South African Sanctions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush assured Zambian President
Kenneth Kaunda on Wednesday that he has no intention of lifting U.S.
sanctions against the apartheid government of South Arica.
   Bush and Kaunda also discussed the AIDS epidemic, and Bush
assured the visiting African leader of the U.S. commitment to AIDS
research ``and other kinds of support,'' White House spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater said.
   Kaunda urged that sanctions against South Africa be kept in
place. ``President Bush assured him that we would not lift the
sanctions,'' Fitzwater said.
   Kaunda told Bush the Zambian people are confronted with four
``killer diseases'' _ AIDS, malnutrition, malaria and drugs,
Fitzwater said.
   Bush also met Wednesday with President Quett K.J. Masire of
Botswana.
   The White House announced Wednesday that Bush will meet Friday
with Indonesian President Suharto in a private visit.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said that in addition to
bilateral issues, the two leaders will discuss Cambodia, China and
other regional matters.
</TEXT>
