<FIRST>r i AM-Flight103     06-07 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassador Lays Wreath to Lockerbie Victims; Faces Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new U.S. ambassador to Britain
laid a wreath Wednesday at a memorial to the 270 people who died in
the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103, and he faced angry protest from a
victim's wife.
   Wendy Giebler of Hasbrouck Heights, N.J. said U.S. officials have
been ``rude and cruel'' to relatives of Flight 103 victims. She also
accused investigators of witholding information.
   ``We want to know why it was possible to get the bomb aboard and
why Pan Am did not react to warnings,'' said Mrs. Giebler, wife of
Flight 103 passenger William Giebler, who died in the Dec. 21
bombing.
   After the ceremony at Dryfesdale cemetary, Mrs. Giebler, 26,
called for an independent investigation to supplement the work of
Scottish police, the FBI and other law enforcement agencies.
   She spoke only briefly to U.S. Ambassador Henry Catto, who
visited Northern Ireland and Lockerbie this week after taking up his
post in London last month.
   At a news conference later, Catto said he would be surprised if
anyone had been rude to relatives, and he expressed satisfaction
with the progress made by the investigation based in Lockerbie.
   ``Initiatives have been taken to increase airport security, to
cooperate in law enforcement and bring the scourge of terrorism to
an end,'' Catto said.
   Mrs. Giebler, a member of the Victims of Flight 103 group, said
she came across the ceremony by chance.
   ``Not only is the U.S. government not doing enough to bring the
terrorists to justice, it is not keeping the relatives informed of
what went on,'' she said. ``I do not believe anything has been done
by the government to protect people flying today,'' Mrs. Giebler
said.
   The chief investigator, John Orr of the Strathclyde Police, has
said the plane was brought down by a bomb planted in a
radio-cassette player and detonated by an altitude-sensitive trigger.
   The device probably was put aboard the flight in Frankfurt, West
Germany, and transferred to the Boeing 747 during a stop at London's
Heathrow airport, Orr has said.
</TEXT>
