<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 2050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     06-07 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Floods Recede; Death Toll Reaches 315</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flood waters slowly receded Wednesday
in central and southern Sri Lanka after five days of storms and
mudslides that killed at least 315 people, officials said.
   Rescue workers carrying food and medicine Wednesday reached
stranded inland hill areas that were worst hit by the rains, which
began Saturday night, according to D.J. Wijesundera, of Colombo's
Social Service Department.
   More than 200,000 people were left homeless, including 60,000 who
were forced to flee Colombo's northern suburbs, Wijesundera said.
   The Kelaniya River, which winds north of the capital to the sea,
surged over its banks Tuesday, but dropped again by about an inch
Wednesday, according to Upali Delpechitra, of the Irrigation
Department.
   ``The waters are expected to recede very slowly,'' he said. Walls
of sand bags were put up along the river banks to protect villages
near Colombo, he said.
   Most of the deaths occurred in the hills and valleys of the
Kegalle district, about 45 miles northeast of Colombo. Entire
villages of thatched huts were buried after a torrential downpour on
Saturday triggered landslides of mud and rocks already loosed by a
month-long monsoon.
   Meanwhile, in Teldeniya, 60 miles northeast of Colombo, police
opened fire on students protesting the presence of Indian soldiers
on the Indian Ocean island. At least one person was killed and six
others were injured, when students tried to storm a police station,
police said.
   There are 40,000 Indian soldiers in Sri Lanka under a 1987 Peace
accord to end a 6-year-old Tamil separatist movement. President
Ranasinghe Premadasa last week asked India to withdraw its troops by
the end of July but New Delhi has refused.
   India became involved in the ethnic conflict of its southern
neighbor because of the sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils to
the rebel cause.
   Tamils are 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people. Tamils
say they are discriminated against by the majority Sinhalese, who
make up 75 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
