<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--MineDisaster     06-07 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Mine Disaster,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search For Trapped Miners Halted, Seven Still Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAVAO CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military officials Wednesday
called off a search for seven missing gold prospectors believed
trapped in makeshift mine tunnels during a landslide that killed at
least 13 people.
   There were no more signs of life inside the shafts that collapsed
on May 30 and continuous rains made further digging risky, according
to Brig. Gen. Mariano Baccay, the regional Philippine police chief.
   Baccay said five people had been rescued from the collapsed
tunnels on the slopes of Mount Diwalwal, a gold-mining community in
Davao del Norte province.
   Heavy rains caused a maze of tunnels on the mountain to collapse
and triggered a fire that razed at least 160 shanties of miners and
traders.
   Baccay said 13 bodies were recovered. He said 750 miners were in
the tunnels at the time of the accident but most made their way to
the surface through two large tunnels that did not collapse.
</TEXT>
