<FIRST>r i AM-China-ForeignMinister     06-07 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Foreign Minister,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Foreign Minister Needs Security on Arrival in Mexico</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Qian Qichen of China left for
Cuba Wednesday after an overnight stay protested by Mexicans angered
over soldiers' slaughter of student protesters in Beijing, news
reports said.
   About 40 demonstrators shouted at Qian when he arrived Tuesday
night at Benito Juarez International Airport, the Excelsior news
service.
   The news agency said he had been in Ecuador as part of an
official Latin America tour when troops killed hundreds of
pro-democracy demonstrators in China early Sunday.
   Excelsior said the minister, greeted by China's ambassador to
Mexico, was quickly surrounded by security officers who then whisked
him away in an embassy vehicle without taking questions from
reporters. His car was followed by eight Chinese embassy security
vehicles.
   He left at shortly after 6 a.m. Wednesday (8 a.m. EDT) for Cuba
on a commercial flight. Excelsior said the foreign minister was
scheduled to fly later in the day from Cuba to Houston.
   The Notimex news agency said Qian was to make a brief stopover in
Los Angeles later Wednesday en route to China.
