<DOCNO> AP890607-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1701EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Glance     06-07 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Glance,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summary of Developments in China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are developments in China Wednesday:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ARMY IN BEIJING</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Indiscriminate firing by soldiers in Beijing continued. Armed
patrols marched near Tiananmen Square and tanks and troops raced
along main avenues firing at random.
   Soldiers in one convoy chanted: ``We love the people, we love the
capital,'' then opened fire, scattering crowds. Several deaths of
citizens were reported.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>GOVERNMENT ANNOUNCEMENTS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   State television broadcast a statement from the Communist Party
threatening expulsion and severe punishment for any members found to
have ``plotted, organized and led the rebellion.''
   Another announcement said soldiers were authorized to ``forcibly
dispose of, on the spot'' anyone who resisted arrest.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FOREIGNERS EVACUATE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department ordered the evacuation from China of all
U.S. diplomatic dependents and non-essential personnel and is urging
all other Americans ``to leave at once.''
   Previously, the U.S. had urged U.S. citizens only to leave
Beijing.
   Foreign embassies were arranging flights for diplomatic and
civilian evacuees. However, a Soviet Embassy officer said there were
no plans for their personnel to leave.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MILITARY ACTION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of troops in trucks accompanied by tanks and armored
personnel carriers departed in two large convoys, heading east.
Their destination was not clear.
   No major battle between supposedly rival military units has taken
place, but a witness said the 27th and 38th armies fought each other
early Wednesday east of downtown.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DIPLOMATIC COMPOUND FIRED UPON</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers sprayed bullets at a diplomatic compound then surrounded
it in what they said was a search for a sniper. The compound was
sealed off for two hours and security officials took a Chinese man
away.
   U.S. Ambassador James Lilley protested to Chinese authorities
about rifle fire that broke windows at apartments occupied by U.S.
employees, but said there were no injuries.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OTHER CITIES AND PROVINCES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Turmoil spread to more than a dozen provincial cities, where
crowds blocked major roads and railways with barricades in
anticipation of military assaults.
   Six people manning a barricade were run over by a train near the
Shanghai railway station Tuesday night. Shanghai radio said angry
crowds set the train ablaze.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>US-CHINA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Chinese Foreign Ministry said the U.S. decision to stop arms
sales and military contacts was a ``detriment to bilateral
relations.''
   China condemned the United States for giving refuge in the U.S.
Embassy to dissident Fang Lizhi and said Washington was interfering
in China's internal affairs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WORLD REACTION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Governments and citizens worldwide continue to protest the
Chinese action with rallies, marches, and suspensions of exchange
programs.
   Hungary became the first Soviet bloc nation to denounce the
military crackdown in China.
   Taiwan announced it will end a 40-year ban on telephone and mail
links with China to help spread reports of the carnage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
