<FIRST>r a AM-Eastern-Counterfeiter     06-07 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Counterfeiter,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking Machinist Charged in Counterfeiting Scheme</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A striking Eastern Airlines baggage
handler who says he was struggling to make ends meet tried to sell
$250,000 in counterfeit money to an undercover agent, authorities
said.
   Joe Shaheen, 58, was arrested on conspiracy charges Monday along
with his brother and two other men. They were released Tuesday and
Wednesday on $50,000 bail.
   Shaheen and his brother John Peter Shaheen, 60, agreed to sell
the fake money to an undercover agent for $40,000, the Secret
Service said. The Secret Service said it is still investigating the
source of the money.
   In interviews before his arrest, Shaheen said he had fallen
behind on car payments, sent his wife to Boston to live with their
son and took in a boarder since the Machinists strike began March 4.
He collected $100 a week from the union strike fund but said he went
through his savings. He briefly held part-time jobs.
   ``Once they see Eastern Airlines on the application, they don't
want to hire. I applied for unemployment compensation, but was
rejected because of the union dispute,'' he told a federal
magistrate on Tuesday.
   Also charged were Pedro Fiallo, 26, who identified himself as a
professional gambler, and Frank Consalvo, 28, a partner in a
party-planning store.
   Wally Haber, a Machinists spokesman, said Wednesday that a
program had been set up for members with serious financial problems
caused by the 3-month-old strike.
   ``We've got food banks and we've got health and welfare money to
help needy cases,'' Haber said, noting members were advised for two
years to try and save money because of prospects for a strike or
sale of the airline.
   ``Most of our people, and I would say better than 90 percent, had
put some money away for a rainy day,'' he said.
</TEXT>
