<FIRST>r p AM-Pepper'sSeat 1stLd-Writethru a0673 06-07 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepper's Seat, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0673,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Martinez Sets Special Election Dates for Pepper's Seat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts one graf after the 7th, ``Gordon, 67, to update with
added candidate.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Rancho Seco Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Cuban-born Republicans launched bids Wednesday
to become the first from Miami's exile community in Congress, but
the Democratic Party's leader said the battle for the late Claude
Pepper's seat could start turning the GOP tide.
   State Sen. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, an educator elected in 1982 as
the first Hispanic woman in the Florida Legislature, and
conservative businessman Carlos Perez, once hailed by President
Reagan as an example of the American dream, announced in bilingual
news conferences they would run in the Aug. 1 Republican primary.
   National Democratic Chairman Ron Brown told reporters in
Washington the 18th District contest will be tough, but he said the
national party would contribute as much help as possible to the
Democratic nominee.
   Winning the Aug. 29 special election will signal a turning of GOP
momentum and help spark Democrats in the South, Brown said, calling
the region the ``backbone of the Democratic Party's tradition.''
   ``The perception that we are flat on our backs in the region is
false,'' said Brown.
   The Miami Herald reported Wednesday that state Sen. Jack Gordon
of Miami Beach, the most prominent name in a long list of potential
Democratic candidates, said he will seek the Democratic nomination.
Gordon, who had said earlier he would make a decision by Friday,
didn't immediately return telephone calls Wednesday.
   Gordon, 67, has been a spokesman for liberal causes during 16
years in the state Senate, and his participation in a rally against
U.S. aid to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels angered many Cuban and
Nicaraguan exiles. He is married to Washington Post writer Myra
MacPherson.
   Meanwhile, Jeff Allen, a Miami sports attorney and agent, said
Wednesday that he will be the only black candidate in the race. A
registered Republican, Allen said he was considering running as an
independent.
   Ros-Lehtinen, married to U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen, said she
would continue the district's tradition of ``a leadership which has
been based on a caring conscience and conservative convictions.''
   Pepper, who died May 30 after holding the seat 26 years from its
inception, was known as the last of the New Deal liberals.
   Asked if she would continue Pepper's programs, she said: ``I am
not Senator Pepper. I am Ileana Ros-Lehtinen. We have many common
values and many common philosophies. We have some differences.''
   She identified her priorities as bridging ethnic and social
differences, protecting Social Security, the war on drugs and crime,
a tough stand on Cuba and Nicaragua, and strong support for Israel.
   Perez called his announcement a show of his pride in his adopted
country.
   ``I feel very proud about the United States. I feel very proud of
being an American,'' Perez said.
   In his 1984 state-of-the-union address, Reagan told Perez's story
of coming to this country as a destitute immigrant and building a
multimillion-dollar banana importing business. Perez raised funds
for Reagan and formed a fund-raising committee for former National
Security adviser Oliver North.
   Pepper, with nationwide prestige, won every election for the
district since his first in 1962, with his closest race in the past
decade a 61-39 percent victory in 1984 over Cuban-American Ricardo
Nunez. He drew no opposition last year at age 88.
   The district's registration is 54 percent Democrat, down from 72
percent a decade ago. The district is a multi-ethnic mix that ranges
from inner-city black areas to retirement enclaves to Little Havana
to upscale suburbs. Estimates of the number of Hispanics in the
district range from 40 percent to nearly half.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
