<FIRST>r w AM-Cheney-NATO     06-07 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cheney-NATO,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Secretary Heading to NATO Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney left Washington
Wednesday for his second NATO meeting in three months.
   Cheney, whose first exposure to NATO since becoming defense
secretary March 17 came last month, when he attended a Nuclear
Planning Group session, flew to Brussels, Belgium, for Thursday's
start of a regular Defense Planning Committee meeting.
   He and his counterparts are to discuss the next steps in
furthering the conventional arms control proposal proferred by
President Bush at last week's NATO summit meeting.
   Cheney originally had planned to spend several days after the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization meeting visiting U.S. ships and
troops in Europe on a get-acquainted tour. He canceled those plans,
however, after deciding there were still too many matters requiring
his attention in Washington.
   The defense chief will return to Washington on Friday.
