<FIRST>u i AM-China-Foreigners 1stLd-Writethru a0707 06-07 0931</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Foreigners, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0707,0953</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Evacuees Tell Terrifying Stories of Escape</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf `Gasoline is...' with 5 grafs to UPDATE with
quotes from Frankfurt; picks up 11th, `One American...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreigners fleeing Beijing were returning to their
homes Wednesday with terrifying stories of the killings they saw and
the chaos they left behind.
   They flew to Tokyo, Hong Kong and other cities after several
countries ordered their citizens to leave the Chinese capital, where
soldiers have killed or wounded thousands of people in crushing a
pro-democracy movement.
   ``I saw a soldier's body, burned, hanging from the bridge. That
made me get the hell out of there,'' Australian tourist Jimie Reid
said in Hong Kong. He said people told him the soldier had killed
children and women.
   ``We were shot at by the tanks at the Peking Hotel doorway. They
were shooting at anything that moved,'' said Yves Robert, a French
tour guide, after arriving in Paris with a group of 40 tourists.
   ``I came out to the veranda of the Minzu Hotel to see what was
happening and gunfire from a tank hit the veranda about 50
centimeters (20 inches) above my head,'' Japanese businessman
Ryoichi Kikukawa said in Tokyo.
   Peter White, an English teacher from Ithaca, N.Y., got up before
dawn Wednesday to line up for a ticket on the same Japan Airlines
flight.
   As he was about to enter a taxi in front of his hotel, White
said, he threw himself to the ground because of gunfire from
soldiers, which shattered windows on upper floors. ``I think it was
their way of telling us to get back inside,'' he said.
   White expressed concern for 20 American friends, including a
pregnant woman, he believed were still in Beijing.
   In Frankfurt, Donald Pierre-Louis said: ``There's chaos, even
panic, at the airport. Everybody is trying to leave'' Beijing.
   Pierre-Louis, a 34-year-old a native of Haiti, arrived with his
wife Danielle and their two young children.
   He said they kept up with events by watching American cable
television at their hotel.
   ``They cut off our phones for nearly two days but for some reason
they left the television on,'' he said. ``The more we saw the more
afraid we got.''
   Carol Benedict, a graduate student at Stanford University who was
doing research in Beijing, said in Tokyo: ``Gasoline is a problem.''
She said her taxi driver said he had only enough for one more trip
``and all the gasoline stations are closed.''
   One American woman who arrived in Tokyo on Wednesday had been in
a dormitory where soldiers entered firing guns, killing a number of
students, according to her friends. She was too upset to talk to a
reporter.
   ``The airline offices were just two blocks from our hotel, but
with all the tanks out there and gunfire it was too long a walk to
risk,'' said Benedict.
   An American professor at Beijing University was stopped along
with eight other Americans in a van on the road to the airport by
Chinese soldiers who took their baggage, money, tickets and vehicle.
The group had to walk an hour further to the airport, the teacher
told Junichi Nagano, a Japan Airlines supervisor at Narita airport,
near Tokyo.
   Many others on China Airlines flight 925 also arrived in Tokyo
with no baggage or money, Nagano said.
   Ms. Benedict told of a group of seven American students who tried
to stick together in their efforts to escape, helped by a Japanese
student who found them airline tickets. But he could get them only
three tickets, and ``we had to leave the other four behind,''
Benedict said.
   ``The last we knew they were out on Changan Avenue trying to get
to the airline offices, but that was where the heaviest fighting was
going on. I don't know what happened to them,'' she said.
   She said the lack of reliable information was the main problem.
``It was very difficult to get phone calls through. People were
getting hysterical,'' said Benedict, who moved around trying to find
a safe spot in Beijing clutching a shortwave radio to get BBC
reports on what was happening in various parts of the city.
   ``There were hordes of people at the airport, it was hot and
humid, kids everywhere, people near panic, thinking `today I have to
get out at all costs,''' she said, adding that she heard loud booms
that sounded like artillery fire within range of the airport.
   Some embassies, under gunfire, seemed overwhelmed with the task
of evacuating their citizens, leaving some feeling stranded.
   ``The American embassy made it very clear that transportation
arrangements were up to us,'' said White, who said he was worried as
other embassies pulled out their students, leaving him at his
university as the last foreigner, with no clear directions from the
embassy whether to stay or leave.
   The U.S. embassy sent a convoy to bring American students to
safety Monday, but some students, unsure whether they were safer on
campuses, where army units were rumored to be preparing a strike, or
downtown where gunfire was already rife, stayed behind.
   Chinese cheered the American convoy of a half-dozen vehicles led
by a limousine flying an American flag, and flashed victory signs as
it wound through the city trying to find a safe route, Benedict said.
   ``Chinese people are clearly looking to the American government
and the American people for support, and that seems to put American
citizens at risk because the (Chinese) government will try to
suppress that kind of thinking,'' she said.
</TEXT>
