<FIRST>u w AM-Foley 2ndLd-Writethru a0716 06-07 0985</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foley, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0716,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley Says GOP Right, Democrats Too Pushy in House</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Foley, Edwards on ethics committee and bipartisanship,
subbing 9 grafs for grafs 7-11 pvs, He hopes ... House well.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New House Speaker Tom Foley said Wednesday that
Republicans are right in complaining Democrats have at times
overplayed their power as the majority party, and he vowed to wield
a gentler gavel.
   ``I think we've pushed it sometimes to the point where, while we
were still within the rules, we were making maximum use of the power
of the majority or the position of the majority,'' Foley said. ``I
don't think we should do that.''
   Foley, in his first full day as speaker, commented in an
interview with news service reporters.
   He specifically referred to an incident on Sept. 27, 1987, when
then-Speaker Jim Wright held open a House roll-call vote long enough
to get one Democrat to change his vote on a crucial budget bill and
provide the margin of victory. ``I think we went too far on that
day,'' he said.
   Foley's comment seemed to concede a point made a day earlier,
when he was sworn in before the full House, by Republican Leader
Robert Michel of Illinois. Michel said then, ``Thirty-five years of
uninterrupted power can act like a corrosive acid upon the
restraints of civility and comity.''
   In a wide-ranging interview, Foley also said:
   _He hopes to enact, before the year is out, legislation to reform
House ethics rules and campaign laws. Such legislation probably
would have to address the issues of honoraria, or speaking fees, and
a federal pay increase.
   He said the ethics committee's enforcement process is ``somewhat
awkward, to put it kindly,'' and suggested its duties be divided
between two panels _ one to determine whether to bring charges,
another to judge the merits of the case.
   But Foley said he did not think Congress was mired in ``a moral
swamp'' because of recent high-profile ethics cases involving his
predecessor, Wright, and No. 3 Democratic leadership official Rep.
Tony Coelho, both of whom have announced they will leave Congress.
   _As speaker, he will be a staunch supporter of civil rights and
civil liberties, and will be devoted to improving educational
opportunities in the United States. He said the nation is falling
behind countries such as Japan and South Korea in math and science
education, in particular.
   _A combination of tax increases and spending cuts will be needed
to bring the nation's deficit under control, but Democrats will not
on their own suggest a tax hike.
   Foley said such a tax recommendation would be ``an exercise in
futility for all of us'' since, if Congress sent a tax increase to
the White House, President Bush would likely ``shoot it twice and
throw it down the White House well.''
   _It is time to concentrate on governing. He decried political
operatives in both parties who he said spend their days searching
for confrontation and ``seem to want a sort of permanent election.''
He added that Americans don't want ``to make Washington a permanent
political battleground.''
   Meanwhile, Rep. Mickey Edwards of Oklahoma, chairman of the House
Republican Policy Committee, said if Foley is serious about
bipartisanship he should support a package of rule changes proposed
by the GOP five months ago. Democrats ``totally ignored the
proposals under Wright's leadership,'' he said.
   ``There is a new leader and Tom Foley has a different style,''
Edwards said, adding that Wright ``systematically excluded the
views, opinion, debate, amendments of people who disagreed with the
leadership, whether Democrats or Republicans.''
   Earlier, Foley went to the White House for his second meeting
with Bush in as many days, praising the president's willingness to
consult. He said the luncheon was largely social, although a few
issues coming before Congress soon were discussed generally.
   He brushed aside Republican criticism, including a Republican
National Committee memo that stirred considerable controversy.
   Early Wednesday, the GOP committee announced the resignation of
its communications director, Mark Goodin, who had written a memo
titled ``Tom Foley: Out of the Liberal Closet'' that compared
Foley's voting record to that of Rep. Barney Frank, an acknowledged
homosexual.
   Bush spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the president had been
``disgusted by this entire incident'' and had called RNC Chairman
Lee Atwater who had telephoned Foley to apologize.
   ``He repudiated the statement and apologized,'' Foley told
reporters at the Capitol. ``I accepted that,'' along with a promise
that such attacks would not recur.
   Foley was sworn in as the House's 49th speaker on Tuesday to
replace Wright, who stepped down after the ethics committee lodged
charges of financial impropriety.
   Foley and House GOP Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., went to the
White House for lunch with Bush, and Foley sought to focus attention
on legislative matters the House is taking up or will soon consider.
   Foley called the meeting with Bush a sign of a budding
cooperative spirit between the executive and legislative branches
and between the parties.
   ``The president is seeking opinions,'' he said, specifically
referring to clean air legislation. ``It's another example of this
president's willingness to consult fully.''
   Foley also sought to refocus attention on the Democratic agenda
of social issues, mentioning child care, health care, and an
increase in the minimum wage. ``That's what the American people
elected the Congress to address,'' he said.
   Foley appointed Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., to be acting majority
leader until next Wednesday, when the Democrats will fill the No. 2
leadership post as well as the No. 3 slot of majority whip.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., is favored to replace Foley as
majority leader, but is opposed by Rep. Ed Jenkins, D-Ga. There is a
three-way race for whip, the post Coelho is vacating because of his
own ethics controversy. Reps. William Gray, D-Pa., David Bonior,
D-Mich., and Beryl Anthony, D-Ark., are seeking that post.
</TEXT>
