<FIRST>r i AM-EastGermany-Arrests     06-07 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany-Arrests,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest More Than 120 Pro-Democracy Demonstrators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German police broke up a pro-democracy
demonstration Wednesday and arrested more than 120 people protesting
alleged election fraud by communist authorities.
   An Associated Press reporter saw massive security forces move
against about 300 demonstrators, many carrying banners, outside a
church in downtown East Berlin.
   The demonstration was organized by the Lutheran Church, and the
protesters were mostly young people and students. The group planned
to march from Sophie's Church to the government headquarters to
deliver a petition protesting the alleged election fraud, church
sources said.
   The protesters accused communist authorities of election fraud
during the May 7 nationwide municipal elections. Only unopposed
Communist Party candidates ran, and church officials say authorities
did not report all the ``no'' votes.
   Security forces tried to prevent Western reporters from filming
the demonstration, hit some of them and ordered them to leave the
area around the church.
   Michael Passauer, a priest in the church, said he had been
promised by authorities that the 120 arrested would be released
during the night after their names had been taken down.
   Church sources also said police arrested 16 people carrying
flowers and wreaths to on the Chinese Embassy late Tuesday to
protest the military attack on unarmed citizens in Beijing. The
protesters were charged with disorderly conduct and threatening
public order.
   East Germany is one of Eastern Europe's most rigidly controlled
societies, and its state-run media have expressed support for the
military crackdown in Beijing.
</TEXT>
