<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 2113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DefenseConsultants     06-07 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Consultants,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Says Military Using Consultants for Wide Range of Services</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional investigators said Wednesday that
the Air Force is relying on outside consultants rather than its own
personnel to determine the cost of the $6.8 billion system of
rail-garrison MX missiles.
   Officials from the General Accounting Office, an investigating
arm of Congress, told a House panel that the Army, Navy and Air
Force use consultants for a wide range of services.
   The total number, however, is likely higher than the agency found
because the definition of consultant varies and many contractors do
not report whether consultants worked on certain programs,
investigators said.
   The House Armed Services subcommittee on investigations,
responding to last summer's ``Operation Ill Wind'' investigation of
military purchasing fraud, had asked the agency to look into the
Pentagon's use of consultants.
   The GAO studied one weapon system from each of the three services
_ the Army's $3.2 billion Fiber Optic Guided Missile program; the
Navy's V-22 Osprey, a $26 billion tilt-rotor aircraft program, and
the Air Force's system to deploy the land-based, nuclear MX missile
on railroad cars.
   The Ballistic Systems Division, which manages the MX program,
awarded 15 contracts worth about $99 million for support services
during fiscal 1987 and 1988, said Harold J. Johnson, director of
manpower issues in the GAO national security and international
affairs division.
   The support contractors provided cost estimates, reviews of
contractor logistic support plans and helped determine system and
component specifications.
   The GAO report prompted Rep. Nicholas Mavroules, D-Mass.,
chairman of the subcommittee, to question who estimates the cost of
the MX rail-garrison _ the Air Force or the consultants hired by the
service.
   ``The best we can tell it's the consultants that they have hired
do the estimating. The Air Force reviews and approves,'' Johnson
said.
   ``Who are the experts _ the consultants or the people we have in
the Air Force?'' Mavroules said.
   Johnson said the Air Force has told the agency that ``the
contractor in this case has the institutional memory and the
expertise.''
   The Massachusetts Democrat also expressed dismay over the
Pentagon's inability to keep track of the consultants, the absence
of a specific definition of the term consultant and the possibility
that these problems could result in incidents of
conflict-of-interest.
   Allan Burman, deputy administrator and acting administrator in
the Office of Federal Procurement Policy, said his agency has come
up with a policy letter on conflict-of-interest that will require a
60-day comment period.
   Nevertheless, Mavroules was angered by the absence of a tracking
system for consultants.
   ``What in God's name is so difficult? Why is this a hot potato
that when we ask the question we cannot get an answer? Is the
bureaucracy that great?'' Mavroules said, his voice rising.
   ``You categorize, you prioritize, you have certain numbers of
people working for the government. You have a defense industry
you're in touch with everyday. Don't they have an obligation to give
to you the proper information with regard to that question. I want
to know. I have a right to know. The American people have a right to
know. Why can't I get that from you?'' the congressman said.
   Burman said that with the number of broad categories it is
difficult for consultants looking at those categories to determine
whether they are part of the process.
   ``It's very difficult for us to get any kind of consistency,'' he
said.
   Col. John P. Wilhelm, acting director of the Defense Department's
Advisory and Assistance Services for the past two years, told
Mavroules that there is ``no incentive to report this information
because what happens if they don't report it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
