<FIRST>r w AM-Export-ImportBank     06-07 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Export-Import Bank,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Due to Announce New Head of Export-Import Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is expected to announce the
appointment soon of John D. Macomber as president of the U.S.
Export-Import Bank, which subsidizes loans overseas for buying
American goods, government officials said Wednesday.
   The officials spoke on condition they not be identified.
   The bank competes with similar government organizations in other
industrial countries, especially Japan, France, Britain and Canada.
   Macomber, 61, is chairman of J.D. Macomber &amp; Co., a private
investment firm. He was head of Celanese Corp. when it was acquired
by Hoechst AG of West Germany in 1987.
   A graduate like Bush of Yale University, he chairs the advisory
board of its School of Management and is a director of several
companies in Europe and the United States.
   The bank has lost money in recent years because it made many
loans at lower interest rates than it had to pay for the money in
the first place.
   It has also come under criticism from the General Accounting
Office because it continues to list among its assets loans it made
long ago to Cuba and China. These loans have been repudiated by Cuba
and China.
   The bank nevertheless has strong support in Congress because of
the business supported by its billions of dollars in loans since
1934.
