<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writehru,a0640,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Destroys Two Gaza Strip Houses, Collaborator Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 18th graf `Troops shot...' with 1 graf to UPDATE with two
more wounded. Pickup 19th graf `The army said...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIT LAHIA, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army on Wednesday blew
up the home of a Palestinian youth convicted of throwing firebombs
and said it wanted to instill fear in other Arab protesters.
   Also Wednesday, a Palestinian suspected of collaborating with
Israel was hacked to death with a hatchet and his naked body chained
from an electricity pole in the West Bank city of Nablus, Arab
reports said.
   The army confirmed the slaying and said police were
investigating. The dead man was identified as 30-year-old Ziad Abu
Ras, the 48th suspected collaborator killed by fellow Arabs since
the uprising began.
   At least 509 Palestinians have been killed since uprising against
Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip began in December
1987. Twenty-two Israelis also have died in the violence.
   In an unusual move, the army invited reporters to this Gaza
village of 13,000 to witness a house demolition.
   The United States and human rights organizations have condemned
house demolitions, saying they constitute collective punishment and
deny people due process.
   According to the Al Haq-Law in the Service of Man human rights
group on the West Bank, the army has destroyed or sealed more than
330 houses in the West Bank and 58 in the Gaza Strip since the start
of the uprising.
   Army spokesman Lt. Col. Hanan Rubin said the army wanted to
publicize the action so ``they (Palestinians) will see and fear.''
   The home was the residence of 17-year-old Bassam Shaaban Ibrahim
Mukasi, who was convicted in a military court of leading Molotov
cocktail attacks on Israeli troops in a nearby refugee camp, Rubin
said. No one was injured in the attacks, he said.
   A deafening explosion sent debris flying high in the air and
showered the rocks that held the tin roof on neighboring houses. The
owners of several nearby houses said their windows were shattered by
the blast and debris.
   The house, which was home to 17 people, was reduced to rubble in
a matter of seconds.
   Mukasi's father, Shaaban, told The Associated Press that
destroying his house was ``a crime.''
   ``If they think by demolishing my house they will scare me, then
they are dealing with the wrong person,'' he said.
   He added: ``I am going to live in a tent. I will continue my
fight.''
   The army also bulldozed the Beit Lahia home of 19-year-old Akilan
Suleiman Bamilat, who also was convicted in the firebomb attacks,
Rubin said.
   Reporters were not invited to watch the bulldozing.
   The house demolitions came as the army confined the 700,000
Palestinians of the Gaza Strip to their homes for the fourth
straight day.
   Israeli troops shot and wounded 15 Palestinians during clashes
Wednesday in the occupied territories, Arab reports said. One of the
injured, a 19-year-old from Jabaliya refugee camp in Gaza, was in
critical condition with a bullet wound in the head, hospital
officials said.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
   In the West Bank town of Hebron, a confrontation between a Jewish
settler and several Palestinian women kicked off a melee that ended
when an Arab-driven car crashed, seriously injuring the driver and
hurting a passenger.
   The settler, Anat Cohen, told Israel radio that ``There was a
group of Arab women who cursed us, so I asked them to apologize.
They refused, and I hit one.''
   Nearby, the Arab-driven car turned around. Settlers told the
radio it attempted to run Ms. Cohen down, but Arabs said the driver
lost control when he was hit by rubber bullets fired by a soldier.
   Ms. Cohen was struck by the car, treated for minor leg bruises
and released.
   In the town of Qalqilya to the north, masked Arab youths
seriously injured a 45-year-old Palestinian woman and her
17-year-old daughter who were accused of aiding Israeli authorities.
The women were beaten with clubs and chains and stabbed with a
knife, Arab reports said.
</TEXT>
