<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-US     06-07 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-US,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Embassy Will Stop Issuing Visas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Embassy said Wednesday it
will stop issuing visas because results of May 7 elections were not
respected.
   Non-immigrant visas will not be issued after Friday, an embassy
statement said. Immigrant visas will be processed through July, it
said.
   ``These measures were considered necessary because the regime of
(Gen. Manuel Antonio) Noriega brutally ignored the will freely
expressed by the Panamanian people,'' an embassy statement said.
   It said the visa service was being stopped so embassy consular
personnel could use their time ``to protect the interests of United
States citizens.''
   Panamanians and others who need visas for the United States will
have to obtain them in consulates in third countries, it said.
   The embassy will continue to issue visas for other foreign
diplomats in Panama, it said.
   International observers say Noriega, who as head of the Defense
Forces is the country's de facto leader, rigged the election in
support of his candidate, then ordered its results annulled when the
fraud became obvious.
   The three opposition presidential and vice presidential
candidates were beaten by government thugs after the election.
   The United States has been pressuring for Noriega's ouster since
February 1988 when he was indicted on federal drug trafficking
charges in Florida and engineered the ouster of President Eric
Arturo Delvalle.
</TEXT>
