<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Military Posts in Nine Towns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas attacked nine
military posts early Wednesday and claimed to have killed or wounded
six police in a raid on a coffee processing plant.
   The army confirmed the attacks on its outposts and said the only
casualty was a civilian wounded at San Miguel de Mercedes, 47 miles
north of the capital in Chalatenango province.
   A broadcast on Venceremos, the clandestine rebel radio, said
guerrillas damaged the plant, an electrical substation and a
warehouse of the coffee-processing operation at Chalchuapa in Santa
Ana province, 48 miles northwest of San Salvador.
   An Associated Press reporter who visited the scene found only the
warehouse damaged. A plant employee said the rebels launched 14
grenades but did not fire their rifles and there were no casualties.
   Venceremos also reported fighting in the eastern provinces of
Usulutan and Morazan, and in San Vicente in central El Salvador.
   The army said guerrillas killed five civilians they accused of
collaborating with the army.
   An estimated 70,000 people, most of them civilians, have been
killed since the civil war began nine years ago.
