<FIRST>r i AM-Kenya-Detainees     06-07 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kenya-Detainees,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freed Detainees To Pursue Suits Against Kenya Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY CHEGE MBITIRU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cabinet minister on Wednesday reproached
three men who plan to pursue suits against the state for wrongful
confinement and torture after being detained for more than a year
without trial or charge.
   Foreign Affairs Minister Robert Ouko said that David Mukara
Ng'ang'a, a former lecturer in political science at the University
of Nairobi, and lawyers Wanyiri Kihoro and Kariuki Mirugi failed to
appreciate the pardons granted them by President Daniel arap Moi.
   ``Defiance is not the way to respond to magnanimity,'' Ouko said.
``They should abandon those intentions and express gratitude to the
president.''
   The three were among seven detainees freed June 1 and June 6. Moi
said no more political prisoners remained in Kenyan jails, a
contention disputed by Amnesty International, the London-based human
rights organization.
   Amnesty says at least 60 political prisoners are still held
following court convictions based on tainted confessions.
   The four others freed were Raila Odinga, son of former Vice
President Oginga Odinga; business executive Israel Otieno Agina;
Richard Obuon Guya, a former air force private, and Samuel Okumu
Okwany, who was implicated in a trial of people charged with seeking
guerrila warfare training in Libya.
   All seven were arrested between 1986-88 in a government crackdown
on clandestine groups allegedly plotting Moi's overthrow. They were
imprisoned under the Preservation of Public Order and Security Act,
which permits indefinite confinement without trial or charge.
   Kihoro, Ng'ang'a and Mirugi first filed suits against the state
in 1987 and 1988, alleging torture and challenging their detention.
   Their lawyer, Gibson Kamau Kuria, was arrested the day after he
filed the 1987 suits and spent eight months in detention. Kuria told
The Associated Press he is pursuing the cases.
</TEXT>
