<FIRST>u w AM-Senate-Gregg     06-07 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Gregg,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republicans, Democrats Agree on Procedure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Feuding Democrats and Republicans reached
agreement Wednesday to clear the way for a committee vote on the
controversial nomination of Donald Gregg to be ambassador to South
Korea, a key participant said.
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., said Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.,
who has spurred an investigation by the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee into Gregg's alleged links to the Iran-Contra affair,
agreed to schedule a vote for June 20 if the Bush administration
produces all requested documents and information by June 16.
   As a result, McConnell said, he is calling off a one-day
Republican boycott of committee meetings, thus permitting the panel
to act on this and other key nominations as well as a pending $2.5
billion State Department authorization bill.
   ``If the administration doesn't produce the documents, obviously
the deal would be off,'' McConnell said.
   But he said State Department officials who were present at his
meeting with Cranston promised that the material would be produced
by the deadline.
   McConnell said he obtained a written agreement that the vote on
Gregg will be held, even if Cranston is not satisfied with the
materials he recieves.
   ``If he isn''t satisfied, then he can use that as an argument to
vote against the nomination,'' McConnell said. ``But there still
will be a vote.''
   Cranston, meanwhile, will question Gregg under oath for a second
time at a hearing to be held on June 15.
   Cranston and other senators are suspicious of Gregg's contacts
with former national security council official Oliver L. North and
other Iran-Contra figures in 1985 when Gregg served as Bush's vice
presidemntial national security adviser.
   The questions central to the investigation are:
   _Did Gregg help North illegally resupply the Nicaraguan Contra
rebels with military aid?
   _Is he lying about it now?
   Gregg maintains he had no role in supplying the Contras and that
he is telling the truth about what he did and did not do. He has
said he wants to use the hearings to clear the air and remove all
suspicions about his conduct.
   McConnell said he led the Republican boycott of the committee on
Wednesday to prevent committee action on nominations and legislation
because he feared Gregg was being railroaded.
   ``This nomination has been up here since early March and I've
told Sen. Cranston that I thought they were trying to kill the
nomination with delays,'' McConnell said. ``What I was unwilling to
see continue was the effort to kill the nomination with delays and
leaks.''
   McConnell said he is optimistic that the Gregg nomination can
still be approved.
   ``But I think this has been made into a partisan matter so we'll
have to wait and see,'' he said.
   The end of the GOP boycott apparently will permit votes Thursday
morning on the State Department bill and nominations of Bernard
Aronson to be assistant secretary of State for Latin American
Affairs, John Kelly to be assistant secretary of State for Middle
Eastern and South Asian Affairs and former Sen. Chic Hecht, R-Nev.,
to be ambassador to the Bahamas.
</TEXT>
