<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 2018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-BabyBirds     06-07 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby Birds,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baby Birds, Eggs Saved From Destruction in Bridge Construction Zone</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Carrol in 3rd graf cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARREN MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUTCHINSON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adult barn swallows and cliff swallows
swooped and screeched Wednesday as two biologists carefully removed
seven newborn birds and about 120 eggs from nests under two bridges
scheduled for demolition.
   The birds and eggs found in about 60 nests had to be removed
under provisions of the U.S. Migratory Bird Act before the bridges
could be torn down, said state Department of Transportation
spokeswoman Cheryl Plathe.
   The two species are extremely abundant birds but are covered
under the act, as are all migratory birds, said Carrol Henderson of
the state Department of Natural Resources.
   ``We're doing this to fulfill the federal requirements,'' said
Plathe. ``We hope we don't have to do this to every bridge in the
future.''
   As the nests were demolished, the adult birds flew around the
area frantically.
   ``They don't like their homes being torn down. But it's something
we have to do to give the public a better ride,'' said Bill Langston
of the Transportation Department.
   The $2.6 million road project includes two new, wider bridges and
repaving of about seven miles of state Highway 22 about 60 miles
west of Minneapolis near Hutchinson.
   Construction engineers watched as the biologists, working as
volunteers, removed eggs and bird babies before tearing the nests
from the underside of the steel bridges over the Crow River and
scraping remaining mud and straw from the bridge.
   The babies and eggs were taken to the University of Minnesota's
Wildlife Rehabilitation Clinic in St. Paul for nursing and
incubation.
   However, the chance of survival for the newborns was slim, as was
the chance the eggs would hatch after being disturbed, said Linda
Wolf, a clinic biologist who helped in the removal.
   ``If we get 10 healthy hatches out of the eggs, I'd be
surprised,'' Wolf said.
   The baby birds, each only about an inch long and not yet
feathered, will require feeding by hand every 20 minutes from dawn
to dusk by volunteers using tiny syringes, Wolf said.
   While efforts are being made to save their young, the adult
swallows will be looking for a place to build new nests and should
lay another set of eggs in two to three weeks, Wolf said.
   Swallows can build new nests in about three days, Plathe said, so
contractors will have to knock any new nests from the bridges until
they're torn down. One bridge was scheduled for demolition Thursday,
the other in two weeks.
   ``In the future, we have to determine how to keep birds from
nesting under bridges,'' Plathe said.
   ``We should have been out here this spring and hosed them off
before they laid their eggs. But we didn't and they're here, so
that's why we're doing this,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890607-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 2021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Marcos     06-07 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surgery Improves Marcos' Abdominal Pain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgery eased abdominal pain and a persistent
fever plaguing Ferdinand Marcos, but the ousted Philippine president
remained in very critical condition Wednesday, a hospital spokesman
said.
   ``It's not like this was the only source and now the infection is
gone, but there was some response to the treatment and the pain and
the fever appears to have decreased,'' said Eugene Tiwanak, a St.
Francis Medical Center administrator.
   Marcos, 71, underwent three hours of emergency, exploratory
surgery Tuesday in which doctors drained a pancreatic abscess
considered a source of a bacterial infection complicating treatment
of his widespread organ failure.
   Marcos suffered cardiac, kidney and pulmonary failure May 18, and
since has been in very critical and unstable condition. The pancreas
helps break down food and produces hormones necessary to regulate
the body's metabolism.
   The exiled leader remained on life-support equipment Wednesday,
including a respirator to regulate his breathing, Tiwanak said,
adding that Marcos also undergoes hemodialysis four times a week to
cleanse his body of wastes.
   His medical team has been instructed to take any measure to keep
Marcos alive. Aides said the ousted leader's mind remains clear and
that he makes his own decisions.
   ``Just because he can't talk, he can't breathe, doesn't mean he
can't think,'' said adviser Arturo Aruiza, adding that Marcos agreed
to the surgery.
   Tiwanak said no further surgery was planned and doctors had not
determined whether the abscess was a major source of the infection.
   Marcos has lived in exile in Honolulu since a popular revolt
catapulted Corazon Aquino to the Philippine presidency three years
ago.
   Aquino, widow of assassinated Marcos foe Benigno Aquino, has
repeatedly denied the pleas of Marcos and his wife, Imelda, to
return home.
   Both Marcoses are under U.S. indictment for allegedly stealing
more than $100 million from the Philippine treasury and stashing it
in the United States.
   However, a federal judge severed Marcos from the case, meaning he
will not be prosecuted unless he recovers, and no trial date has
been set for Mrs. Marcos, who pleaded innocent to the charges and is
free on $5 million bail.
   Marcos has been hospitalized since Jan. 15 and doctors said it
was a ``miracle'' he has survived so long.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890607-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 2032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-SpendingBill 1stLd-Writethru a0724 06-07 0770</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spending Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0724,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Passes Supplemental Spending Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOPS with 8 new grafs with final passage of bill; picks up 5th
graf pvs: ``Massachusetts Rep.''; SUBS 14th graf: ``McCain's amendment,''
to CORRECT Wednesday to Tuesday; SUBS penultimate graf: ``The House,''
to CORRECT anti-drug spending to $822 million sted $822,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate passed legislation on Wednesday
speeding $3.3 billion to veterans programs and a host of money-short
federal agencies, setting up potentially difficult talks with a
House that passed a different version of the bill.
   Senators approved the bill on a voice vote on the fourth day of
debate.
   Final passage came after lawmakers refused to delay for one year
much of the new Medicare catastrophic health care program for the
elderly. The bill now goes to a conference committee with the House,
which passed its version last month, to iron out differences before
the bill goes to the president.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., had led a fight to postpone parts of
the program, including a surtax on senior citizens that has drawn
complaints because of its cost.
   His effort was defeated 51-49 on a procedural vote in which he
was opposed by leaders of both parties.
   Lawmakers, however, did adopt by voice a non-binding provision
offered by the leaders calling on Congress to consider making
changes in the catastrophic care program in future legislation.
There is widespread agreement that the surtax will likely collect
more money than expected, but disputes remain over whittling down
the levy.
   ``Certainly most Americans would rather not have to pay anything
and receive the benefits,'' said Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole,
R-Kan. ``That's the American way. But we're broke.''
   Earlier, across the Capitol, four House members of both parties
joined members of veterans associations at a news conference to
accuse the Senate of delaying the legislation while senators attach
pet projects to it. The House approved the veterans money, $1.2
billion, on May 24.
   Massachusetts Rep. Silvio Conte, ranking Republican on the House
Appropriations Committee, said the Senate was holding the veterans
funds ``hostage to the pet projects of senators who have included
the veterans money in a Christmas tree of non-emergency
appropriations.''
   Chairman G.V. Sonny Montgomery, D-Miss., of the House Veterans
Affairs Committee complained that because of the delay, the
Department of Veterans Affairs was already ``gearing down'' some of
its operations.
   ``We've never hollered wolf about this situation at all,'' he
said.
   The spending bill, which President Bush first proposed as a $2.2
billion measure in March, contains money for health care,
compensation increases, and other programs for veterans.
   For want of the money, the veterans agency has begun limiting
out-patient care in less-serious cases, delayed opening new
facilities and halted many maintenance proects and equipment
purchases. The department annually treats around 3.5 million of the
nation's 27 million veterans.
   McCain's amendment, offered Tuesday, would delay for a year the
surtax people over age 65 must pay to help finance the catastrophic
care program. It would also postpone other important parts of the
program, including caps it places on senior citizens' doctors' bills
and a prescription drug benefit.
   Democrats had countered with an alternative calling for changes
to be considered in future legislation.
   The overall measure also contains $892 million for student loans,
$100 million to help refugees move to this country, and finances for
fighting forest fires, United Nations peacekeeping, unemployment
benefits, foster care, and other programs.
   The legislation has picked up a batch of amendments in the
Senate, including several of interest to particular lawmakers.
   One addition would protect a school district in Sumter County,
S.C., from sacrificing about $700,000 in federal aid this year it
would otherwise have to yield because of a loss of students covered
by an assistance program. The clause was sponsored by Sen. Ernest
Hollings, D-S.C., an Appropriations Committee member.
   The bill also contains $75 million to repair a radio telescope in
the home state of Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Robert
Byrd, D-W.Va.; orders the Army to spend $50 million to buy
cold-weather clothing made in 10 states; and sets aside $400,000 to
study last year's fires in Yellowstone National Park.
   The House also added its own favorite provisions to the bill.
These include: language easing the way for Alton, Ill., to lease
land on which it could build a public marina; allowing a $2.5
million increase in spending for cotton and tobacco grading; and
providing up to $360,000 for aviation research at the University of
Minnesota.
   The House bill also contains $822 million not in the Senate
measure for anti-drug programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
