<SECOND>AM-Newman-OPM,120</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Federal Personnel Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate approved Constance B. Newman
Wednesday s director of the Office of Personnel Management.
   The voice vote approval came a day after the Senate Governmental
Affairs Committee held hearings on her nomination.
   Newman, 53, is a career federal worker who started in government
as a clerk typist in the Interior Department and rose to become an
assistant secretary of housing and urban development.
   At her confirmation hearing Tuesday, Newman expressed concerns
about widespread drug testing for federal workers that had been
advocated by the Reagan administration. She said she believed drug
testing should be limited to cases where probable cause of abuse are
found and for workers in sensitive jobs such as air traffic
controllers.
