<FIRST>r p AM-NJGovernors     06-07 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NJ Governors,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Veteran Congressman Hit The Ground Running After Primary Wins</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0772 with `p' category code.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Rancho Seco</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two congressmen vying to succeed Gov. Thomas
H. Kean started hitting the campaign trail and each other Wednesday,
only hours after their primary victories.
   Democrat James Florio, a winner by 27,000 votes, was at commuter
train station by 7:30 a.m. and talking to more than 1,000 senior
citizens by lunch time. Nearly eight years ago he lost to Kean by
the narrowest margin in state history _ 1,797 votes out of 2.3
million cast.
   Republican James Courter used the day to appear with Kean, who's
still very popular among voters and is considered an important
political ally, even though he differs with Courter on key issues.
   Kean, barred by law from seeking a third consecutive term,
endorsed no primary candidate but filmed commercials for the
frontrunners that aired in a media blitz during the final weeks of
the primary.
   Also decided in New Jersey on Tuesday was a bitter primary for
the Democratic mayoral nomination in Plainfield, where City
Councilman Harold Mitchell upset Mayor Richard L. Taylor by a
198-vote margin, 2,172 to 1,974.
   Taylor, elected mayor in 1985, and Mitchell, a 7-year councilman,
head two factions of the city's Democratic party for years. Their
primary fight this year was the most public show of animosity
between the two popular politicians.
   At one point, both submitted to urine tests to fend off
allegations that they consorted with drug dealers.
   Courter, a conservative who comes from a wealthy family and the
Republican-rich northwestern part of the state, is expert on foreign
affairs and gained national attention as a member of the Iran-Contra
committee.
   Florio, the son of a Brooklyn shipyard worker, has a formidable
political base in southern New Jersey and a national reputation as
an environmentalist.
   Courter said Florio has amassed a ``big spending'' voting record
in Washington and established himself as the head of machine
politics in Camden.
   Courter also backed away from his ``no new taxes'' primary
campaign platform, and said if he ever had to raise taxes it would
be ``only as a last resort'' but he would ``bend over backwards'' to
avoid a tax increase.
   Florio picked up a favorite theme of Courter's Republican primary
opponents and condemned Courter's free-market plan to lower
insurance rates by deregulating the industry.
   While saying political labels serve no purpose, Florio termed
Courter's call for deregulation so politically conservative it was
``off the charts of reasonability.''
   Both candidates promised to spell out where they differ from one
another, and said voters will have some clear choices.
</TEXT>
