<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 2114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-CatastrophicHealth     06-07 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catastrophic Health,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Rejects Move to Delay Catastrophic Act Benefits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate narrowly rejected a proposal
Wednesday to delay the start of major provisions of Medicare's new
catastrophic health care coverage, a proposal opponents argued would
have effectively killed the new benefits.
   Reacting to criticism from senior citizens opposed to paying an
income tax surcharge to help pay for the program, backers of the
delay proposal argued that it was unfair to put roughly two-thirds
of the cost of the program on roughly one-third of retired Americans
with enough income to make them subject to income taxes.
   Those who voted against delaying the coverage maintained that
huge federal budget deficits make it impossible to provide new
benefits without providing a way to pay for them and that middle-and
upper-income retired Americans should foot a major share of the cost.
   The surtax could be as much as $800 a year for Medicare-eligible
retirees in upper income ranges.
   In the key vote, the Senate voted 51-49 against an attempt by
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., to kill an amendment by Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell of Maine that called on the Finance Committee
to review the program while benefits continue on schedule. Mitchell
introduced his amendment as a substitute to McCain's proposal to
delay provisions while a way to reduce the surtax is found.
   The Senate then quickly adopted by voice votes the Mitchell
substitute amendment and attached it to a pending supplemental
appropriations measure to pump $3.3 billion additional money into a
variety of federal programs for the current fiscal year.
   ``Nowhere in my amendment will you find the word repeal, but you
will find the word delay,'' McCain maintained. He termed the
Mitchell amendment a ``smokescreen'' that would not require Finance
Committee action and vowed to continue his fight to in order delay
in implementation of the surtax.
   Sen. Dave Durenberger, R-Minn., argued that approving McCain's
delay of some benefits would amount to repeal because it would send
a clear signal to the Finance Committee to let the program languish.
   ``We're going to get wisdom real quick and there is no way you're
going to get this back out of that committee,'' said Durenberger, a
member of the panel that crafted the catastrophic health act.
   The measure cleared the Senate last summer on an 86-11 vote and,
with similarly overwhelming House approval, was signed into law with
great fanfare by President Ronald Reagan who had proposed a more
modest and less expensive version.
   McCain was one of the 11 senators opposing the catastrophic
health measure last year.
   Opponents of the McCain attempt argued that an estimated 59
percent of the 32 million Medicare beneficaries do not have enough
income to qualify for income tax and would pay only $4 a month for
the additional coverage.
   They cited Congressional Budget Office estimates that 70 percent
of those eligible for Medicare would pay $100 or less a year in
additional surtaxes and that only 5.6 percent in upper income levels
would pay the maximum $800 tax.
   The catastrophic coverage took effect Jan. 1 with unlimited
hospitalization coverage after a once-a-year $560 deductible.
However, a $1,370 cap on out-of-pocket doctor bills does not kick in
until next year and a new prescription drug benefit begins a
three-year phase-in period in 1991.
   It was those benefits beginning next January that McCain wanted
to delay, along with the surtax _ or ``supplemental premium'' _ to
finance them. The surtax started this year to build up a trust fund
to pay the new benefits without dipping into the federal treasury.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
