<FIRST>r a AM-ChowchillaParole     06-07 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chowchilla Parole,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kidnapper of 26 Children Denied Freedom _ Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN LUIS OBISPO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of three men who kidnapped and
buried a bus full of schoolchildren in 1976 was denied parole
Wednesday.
   Richard Schoenfeld, 35, serving a life sentence at the California
Men's Colony here, is still a danger to society, a Board of Prison
Terms panel ruled in refusing the inmate's 10th plea for a parole
date.
   The panel's vote was 2-1: Deputy Commissioner Anthony Smith
argued that a date should be set, but far enough in the future to
exceed the prisoner's life span.
   The board turned aside a lengthy apology from Schoenfeld, who
said: ``I ask that you at least set a date so I can see a light at
the end of the tunnel.''
   He was convicted for his role in the kidnapping and abduction of
26 schoolchildren and their driver from the rural town of Chowchilla
in California's Central Valley for $5 million ransom.
   Schoenfeld, his brother, James, and Frederick N. Woods
commandeered the bus at gunpoint on July 15, 1976, and took it 100
miles to Livermore, outside San Francisco.
   There they shut the victims in a poorly ventilated moving van
buried in a quarry. It took the group 16 hours to dig to safety
through the wood- and earth-covered hole.
   All three inmates are serving life terms.
</TEXT>
