<FIRST>u a AM-RogersTrial     06-07 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rogers Trial,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Sentences Man To Death For Torture Killings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Prosecutor's name in 5th graf is cq. Note contents, especially
8th graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OREGON CITY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury Wednesday sentenced a 36-year-old
man to death for the torture slayings of six young women whose nude
bodies were found dumped on a remote hillside.
   Dayton Leroy Rogers, 36, shook his head repeatedly as Clackamas
County Circuit Court jurors were polled after 17 hours of
deliberations over two days. ``They didn't follow the rules,'' he
said.
   Judge Raymond Bagley Jr. then formally sentenced Rogers to die by
injection.
   The small-engine repairman, convicted of aggravated murder May 4,
is already serving a life sentence for stabbing a prostitute to
death in a suburban parking lot in 1987.
   ``We're happy justice was done,'' said prosecutor Andrejs Eglitis.
   Defense attorney Christoper Burris said Rogers' case, like all
death penalty cases, are appealed automatically to the state Supreme
Court.
   The six victims were known or suspected prostitutes ranging in
age from 16 to 35 whose bodies were found on a rural hillside near
Molalla about 30 miles southeast of Portland. All were stabbed
repeatedly in the back. Rogers was not charged in the death of a
seventh victim, who has not been identified.
   The feet were sawed from three of the bodies, and one victim was
sliced open from her pubic bone to her sternum.
   During the trial, several prostitutes testified that Rogers took
them to the Mollala area, bound their wrists and angles, and cut or
bit their feet and breasts.
   Aggravated murder is punishable by death or life in prison in
Oregon. To sentence Rogers to death, jurors had to unanimously find
the crimes were deliberate and that the defendant was likely to
commit violence again.
   Rogers' criminal history stretches back to 1972, when he stabbed
a 15-year-old girl with a hunting knife. The girl told police Rogers
proposed marriage to her immediately after the attack.
   Rogers served 27 months in prison between June 1979 and January
1982. He also spent nine months in the Oregon State Hospital in 1974.
</TEXT>
