<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-Violence 1stLd-Writethru a0757 06-07 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-Violence, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0757,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Police Clash With Mobs</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Updates with crowd swells to 4,000, 17 injured, changes throughout.
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A demonstration by car drivers protesting the
military crackdown in China turned violent early Wednesday as mobs
smashed shop windows and attempted to attack banks linked to
Communist China.
   Up to 4,000 people rioted in the Mongkok and Yaumatei districts
of Hong Kong's sister city of Kowloon, according to police.
   They said rioters hurled stones and bottles at police who
responded with tear gas. Seventeen people, including five policemen,
were injured, according to a police statement.
   It reported a procession of cars was traveling through the zone
with horns honking to protest the killings in China when an object
thrown from a building struck one of the vehicles. A crowd quickly
gathered and some people began rampaging through the streets,
setting fires in garbage cans, smashing windows and trying to break
into shops, witnesses said.
   The violence began shortly after midnight and when order was
restored before dawn the main Nathan Road throughfare was littered
with glass and charred rubbish.
   Government-owned Radio Hong Kong said some people in the crowd
wore black arm bands and shouted ``Down with Li Peng!'' the Chinese
premier.
   But Hong Kong Police Commissioner Ray Anning said the rioters
were not part of the main stream of people who have been
demonstrating daily in this British colony in support of Beijing
students demanding more democracy.
   He appealed to people who want to demonstrate their support for
the students to ``disassociate themselves from criminal and unruly
elements.''
   A local group supporting the pro-democracy movement in China
announced after the violence that it was cancelling all rallies and
a procession planned for Wednesday that it had scheduled as part of
a general strike.
   The Hong Kong Alliance was formed after up to 1 million people
joined in a march on May 21 to demonstrate support for the residents
of Beijing.
</TEXT>
