<FIRST>r i AM-Japan 1stLd-Writethru   06-07 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0756,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Figure in Recruit Scandal Freed on $1.4 Million Bail</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf, `Ezoe also...' to CORRECT former company of Hisashi
Shinto.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former chairman of Recruit Co., the central
figure in the bribery scandal that has rocked Japanese politics, was
released Tuesday on bail of $1.4 million, officials said.
   Hiromasa Ezoe, 52, spent 113 days in custody after his arrest in
February on charges of bribing former Nippon Telegraph and Telephone
Corp. executives Ei Shikiba and Hisahiko Hasegawa.
   Ezoe was the last person to be released from among the 12 people
indicted and arrested in the scandal. Bail for the others ranged
from the equivalent of $35,200 to $209,800, said Akira Saito, Tokyo
District Court spokesman.
   Ezoe also was charged later with offering cut-rate stock shares
to Hisashi Shinto, former chairman of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone
Corp., ex-Vice Education Minister Kunio Takaishi, former Chief
Cabinet Secretary Takao Fujinami, former Parliament member Kasuya
Ikeda and ex-Vice Labor Minister Takashi Kato.
   Recipients of the stock shares were charged with receiving bribes
and have been freed on bail.
   Ryutaro Hashimoto, the new secretary general of the governing
Liberal Democratic Party, told a news conference Tuesday his
political support group had received but did not report about $1.1
million in donations in April 1985, including $2,820 from Recruit
Co., an information and publishing conglomerate.
   Hashimoto said Friday he had received $14,000 in donations in
1986 from Recruit.
   He said Tuesday he had not intended to conceal the 1985 donations
and apologized for not having properly supervised his secretaries
who he said had handled the transactions.
   Hashimoto was appointed to the party post as part of the
administration of new Prime Minister Sousuke Uno.
   Former Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita and his Cabinet resigned
Friday in an attempt to clear the stains of the bribery scandal from
the Liberal Democrats.
   The scandal surfaced last summer when the newspaper Asahi Shimbun
reported that the deputy mayor of a city near Tokyo had received
bargain-priced stocks from Recruit in exchange for favors to the
company.
   In the following months investigations showed that Recruit
provided cut-rate stock to about 160 politicians, bureaucrats and
businessmen and gave large donations to some politicians and their
organizations in an alleged attempt to buy influence.
</TEXT>
