<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv09   06-07 0823</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 09,0849</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, June 9 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Southern Baptist Candidates Partly Agree, But Not Mainly</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Both say that they want to cool it, to stop the battling. Both
take a fundamentalist view of the Bible. Both affirm friendship. But
they're poised for a fight over the nature of Southern Baptists.
   Both claim to represent the genuine Baptist way, the authentic
heritage. But the two candidates for the denomination's presidency
disagree strongly about principles essential to that heritage.
   It's a conflict that has gone on for a decade in the nation's
biggest Protestant denomination, numbering l4.8 million. Its
presidency holds sway over makeup of its operating personnel.
   Filling that powerful top post is the key decision for the
denomination's convention June 13-15 in Las Vegas determining
whether fundamentalists will keep the office for an 11th straight
year.
   Their incumbent candidate, the Rev. Jerry Vines of Jacksonville,
Fla., seeks a second term, calling for peace in the ranks.
   ``I have made a conscious effort to create an atmosphere where
healing and reconciliation could occur,'' he says.
   His challenger, the Rev. Daniel Vestal of suburban Atlanta,
backed by moderates, also calls himself a peacemaker, a
``responsible reconciler, a bridge to call our people back
together.''
   While both speak of ``peace,'' however, both also declare their
adherence to differing positions on principles considered basic for
Baptists, involving the latitude of condoned doctrinal freedom.
   On that, Vines sets certain limits on what is acceptable,
primarily about the Bible but impinging on many other issues, while
Vestal insists on greater room for acceptable differences.
   ``We have certain parameters which are overwhelmingly accepted in
Southern Baptist life,'' Vines says, adding that he has confined his
appointments to those whose beliefs are within those approved
``parameters.''
   Vestal says this has clamped on ``a kind of tight control''
demanding allegiance to it. ``Our freedom is being threatened,'' he
says. ``It has to stop...or we are going to destroy this
denomination.''
   Vines, 51, a native Georgian, has been pastor of First Baptist
Church of Jacksonville, Fla., for the last seven years. Vestal, 44,
a Texan, led the First Baptist Church of Midland, Texas, for 12
years, before becoming pastor of suburban Dunwoody, Ga., Baptist
Church last fall.
   Weighing against Vestal's bid is a longtime convention custom,
unvarying in modern history, of always giving the incumbent a second
term. Vines also is riding a fundamentalist tide.
   Its appointive authority, surpassing that of any post in U.S.
Christianity, determines trustees that control the denomination's 26
agencies and institutions with budgets totalling about $400 million
annually.
   ``In my second year,'' Vines told Baptist Press, ``I would
emphasize building soul-winning churches, and I would like to lead
our convention to a renewed emphasis on church growth.
   ``We have settled the debate over the nature of Scripture. Now it
is time to move into a new era of growth in our local churches.''
   Vestal says that ``humanly speaking, it is not likely that I will
be elected, although I'm going to try.'' If he does win, he says he
would seek a limitation on presidential powers to ``de-politicize''
that office.
   ``The pattern of the last 10 years has been basically a
philosophy of winner-take all,'' he says. ``My philosophy would be
that the winner shares all.''
   Curiously, both Vines and Vestal espouse ``biblical inerrancy,'''
meaning Scripture is literally without error historically,
religiously or scientifically.
   However, Vines' policy has restricted appointments to persons
inside those ``parameters.'' Linked to the paramenters have been
various social positions such as against divorced personnel,
abortion or ordaining women.
   Vestal says his ``appointments would be from a different
perspective. I would include all Southern Baptists'' on both sides
of the prolonged conflict.
   He says that he himself is an ``inerrantist'' about the Bible,
but also is a ``centrist'' who accepts differing approaches under
the Baptist principle of the right of believers to interpret
Scripture as each understands it.
   Vines, seeking to deflect sharp conflict from the convention, has
asked the executive committee to postpone action on a highly
controversial proposal to establish a separate Washington, D.C.,
religious-liberty arm.
   It would be an alternative to the current agency in which nine
Baptist bodies cooperate, the Baptist Joint Committee on Public
Affairs. Fundamentalists have assailed it as not adhering to their
social agenda.
   Vines says he wants the matter deferred so the convention can
focus on evangelism and be ``as positive and united as possible.''
   Vestal, who has campaigned in church meetings in several states,
says he wants the convention to return to its ``time-honored
principles'' such as local church autonomy and ``priesthood of
believers'' emphasizing their equal rights.
   ``We have forsaken basic principles,'' he says. ``It is a power
or control issue, and Southern Baptists have got to resist it. We
have got to stand up and say enough is enough.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, June 9</NOTE>
