<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1423EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Connick Adv15   06-07 1102</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Connick, Adv 15,1141</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thu AMs, June 15 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Harry Connick Jr. _ A Young Pianist Praying For the Past</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICIA BIBBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harry Connick Jr., the young pianist whose music
has been rattling chandeliers at the city's swankier jazz joints,
planned to do just one thing before the biggest gig of his life, a
sold-out show at Lincoln Center.
   ``Pray,'' said the 21-year-old Connick.
   On the day of the concert, he'd sleep the day away, go to the
little Catholic church around the corner and ask for some divine
guidance.
   The day before the May 6 Lincoln Center performance, he's up
before dawn to appear on a morning TV news show. He'll be playing in
Washington that night. He's fighting a case of strep throat and,
since he sings during a good portion of his performances, he's
worried that his voice won't hold for the big show the following
night.
   ``Hopefully, I'll have my chops back,'' Connick says, rubbing his
throat with his huge hands. ``This is awful. It's like I can sing
but I have no control.''
   His Greenwich Village studio apartment is littered with tiny
throat lozenge wrappers, most of them crumpled in a pile on the
mantle of his grand piano, which takes up a good part of the space.
It's a gray day, and the studio is lighted only by the muted sun
streaming in the window. The only glow comes from Connick who beams
when he talks about his favorite topics: music and singing.
   Lately he's been practicing all night and, he says, ``praying is
the only thing that can help me now.''
   It's a tactic that's served him well. Relying on religion, in
part, brought him from a rich bog of musicial influences in his
native New Orleans to the splendor of New York's Alice Tully Hall at
Lincoln Center.
   He arrived in New York at age 18, got a room at the local YMCA
and within a month had a job playing the piano in a church. Then
another church in the Bronx needed a choir director. After that,
gigs at ``little dives here and there'' led to others; the joints
got classier, the pianos better tuned.
   Three years later, he has two albums out with Columbia Records _
the first called ``Harry Connick Jr.'' and the second ``20,'' as in
his age at the time. Earlier this year, he had a successful and
often sold-out run at the famed Algonquin Hotel.
   His repertoire relies heavily on nostalgia: Harold Arlen's ``If I
Only Had a Brain''; Hoagy Carmichael's ``Lazy River''; and Bart
Howard's ``In Other Words'' (also called ``Fly Me to the Moon'').
   Connick finds the whole notion of today's popular music
distressing.
   ``They don't understand,'' said Connick, his trademark slick
ash-blond hair bobbing back and forth, referring to no one in
particular and everyone in general who produces and performs trendy
tunes.
   ``There was just an innocence which is lost in American society
today. Can you imagine how nice it would have been, back in the
'40s? The innocence they had back then _ there is such a joyousness
about the music back then.''
   Still, his passion for the past leaves many puzzled.
   ``People always say, `Harry why do you do all those old songs?' I
would just run out of songs to play,'' Connick said of his first
days as a performer in New York when he'd be pressed to play for
hours on end.
   ``I would hear a song like `Somewhere Over the Rainbow,' by
Harold Arlen and I would say, `That sure is a pretty song. I'm going
to buy all his music.' Then I started reading his music and realized
he wrote `Come Rain or Come Shine,' `That Old Black Magic,' `It's
Only a Paper Moon' and a bunch of other songs that are really great.
   ``Not only lyrically are they wonderful to sing, but the melodies
are so perfect,'' Connick said. ``No one writes like that now.''
   He denies he's on a revival trip, and says his polished image _
big, pouty lips, slicked back short hair and loose-fitting suits _
isn't calculated.
   ``I didn't say, `What can I do to market myself? I got it! I'll
slick my hair back, wear baggy suits and sing songs from the 40s.'
Everything just happened coincidentally.''
   Not completely.
   Growing up near New Orleans' bohemian French Quarter with parents
who loved to indulge their boy's musicial aspirations, helped make
the package of Harry Connick Jr. what it is today.
   He made his first public performance when he was 5 for his
father's inauguration as the city's district attorney. ``I got up
there and I remember hearing that applause and I said, `I gotta have
more of that! Where can I get more of that?'''
   In his quest for a big, happy audience, he began to study a host
of musicial influences _ rhythm and blues, honky-tonk, bebop and
stride. Stride is a devilish piano style that requires one hand to
race across the keyboard at a furious speed while the other one
pounds away at a different tempo.
   He began to incorporate sounds from other artists including
Erroll Garner, Earl Hines, Duke Ellington, Thelonius Monk and Louis
Prima. Under the tutelage of jazz pianist Ellis Marsalis (father of
Wynton and Branford), Connick began to master bebop.
   The Marsalis family played a large role in Connick's young
career. Connick admits one of the reasons he moved to New York was
to be near his friend Wynton Marsalis, the Grammy-winning jazz and
classical trumpeter. Delfeayo Marsalis, Wynton's brother, produced
Connick's first album, which was recorded in one afternoon in
January 1987.
   But on this day, ballads were on Connick's mind. He said he'd
been listening to a piece by Frank Sinatra from the album ``In the
Wee Small Hours'' over and over again. He jumps up and plays it to
explain a nuance of the pain he hears in Sinatra's voice and how he
hopes to one day be able to sing a ballad as well.
   ``He's saying, `I get along without you very well, of course I
do.''' Connick said. ``He's being sarcastic.
   ``Now listen,'' he adds, reciting the lyrics along with the
music: ``Except when soft rains call and the drip of the leaves,
then I recall the thrill of being sheltered in your arms, of course
I do.''
   Connick stares off and gets a melancholy look in his eyes.
   ``These days they just don't understand,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, June 15</NOTE>
