<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-Silverman Adv23-25   06-07 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Silverman, Adv 23-25,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 23-25, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jonathan Silverman Stars As Opportunistic Rookie Salesman</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Jonathan Silverman was first offered his
role in the HBO movie ``Traveling Man,'' he loathed the character.
   ``I enjoyed the script but I couldn't see myself in it,'' he
said. ``It called for someone in his late 20s, cocky and a
Southerner. I read it again. I really hated Billy Fox.
   ``But the more I hated him the more I loved him. Then when I
heard John Lithgow was also going to play the older salesman I was
thrilled.''
   Billy Fox is a pushy, opportunistic young hustler ready to steal
his mentor's sales route out from under him in the HBO film,
premiering Sunday.
   Silverman is best known for playing ``nice Jewish boys,'' most
particularly Eugene Jerome in playwright Neil Simon's
autobiographical trilogy, ``Brighton Beach Memoirs,'' ``Biloxi
Blues'' and ``Broadway Bound.'' Silverman played the role on
Broadway, and in the movie version of ``Brighton Beach Memoirs.''
   ``Traveling Man,'' described as a combination of ``Death of a
Salesman'' and ``Tin Men,'' was written five years ago by David
Taylor. The crackerjack movie, with fine performances all around,
had kicked around so long, because it wasn't considered commercial
enough, until it was picked up by Home Box Office.
   Ben Cluett (John Lithgow) is a middle-aged salesman of industrial
foam in the deep South whose spectacular sales record hits a slump.
John Glover is the district sales manager with an evangelical fury
and a heart of stone. Glover induces Cluett to take along rookie
salesman Billy Fox to show him the ropes. What Billy has in mind is
to hang Cluett from the ropes and take over his lucrative route.
   Irvin Kershner (''The Empire Strikes Back,'' ``The Flim-Flam
Man'') directed. The movie was shot in Atlanta and New Orleans. It
also stars Margaret Colin as a caring woman Billy meets during Mardi
Gras.
   ``I've never played a character as shady or with such evil
intentions as Billy Fox,'' Silverman said during a break in shooting
his next movie, ``Sketches,'' also starring C. Thomas Howell and
Jason Bateman. ``He's a very complex character, but he has to come
across as naive and innocent until he sticks it to John Lithgow.
   ``He's thoroughly messed up Ben's life, but when Billy gets into
trouble Ben comes back and rescues him. John Lithgow's my idol. It
was a thrill to work with him, but it was difficult to yell at him
and hit him.''
   Silverman grew up in Beverly Hills and was 17 when he landed the
role in ``Brighton Beach Memoirs'' in 1983, replacing Matthew
Broderick.
   ``Working in `Brighton Beach Memoirs' was my first job and my
first time away from home,'' he said. ``I'd never intended to become
an actor. It was just something I'd done in high school. My passion
was playing baseball, and I went back and forth between baseball and
drama. An agent saw me in a school play and called me. I thought it
was a friend playing a joke. He sent me on an audition and that's
how I was cast in the play.''
   His other film credits include ``Stealing Home,'' ``Caddyshack
II,'' ``Girls Just Want to Have Fun,'' and ``Weekend at Bernie's.''
He was on the NBC series ``Gimme a Break'' in 1984-86. The producers
had a role written for him after seeing him on stage.
   In ``Weekend at Bernie's,'' which will be released in July,
Silverman and Andrew McCarthy play two insurance agents who stumble
across some information on a crime. They tell their boss, who turns
out to be the crook.
   ``The boss invites us to his beach house so he can have the Mafia
kill us,'' Silverman said. ``But they kill him instead, so it's two
guys with a body. There's a party going on in the house and no one
else is aware he's dead. It's a very black comedy.''
   What's next for Silverman? ``I'm being offered a lot of things,''
he said. ``I usually have to fight for things. This is a lovely
time. But I haven't decided yet what to accept.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 23-25</NOTE>
