<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Shatner Adv9-11-1stld-writethrub0878   06-07 1007</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Shatner, Adv 9-11-1st ld-writethru b0878,1029</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 9-11 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, ``Leonard Nimoy,'' to correct title of movie
he directed to ``The Good Mother.'' Movie opens June 9.</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Paramount Hopes For Another `Trek' Into Profits </HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The allure of ``Star Trek'' has long delighted
its followers and confounded its detractors. Star William Shatner
has an explanation.
   ``Is it possible that we're creating a mythology, that we touch a
mythological vein somewhere? The more I read and the more I think
about it, I wonder if the key to `Star Trek' is not all the
wonderful stuff we talk about: the character interplay, the sci-fi,
action and adventure and all those good things that seem to be on
the surface,'' he said.
   ``Somewhere underneath, the chemistry and the concept touch upon
a mythological need in modern culture. That's my real thought. I
don't quite know what I mean. It would take a far more intelligent
and perceptive person to divine what I mean.''
   Paramount Pictures takes a far less intellectual view of the
phenomenon. The company still makes nice rentals on the 1960s TV
series, and ``Star Trek: The Next Generation'' has prospered in
syndication. A $50 million gamble on the 1979 ``Star Trek: The
Motion Picture'' paid off handsomely. ``Star Trek IV: The Voyage
Home'' was the highest moneymaker of the series, earning $57 million
in rentals.
   Now comes ``Star Trek V: The Final Frontier,'' directed by
William Shatner. Why would he want to take on the onerous job of
guiding an immensely complicated production?
   ``Directing a film is the end of the rainbow,'' he said in an
interview. ``You've seen those T-shirts: `What I really want to do
is direct.' What I really want to do is direct. I've directed
several stage plays, some television. I thought that directing a
huge, large-budget motion picture might be something that would be
the culmination of all my efforts.
   ``I was indeed the culmination of my career _ I don't know if
this will be the end of my career. It is certainly the top moment of
my life, and it was everything I hoped it would be.''
   Leonard Nimoy, who directed ``The Voyage Home'' as well as
``Three Men and a Baby'' and ``The Good Mother,'' gives his co-star
good marks as a director.
   ``I think he's terrific,'' Nimoy said. ``He has a quality which
is wonderful. It's an almost childlike desire to entertain, to tell
a story, to capture your attention, to surprise you and touch you,
make you laugh. He wants to do that: to be a fun storyteller. That
kind of exuberance will serve him well.''
   Nimoy also discussed the difference in their directorial styles.
   ``The joke is that in a William Shatner film he does a lot more
running and jumping,'' he said. ``He's much more physical as a
person than I am. I've always been a lot more sedentary, always made
more cerebral choices in my acting. He makes more physical choices.
He would rather do a chase than a conversation.''
   ``The Final Frontier'' was Shatner's baby from the beginning. He
submitted a 14-page original story about a messianic leader who
kidnaps the Enterprise and its crew and takes them to a faraway land
where he believes God resides. Producer Harve Bennett approved his
story idea, and the pair worked on the plot with David Loughery, who
wrote the script.
   Production was stalled by two industry strikes and Nimoy's
commitment to direct ``The Good Wife.''
   ``The Final Frontier'' had only 18 weeks in post-production,
Shatner said, which was about one-third of what was needed. The
speed may have contributed to bad previews which were reported in
the press. The movie was retooled for its wide release on June 9.
   With all of his directorial duties, was Shatner the actor
neglected?
   ``Interesting,'' he mused. ``If I had been handed this script and
somebody else was directing, I probably have gone in and said,
`Look, I don't think the character is quite focussed.'
   ``I might have shortchanged myself as the egotistical actor. Let
me rephrase that. I don't mean egotistical in the bad sense; I mean
in the actor whose sole point of view is the character.
   ``My job when hired for Capt. Kirk was to keep my focus on Capt.
Kirk, to protect Capt. Kirk, to make him as exciting and make him
move as well as possible,'' he said.
   ``I didn't want to do that with this film. I wanted to open
myself up and make sure the other characters were not only protected
but a great deal was made of them.''
   Shatner, 58, is a Canadian, born and reared in Montreal. He
started acting early.
   ``I began at the age of six, acting in camp plays,'' he related.
``I continued in Montreal amateur theatricals as a teen-ager. I put
myself through college with radio work. I went to the professional
theater when I graduated from the university (McGill), stayed in the
professional theater through thick and thin. I've never done
anything else but act, write and direct.''
   Trained in the classics at the Stratford (Ontario) Shakespeare
Festival, he made his Broadway debut in the festival's ``Tamburlaine
the Great.'' Shatner became one of the busiest actors in live TV
dramas, won an MGM contract and made his film debut in ``The
Brothers Karamazov.''
   For a time he bounced between the theater (``The World of Suzie
Wong,'' ``A Shot in the Dark''), films (``Judgment at Nuremberg,''
``The Outrage'') and television (``For the People'').
   In 1965, Gene Roddenberry produced a pilot of a new space series
starring Jeffrey Hunter as Capt. Christopher Pike. NBC gave it
thumbs down, declaring it too cerebral. Roddenberry shot a second
pilot for ``Star Trek,'' casting William Shatner as Capt. James T.
Kirk in what became something of a lifetime job.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 9-11 and Thereafter</NOTE>
</DOC>
