<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     06-07 0852</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0890</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Communications Inc. launched a $10.7
billion takeover offer for the publishing and cable giant Time Inc.,
whose board has already agreed on a merger with Warner
Communications Inc.
   Paramount, an entertainment and and communications company
formerly known as Gulf &amp; Western Inc., said Tuesday it offered $175
a share for all of Time's stock.
   The announcement came less than three weeks before shareholders
of Time and Warner are scheduled to vote on the merger agreement
announced in March.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc.
proposed a $6.5 billion takeover of LIN Broadcasting Corp. in a deal
that would solidify McCaw's position as the nation's largest
cellular telephone company.
   McCaw, which is based here, said Tuesday it planned to launch a
cash tender offer for all of LIN's stock at a price of $120 a share.
   New York-based LIN operates seven network-affiliated television
stations and has interests in cellular systems serving New York, Los
Angeles, Philadelphia, Dallas and Houston. It said it would study
McCaw's bid.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's upheaval has prompted U.S. tour operators
to cancel vacation packages there and compelled airlines
specializing in the Pacific region to re-evaluate their service to
Chinese cities on a daily basis.
   A number of operators, including American Express, said Tuesday
they've decided to scrub tours to China in the wake of the military
crackdown in Beijing on pro-democracy demonstrators.
   Customers, who have been promised full refunds, may experience
delays in claiming them from smaller companies, travel experts warn.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CNW Corp.'s board of directors approved a $1.6
billion buyout offer from a group that includes company management,
railroad company Union Pacific Corp. and other investors, prompting
hostile suitor Japonica Partners to withdraw its own offer.
   The buyout group formed by investment banker Blackstone Group,
which will hold a controlling interest in the railroad company,
agreed to pay $45.50 per common share in cash and $4.50 per share of
preferred stock.
   CNW stock jumped 75 cents to close at $47.50 a share Tuesday in
New York Stock Exchange composite trading.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Average airline fares have decreased at most
major airports, with competition increasing substantially since
deregulation a decade ago, according to an industry study.
   But another report, by the General Accounting Office, says
airlines charge an average of 27 percent more per passenger mile on
flights to and from 15 major hub airports than at other airports
included in the study.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alaska's governor and tourism officials, fearing
that Americans picture their state as a soiled paradise since the
biggest oil spill in U.S. history, began a damage-control tour to
promote the vast reaches unaffected by the disaster.
   ``If you went to Alaska and if you wanted to see the oil, you
would have to go to a pretty substantial expense and a lot of
trouble to do so,'' Gov. Steve Cowper said Tuesday.
   Tourism is a $750 million-a-year industry for Alaska, behind only
oil and seafood among the state's biggest industries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. said it sold five of its European
businesses to BSN, a French food and beverage company, for $2.5
billion in an effort to reduce some of its debt from a record buyout.
   The company said Tuesday that BSN bought the British biscuit
business of Nabisco Brands; British snack food makers Walker's
Crisps and Smith's Crisps; Belin Group, a French biscuit and pastry
business; and Saiwa, a biscuit and snack producer in Italy.
   The five European companies had pretax profit of $137 million on
sales of $1.2 billion in 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional efforts to force the
nation's thrifts to meet stringent capital requirements would push
almost one-third of the industry into insolvency and keep home
mortgage rates above 10 percent, the chief economist for a trade
association said.
   James Christian, director of the economics department for the
U.S. League of Savings Institutions, told Texas thrift executives
Tuesday that as many as 973 thrifts, with $768 billion in assets,
would fail to meet requirements that they maintain 3 percent
tangible capital.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banking groups lined up to oppose legislation
that would require financial institutions to cash government checks
for non-customers and offer low-cost savings or checking accounts.
   The bankers on Tuesday told the Senate Banking subcommittee on
consumer and regulatory affairs that banks have been doing a good
job of voluntarily meeting the needs of the poor and elderly.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market closed moderately higher Tuesday after a choppy
session marked by continued program trading and nervousness about
the situation in China. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose
15.62 points to 2,496.32.
   The price of gold shot up nearly $12 an ounce, while the dollar
sagged.
   Bond prices finished mixed.
   Demand for precious metals increased because of the turmoil in
China, driving up the price of gold and silver; cotton prices
continued their slide; grain and soybean futures fell; livestock and
pork prices declined; and oil futures were lower.
</TEXT>
