<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 0206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-China-USBusiness Bjt   06-07 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-US Business, Bjt,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Big Companies Evacuate China; Banks Tighten Lending Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. banks are tightening lending guidelines for
Chinese-foreign business ventures because of the civil strife that
threatens to engulf China, and American companies are accelerating
their retreat from the country.
   Reversing its position of a day earlier, McDonnell Douglas
Corp.'s Douglas Aircraft Co. announced Tuesday it was evacuating
expatriates and was among the first companies to charter a plane for
the pullout.
   The Douglas Aircraft workers included 43 from a Shanghai factory
that assembles MD-80 twinjets, seven workers based in the southwest
city of Chengdu and one representative in the northeast city of
Shenyang.
   ``We've changed our situation in China. We decided last night to
begin pulling our people out of China back to Hong Kong,'' Douglas
Aircraft spokesman Donald Hanson said from company headquarters in
Long Beach, Calif. ``The situation apparently has changed
overnight.''
   Babcock &amp; Wilcox Co. also was moving out its staff of about 30
workers housed near Beijing's Summer Palace and Hewlett-Packard Co.
was attempting to withdraw an unspecified number of people from
Beijing and Shanghai.
   Several other companies also ordered employees to leave China and
scrapped business trips there because of the growing fear of civil
war.
   The intensified effort to get employees out reflected the
deteriorating situation in Beijing since the weekend, when soldiers
killed hundreds of unarmed pro-democracy demonstrators and other
civilians. Protests have flared in other cities and it has become
unclear if anyone is running the country.
   In another sign that the chaos may have a widening and profound
economic impact, U.S. banks began reviewing credit to companies that
do business with China and shortened time limits on new loans for
trade and investment projects.
   ``We're doing something all banks are doing, just making sure any
new commitments and any renewed commitments are kept very
short-term, three months or less,'' said an official of one major
New York bank, who asked not to be identified by name.
   An official of another big New York bank, who also requested
anonymity, said: ``It's obvious that any sensible country-risk
process would be operative under present conditions and commitments
would be reviewed.''
   Bank of America, Chase Manhattan Bank, Chemical Bank, Citibank
and First Chicago are among some of the prominent U.S. banking
companies with offices in China. Many established representative
offices there after relations were normalized a decade ago.
   The banks' main role is to expedite financing for joint ventures
between U.S. and Chinese companies, but their direct loans to the
Chinese are considered inconsequential and aren't reported in their
accounting statements.
   A study by Morgan Guaranty Trust Co. estimated that total U.S.
bank loan exposure in China was less than $1 billion.
   Nonetheless, China's government historically has been considered
an excellent credit risk and many other foreign banks have loaned
money to the country.
   The Institute of International Finance, a Washington research
organization for commercial banks, estimates China's foreign debt
totaled $42.4 billion at the end of 1988, of which 46 percent was in
commercial bank loans. But the size of the debt compared with the
country's overall economic output is small.
   ``A simple way of looking at it is that China doesn't have that
much external commercial debt,'' said Thomas Layman, the institute's
director for Asia and the Pacific.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890607-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 0453EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Children'sTV     06-07 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Children's TV,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Backs TV Station Targeted by Complaint About Children's Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Los Angeles television station was not
required to tell viewers that a toy maker was providing a children's
program in exchange for free advertising time, the Federal
Communications Commission ruled.
   The commission, in a ruling Tuesday that uphold's the common
industry practice of ``barter'' sales, denied a complaint that
KCOP-TV should have identified Mattel Inc. and TV syndicator Group W
Productions as the sponsors of the animated cartoon show, ``He-Man
and the Masters of the Universe.''
   The Los-Angeles based National Association of Better Broadcasting
had characterized the children's fantasy show as a non-stop
depiction of ``He-Man'' logo and ``He-Man'' toy products, which are
made by Mattel.
   The association said the barter arrangement, whereby Mattel and
Group W provided ``He-Man'' in exchange for two minutes of
commercials distributed throughout KCOP's children's program
schedule, constituted a ``token payment,'' given the cost of
producing the shows.
   The association said the producers spent $14 million to make 65
episodes of the program.
   The association, in a 1984 complaint, said Section 317 of the
1934 Communications Act requires that sponsors be identified
whenever shows are provided free or with only nominal payment.
   But KCOP valued the commercial time at $300,000 a year. At the
same time, it said that even if the payment were deemed ``token,''
Section 317 does not require sponsor identification when the
sponsors are mentioned incidentally or not at all in the broadcast.
   The FCC in 1985 denied the complaint, which had been joined by
Action for Children's Television. NABB appealed to the U.S. Court of
Appeals in Washington, which in September 1987 remanded the case to
the commission.
   The FCC denied the complaint again Tuesday.
   ``I guess it would be amazing if they had voted any other way,''
Peggy Charren, head of Action for Children's Television, said of the
3-0 FCC ruling.
   She said the problem of advertising messages slipped into TV
programs was ``one of the sorriest problems in all of broadcasting''
and that the FCC was saying they are ``going to let everything relax
on the subject of advertising and editorial content.''
   NABB President Frank Orme said his group would continue the fight.
   ``Whatever they have done, the court will have to approve,'' Orme
said by telephone from Los Angeles. ``I think eventually we will win
this.''
   Charren's group, which helped write a bill pending in Congress
that would re-impose limits on the amount of commercials on kids'
shows, had said various broadcasters were violating FCC regulations
by airing ``He-Man'' and seven other programs with substantial
product tie-ins.
   But the commission, in its 1985 ruling, said such the shows were
not program-length commericials. The commission said the
broadcasters ``had made a good faith determination that `He-Man' and
the other challenged programs possessed significant entertainment
value for child audiences.''
   The appeals court said the FCC had interpreted Section 317
incorrectly and it instructed the agency to devise a standard to
determine if Section 317 covers barter arrangements.
   In its ruling Tuesday, the FCC admitted it erred when it said
Section 317 applied only to broadcasts that were purely commercial
in content. As for determining a standard, it said KCOP clearly had
paid more than a nominal fee for ``He-Man,'' and Section 317,
therefore, did not apply.
   The commission said it was not its business to ``engage in a
detailed review of the adequacy of a broadcaster's payment in every
case in which a program discount is alleged.''
   It such such an approach would ``not necessarily further the
statutory objectives, is unlikely to yield conclusive results and
could require disclosures that cause substantial competitive harm to
program suppliers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
