<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0311 06-07 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0311,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Edges Up, Share Prices Erase Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged up against the Japanese yen
Wednesday morning, while share prices erased early gains and
declined on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost 5.07
points Tuesday, lost another 15.04 points, or 0.04 percent, to
finish the morning session at 33,436.97.
   The dollar was trading at late morning at 142.88 yen, after
opening lower at 142.45 yen, down 0.18 yen from Tuesday's close of
142.63 yen. The currency moved in the range of 142.40 to 143.00 yen.
   There were two main incentives in the foreign exchange market
Wednesday: an incentive to buy due to the turmoil in China, and one
to sell sparked by a prime rate cut by U.S. banks, said Mitsuhiko
Kinugawa, a trader at Daiwa Bank.
   He said the buying pressure due to the situation in China was
stronger.
   Investors tend to purchase dollars in times of uncertainty or
crisis.
   ``Although Japanese investors don't have a feeling of emergency,
they are buying because of reactions overseas,'' he said.
   Many market players believe the U.S. Federal Reserve Board has
been easing its monetary policy since major U.S. banks lowered their
prime lending rate by 0.5 percentage point to 11 percent Monday.
   The trader said the Bank of Japan intervened in the market by
selling the dollar to support the yen. He said the amount of the
bank's selling was unknown. The central bank does not comment on its
monetary activities.
   On the stock market, the index fell marginally mainly due to
selling for profit-taking after earlier gains, while the majority of
market players remained on the sidelines.
   Other traders said turmoil in China contributed to the
wait-and-see mood in the Tokyo market.
   Japanese goverment has urged the swift evacuation of Japanese
residents in China. Many Japanese businesses in China have closed
temporarily and brought employees back to Japan.
</TEXT>
