<SECOND>BC-China-Hong Kong,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Stocks Up Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange
rose for a second day Wednesday on reports that the power struggle
in China may be ending.
   Trading was active, and brokers said they were surprised by the
brisk activity.
   The Hang Seng Index of blue chips, which plummeted Monday in its
worst loss since the worldwide market collapse in 1987, closed at
2,224.66 points, up 74.95 points. All blue chips registered gains.
   Volume totaled $296.5 million, up from $256.6 million Tuesday.
   On Monday, the index closed at 2,093.61 points, down 581.77
points from Friday. The drop was the worst since the 1987
international market collapse, when the index fell 1,120.99 points
in one day.
   The Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corp., the territory's largest
bank, said it purchased shares for a third straight day to bolster
the market.
   Brokers linked the market's activities to reports that Chinese
troops responsible for attacks on pro-democracy demonstrators last
Sunday were leaving Beijing.
