<FIRST>r f BC-Spain-Bankers     06-07 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spain-Bankers,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Banker Says Cooperation Exists In Exchange Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of France Governor Jacques de Larosiere
said Wednesday that the top seven industrialized nations continue to
cooperate to keep exchange rates stable despite recent volatility in
world markets.
   ``There has been some volatility over the past month,'' he told a
bankers' forum. ``But what is important is that the international
cooperation put in play since 1985 is still operating.
   ``The seven major countries are on the same wave-length and do
understand the problems in the same fashion,'' de Larosiere said at
the end of the three-day International Monetary Conference attended
by members of 99 comercial banks from 22 countries.
   He said the major task of the cooperation was to keep inflation
down and sustain current economic growth.
   De Larosiere made the remarks to reporters after a closed meeting
with private bankers and central bank governors or senior officials
of the United States, Japan, West Germany, England and Spain.
   Sir Jeremy Morse, chairman of Lloyd's Bank Plc, moderated the
central bankers' discussion and appeared later before reporters.
   U.S. Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan and Bundesbank
President Karl Otto Pohl participated in the closed-door panel but
did not attend the press briefing.
   Morse said Greenspan had told the bankers it was difficult to
correctly evaluate the recent rise in the dollar's value.
   But he said Greenspan indicated the dollar's rise appeared to be
more of a market phenomenon than the result of fundamental economic
factors.
   Morse said the central bank officials did not believe the dollar
``was likely to go raging on.''
   The Bank of England's Robin Leigh-Pemberton sai, ``The degree of
currency stability is still reasonably satisfactory'' if seen from
the view of whether it inhibits cross-border investment.
   He added that the markets had seemed to incorrectly imply that
the international coordination policy on exchange rates ``had given
up.''
   Takeshi Ohta, the Bank of Japan's deputy governor for
international relations, said policy coordination among the major
nations does not always mean taking measures ``at the same time in
the same direction.''
   But he said, ``We should be able to move swifly when necessary.''
   He and de Larosiere expressed concern over too much emphasis
being placed on monetary policy to attempt to cut back economic
imbalances.
</TEXT>
