<FIRST>r f PM-OPEC 2ndLd-Writethru   06-07 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OPEC, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC Works to Restart Talks on Production, Pricing Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with three grafs to UPDATE with several bargaining sessions
being held. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `We are ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC oil ministers today held a flurry of
bargaining sessions to try to break a deadlock in negotiations for a
new production and pricing agreement.
   ``We are working toward an agreement for sure,'' said Iraqi Oil
Minister Issam Abdul Raheem al-Chalabi.
   The ministers of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries held private meetings in their hotel rooms in
late morning and early afternoon. They took a break after lunch and
planned further discussions in late afteroon.
   ``We are consulting with each other and hope to reach an
agreement,'' said Qatar's minister, Abdul Aziz bin Khalifa al-Thani.
   He predicted a deal could be struck within the next two days.
   OPEC Secretary-General Subroto raised the possibility that all 13
ministers would gather at cartel headquarters later in the day to
resume their formal strategy session.
   The ministers opened their mid-year conference on Monday, then
broke up to bargain privately.
   The talks have stalled over a Kuwaiti demand for a much larger
share of any increase in cartel production in the last half of the
year. Other members, including influential Saudi Arabia, want the
increase shared proportionately among all the members.
   ``A lot of work needs to be done,'' Iranian Oil Minister
Gholamreza Aqazadeh said Tuesday. ``We need about one or two days
for consultations,'' Aqazadeh said.
   A delegate from one nation, who demanded anonymity, said, ``It's
a deadlock.''
   The ministers seemed in agreement on lifting their production cap
to 19.5 million barrels a day, or at most 20 million barrels a day,
in the last six months of the year. The ceiling in the January-June
period is 18.5 million barrels a day.
   The ministers also appeared to have settled on retaining their
benchmark price of $18 a barrel. Saudi Arabia had recommended
getting rid of the target price.
   The cartel late last year agreed on its supply ceiling of 18.5
million barrels a day for the January-June period, well under output
levels at that time.
   Cutbacks earlier in the year helped drive prices beyond the
cartel's $18 benchmark.
   Prices have eased a bit recently as OPEC has turned up its
production. But the price of a basket of crudes monitored by the
cartel was still more than 40 percent above the level of late
November.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for July
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, has
been trading at more than $20 a 42-gallon barrel.
   The International Energy Agency, meanwhile, reported that the
OPEC nations lifted their crude production by 500,000 barrels a day
in May to 21 million barrels, the highest so far this year.
   ``This was primarily the result of higher production in Kuwait
and Nigeria, partly offset by a small decline in Iranian and
Ecuadorian production,'' it said.
   The slippage in Ecuador's output, it said, was due to a landslide
that damaged the country's main oil pipeline.
   The agency's Monthly Oil Market Report predicted demand for the
cartel's oil would rise in the second half of the year to about
20.85 million barrels a day. The agency previously estimated demand
for the period at 20.4 million barrels a day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
