<FIRST>u f PM-LIN-McCaw 1stLd-Writethru   06-07 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LIN-McCaw, 1st Ld - Writethru,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw Offers $120 A Share For LIN Broadcasting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 new grafs to UPDATE with early stock activity,
editing to conform. Picks up 7th graf, There had...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LIN Broadcasting Corp. shares shot higher
in early trading today in response to a $6.5 billion takeover offer
by McCaw Cellular Communications Inc.
   The $120-a-share unsolicitated offer, disclosed after stock
trading closed late Tuesday, would solidify McCaw's position as the
nation's largest cellular telephone company.
   In national over-the-counter trading early today, LIN was up
$24.25 a share to $127.25. McCaw rose $2.50 to $45.75 a share.
   McCaw, which is LIN's largest shareholder with a 9.8 percent
stake, has franchises serving customers in Seattle, San Francisco,
Miami, Denver, Minneapolis and Portland, Ore.
   New York-based LIN operates seven network-affiliated television
stations and has interests in cellular systems serving New York, Los
Angeles, Philadelphia, Dallas and Houston. It also owns a specialty
publishing house that produces hard-cover tourist guides for hotel
rooms.
   LIN said in a statement it would ``study the offer carefully and
act in the best interests of its shareholders.''
   There had been speculation for months that McCaw would launch an
offer for LIN.
   LIN announced two weeks ago that its board had approved in
principle spinning off all of the stock in a new subsidiary that
would own its TV stations. It said it would operate its cellular
operations along with a specialty publishing business as a separate
company.
   LIN said the move was made for operating and strategic reasons
due to the differences in the nature of the television and
cellular-phone industries.
   The McCaw proposal was seen by industry analysts as a recognition
of the premium that the stock market has placed on the fast-growing
cellular business.
   ``Given the regional geographic and operational nature of the
cellular business, the logic of combining our two companies is
compelling,'' McCaw Chairman Craig O. McCaw said in a letter to Lin
Chairman Donald A. Pels.
   In the letter, McCaw called the $6.5 billion bid ``the highest
price per `pop' in the history of our (cellular) industry.''
   Pop, a yardstick in the industry, refers to market area
populations multiplied by percentage ownership in the cellular
systems serving those areas.
   McCaw's cellular telephone systems serve 50 million pops, while
LIN serves more than 18 million pops.
   ``The next stage in the development of American cellular
communications must be the rationalization of the many disconnected
fragments of our industry,'' the McCaw letter said. ``The McCaw-LIN
combination would hasten that process. ... We would thus advance the
effort to provide a truly national cellular network for American
consumers.''
   LIN's TV stations are KXAS in Fort-Worth-Dallas; WISH in
Inidianpolis; WOTV in the Battle Creek, Mich., area; WAVY in Hampton
Roads, Va.; KXAN in Austin, Texas; WAND in central Illinois; and
WANE in Fort Wayne, Ind.
   Last year LIN earned $82 million on revenue of $226 million.
</TEXT>
