<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1022EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f BC-Britain-Dockworkers     06-07 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Dockworkers,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Blocks Dock Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Court of Appeal on Wednesday granted British
port employers an injunction banning a national dock strike.
   The strike had been planned for sometime this summer by 9,400
dockers affected by the British government's plans to abolish a job
guarantee scheme.
   The Court of Appeal's verdict overturns an earlier decision by
the High Court which refused to outlaw a dock strike.
   The Transport and General Workers' Union, which represents
dockworkers, is expected to appeal the verdict to Britain's highest
court, the House of Lords.
   Since the government first announced its intention to abolish the
dock labor scheme, under which employees are guaranteed lifelong job
security, a dispute has raged between employers and unions over
whether strike action would constitute a ``political protest''
against the government or a genuine ``trade dispute.''
   Under the 1982 Employment Act, political disputes are illegal.
   Last month, dockworkers at 46 British ports voted overwhelmingly
in favor of striking against the government's proposals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
