<HEAD>Turmoil in China Continues to Affect Grain Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower this
morning on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   China again was on the minds of traders, as the unrest there
raises concern there will be reduced demand by that nation for U.S.
wheat, according to Rich Feltes, an analyst for Refco Inc. in
Chicago.
   Forecasts for dryer weather in winter crop areas is expected to
allow farmers to move ahead with the harvest, putting added pressure
on wheat prices.
   The announcement yesterday of the sale of 300-thousand metric
tons of corn to the Soviet Union may offer limited support to corn
prices.
   In early trading, wheat was 2 cents to 2} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.86 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
1} cents lower with July at $2.59} a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1{
cent lower with July at $1.61 a bushel and soybeans were a { cent to
2 cents lower with July at $7.12 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat prices were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent lower to .30 cent higher with June at
68.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .43 cent
higher with August at 79.10 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower
to .17 cent higher with June at 48.32 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .40 cent lower to .15 cent higher with July at 30.60
cents a pound.
   Livestock and pork futures settled lower Tuesday.
