<FIRST>r f PM-NissanVote     06-07 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nissan Vote,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Election July 26 and July 27</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan Motor Manufacturing Corp. U.S.A.
and the United Auto Workers have agreed to a union election at the
plant July 26-27.
   It will be the first vote on union representation since
production began at the plant southeast of Nashville in 1983.
   The plant, Nissan's only one in this country, manufactures light
pickup trucks and Sentra cars.
   The agreement Tuesday came after three days of testimony before
the National Labor Relations Board in which the parties argued over
which employees would be eligible to vote.
   Union officials have made the plant a priority. The UAW filed a
petition with the NLRB May 18 to hold the election.
   Union organizers said about 2,400 of Nissan's 3,200 workers are
eligible to join the union.
   Under the agreement, the collective voting unit will include all
hourly production and maintenance employees _ or technicians _
including the 176 lead technicians and maintenance apprentices.
   Excluded are all other personnel, including office, clerical,
professional, managerial, contract labor, guards and supervisors.
</TEXT>
