<HEAD>Eastern in Talks with American on South American Routes</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf to UPDATE with comment from American spokesman;
picks up 5th graf pvs bg'ng, Wall Street ...; ADDS byline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikebound Eastern Airlines is in negotiations
to sell its South American routes to rival American Airlines, an
Eastern spokesman said today.
   ``We have talked to American,'' Jim Ashlock said from Eastern's
headquarters in Miami. He said Eastern also has had talks on the
routes with other airlines since announcing its plan to rebuild as a
smaller carrier and sell around $1.8 billion in assets separately.
   Ashlock declined to identify the other carriers interested in the
South American network or to disclose Eastern's asking price.
   Ed Stewart, a spokesman for American at its headquarters in Fort
Worth, Texas, wouldn't confirm that the talks had taken place
although he acknowledged American's general interest in Eastern
assets. ``We're looking at things that might be for sale,'' he said.
   Wall Street analysts have estimated the value of the South
American routes at around $150 million.
   Any sales of Eastern assets must be approved by the federal
bankruptcy court. Eastern sought bankruptcy protection from
creditors on March 9, five days after pilots and flight attendants
joined striking ground workers represented by the Machinists union
in a walkout that virtually grounded the airline.
   The court recently approved the sale of Eastern's prized
Northeast shuttle to developer Donald Trump for $365 million.
   For American, the nation's largest airline, a purchase of the
South American routes would bolster its strategy to expand overseas
operations.
   American, which recently added new flights to Western Europe,
also has expressed interest in Eastern's Caribbean routes.
</TEXT>
