<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with closing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rallied to close higher Wednesday
inspired by gains on Wall Street and news of two big U.S. takeover
bids.
   The gains came against the background of a modest boost in
sterling, which helped to erase some of the lingering nervousness
from the pound's plunge last week.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index gained for the
second straight day after five days of losses prompted mainly by
fears that sterling's weakness would force another rise in British
interest rates.
   The 100-share index closed 10.5 points, or 0.5 percent, higher at
2,117.9, near the peak of 2,118.1 moments before the close. The
market's low was 2,103.9 at midmorning.
   Volume was 481.0 million shares, up from 445.8 million shares a
day earlier.
   News of the U.S. takeover bids bolstered stocks in the
telecommunications and publishing sectors of the British market.
   Paramount Communications Inc. launched a $10.7 billion offer for
Time Inc. and McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. announced a $5.85
billion bid for Lin Broadcasting Corp.
   London shares were able to advance across a broader front in the
afternoon as Wall Street posted some early gains.
