<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1402EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-RanchoSeco 1stLd-Writethru f0029 06-07 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rancho Seco, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0029,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voters Decide To Close Nuclear Power Plant; Child-Care Measure Nixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: NEW thruout to UPDATE with shutdown beginning; PICKS UP 13th
graf, `But supporters ...' Also moved on general news wired</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rancho Seco nuclear plant began
shutting down today after voters for the first time in U.S. history
decided to close a working reactor.
   With all precincts reporting, there were 111,867 votes, or 53.4
percent, against a measure that would have kept the plant operating,
and 97,460, or 46.6 percent, in favor. About 40 percent of
registered voters turned out.
   Tuesday's vote was not binding on the Sacramento Municipal
Utility District, which owns the 15-year-old plant, but a majority
of its elected board members had promised to abide by the will of
the people.
   ``The plant is in the process of being shut down today,'' said
Jeff Marx, a Rancho Seco spokesman.
   Marx said the mood is ``pretty somber'' at Rancho Seco, where the
jobs of many of the 1,500 to 2,000 employees and contractors are in
jeopardy. How many of those workers will be laid off is uncertain,
Marx said.
   SMUD General Manager David Boggs said he would put the plant into
``hot shutdown,'' in which the reactor is operable but producing no
electricity. SMUD will then confer with the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission on putting the reactor in cold shutdown and beginning the
decommissioning, he said.
   He said he had already informed the SMUD directors of his plan to
shut down the plant and would not seek their approval. He lamented
the vote and said decommissioning and dismantling could cost more
than $210 million.
   Public Citizen, a group formed in 1971 by Ralph Nader, said in a
statement that the vote ``marks the beginning of the end for nuclear
power in the United States. ``America's love affair with the atom is
over,'' it said.
   Meanwhile in Fremont, a city of 165,000 on the San Francisco Bay,
a child-care tax measure that was touted as the first of its kind in
the nation was trounced at the polls.
   Measure B, which would have taxed residents and businesses to pay
for citywide child care, was supported by many working parents,
feminists and business leaders but opposed by activists who targeted
senior citizens, older families and Christian groups.
   With all precincts reporting, there were 3,671 votes in favor and
12,697 against. The measure needed a two-thirds majority to pass.
   Voters in the utility district that includes most of Sacramento
County and parts of Placer County gave Rancho Seco a reprieve in
June 1988 but put it on probation until Tuesday's vote.
   Critics claimed the plant 25 miles from California's capital is
unsafe and has a poor operating record. They also expressed anger at
rising utility bills and pointed to a $400 million repair bill after
a 1985 overcooling accident that caused a two-year outage.
   But supporters said the 913-megawatt plant's bad days were over
thanks to an overhaul and hiring of new managers.
   The expense of decommissioning Rancho Seco, together with the
higher cost of buying electricity from outside sources, is expected
to boost utility bills, but estimates vary widely as to how much.
Boggs predicted an initial increase of 7.5 percent in 1990.
   Kim Dellinger, a spokeswoman for the the campaign to keep the
plant open, called the vote ``a big mistake.''
   ``It was based on the historical performance of Rancho Seco and
frustration with SMUD, without considering the ramifications of
shutting the plant that supplies half the power of the community,''
she said.
   The vote Tuesday marked the first time in the nation that voters
chose to shut down an operating nuclear power plant, according to
Greg Cooke, a Nuclear Regulatory Commission spokesman.
   Nuclear opponents have won elections preventing new nuclear
plants from being built in some states.
   The nuclear industry, fearful that a closure vote could
strengthen nuclear opponents, raised $580,000 for the campaign to
keep Rancho Seco open.
   Opponents, including the Campaign California environmental group
formed by Assemblyman Tom Hayden and his estranged wife, actress
Jane Fonda, raised $111,000, according to the latest campaign
reports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
