<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1634EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Soviet-Economy     06-07 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Economy,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economist Says 1988 Inflation Was 8-9 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet inflation was 8 percent to 9 percent last
year, about double previous government estimates, a top economist
said Wednesday.
   Abel Aganbegyan, an economic adviser to President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, said a 4 percent to 5 percent increase in official prices
combined with another 4 percent rise caused by excess money
consumers can't spend due to shortages.
   Deputy Finance Minister Vyacheslav Senchagov termed Aganbegyan's
estimate too high. He said the official estimate for 1988 price
increases was 2.7 percent to 2.8 percent, not 4 percent to 5 percent.
   The two Soviet economists spoke at a conference ``The Soviet
Union in the 1990s'' sponsored by the International Herald Tribune,
the Soviet Union's Economicheskaya Gazeta and the Soviet Chamber of
Commerce.
   They said the Soviet Union is hampered by lack of proper
statistics to determine the actual rate of inflation.
   Soviet officials denied for years that inflation existed, but
under the influence of Gorbachev's reforms have acknowledged
inflation and begun to talk about how to combat it.
   Last October, deputy statistics director Nikolai Belov said wages
rose 6.7 percent in the first nine months of 1988, but real income
rose only 3.5 percent. But he refused to term the difference a rate
of inflation.
   Aganbegyan said Soviet economic reformers were hampered when
Gorbachev took power in 1985 by a lack of understanding of the
severity of problems. Economic managers made the situation worse by
boosting spending on housing, education and health but implementing
no cuts, he said.
   Aganbegyan said that aggravated a budget deficit, officially set
at 35 billion rubles, or $56 billion, this year. But economists said
including money the government borrows from its savings, the deficit
is more than 100 billion rubles, or $160 billion.
   Senchagov said the Soviet government plans to attack the deficit
by slashing construction expenditures and relying on a drive for
efficiency for added production.
   Plans for 80 billion rubles, or $140 billion, in capital
investments will be halved, and 390 new construction projects will
be eliminated, he said.
   Gorbachev already has announced a 14 percent defense budget cut.
   But Ed Hewitt of the Brookings Institute in Washington, who also
spoke at the conference, said he saw ``every prospect that the
deficit will increase.''
   He called for the government to stop a flood of ill-considered
economic decrees.
   ``They've come out quickly, they've been poorly coordinated, in
some cases fighting with each other,'' he said. ``That's basically
because the reform has gone half-way.''
   U.S. industrialist Armand Hammer, who began his business career
with a deal with Soviet founder Vladimir Lenin to supply grain in
1921, told Western businessmen that flexibility would pay off in
dealings with the Soviet Union.
   ``Above all, you've got to have patience,'' the 91-year-old
Hammer said. ``I think it's worth it because they have a huge
population ... and they need everything.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
