<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Drop in Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed lower
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as traders continued to cast
a wary eye on events in China.
   Wheat prices were pushed lower by heavy professional and
commission house selling because of civil unrest in Beijing and
other Chinese cities.
   There is some doubt among traders that the 1.85 million metric
tons of wheat sold to China, which was announced earlier this week,
will be shipped or paid for, said Ted Mao, an analyst with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   ``Although the Agriculture Department says there has been no
disruption of business in China, it is a situation that can change
day by day,'' Mao said.
   Added pressure was placed on wheat prices by forecasts for drier
weather in winter crop areas, which is expected to allow farmers to
move ahead with the harvest.
   Corn prices were down despite the announcement Tuesday of the
sale of 300,000 metric tons of corn to the Soviet Union.
   The forecasts for drier weather is expected to promote soybean
planting in eastern crop areas, while wetter weather in other areas
is expected to spur growth, forcing down soybean prices, analysts
said.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 6\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.82 a bushel; corn was 1} cents
to 4\ cents lower with July at $2.57 a bushel; oats were unchanged
with July at $1.62{ a bushel; soybeans were 3\ cent lower to 1 cent
higher with July at $7.11 a bushel.
