<DOCNO> AP890607-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 2015EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Bankers-Mexico     06-07 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bankers-Mexico,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico, Creditors To Continue Debt Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico and its commercial bank creditors
agreed Wednesday to reconvene debt-reduction talks in New York
Friday.
   Mexico's undersecretary of finance, Angel Gurria, and William R.
Rhodes, co-chairman of a bank-negotiating committee, said in a
statement that a two-hour meeting in Madrid ``set the stage for
rapid progress in the negotiations with the commercial banks.''
   The meeting coincided with a three-day International Monetary
Conference attended here by members of 99 comercial banks from 22
countries.
   After the debt meeting with Mexico, Rhodes, a Citibank executive,
told reporters, ``We have gotten a better understanding of what type
of funding and guarantees the IMF (International Monetary Fund) and
World Bank are willing to provide.
   ``We've heard from the official institutions, now we will have to
work out the details.''
   Mexico has criticized the commercial banks' attitude toward debt
rescheduling.
   Mexico owes $74 billion to about 500 commercial banks. Its
overall foreign debt totals $107.4 billion and is the second-highest
in Latin America, behind that of Brazil.
   The joint statement said the International Monetary Fund and the
World Bank had explained ``the nature and extent of their financial
support for debt and debt service reduction transactions to be
negotiated by Mexico and the commercial banks.''
   Mexico is viewed as a test case for the Bush administration's
Third World debt strategy, which calls on commercial banks to
forgive a substantial part of their loans to heavily indebted
countries in return for guarantees the rest will be repaid.
   But it did not specify how much financial support the lending
agencies had offered.
   IMF managing director Michel Camdessus told reporters at a
separate news briefing that the Madrid meeting was ``very positive''
and provided an opportunity for the international lending agencies
to inform Mexican officials and the commercial banks their view in
detail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
