<FIRST>r f AM-BlackFlag     06-07 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Black Flag,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>No More Taps for Ants on Black Flag Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black Flag admakers will still the sounding
of taps when ants and roaches die at the end of one of its insect
spray commercials.
   Viewer complaints about a few notes of the bugle call sounded at
military funerals have prompted the company to alter the ad,
American Home Products Corp. of New York, maker of Black Flag
insecticides, said Wednesday.
   Company spokeswoman Carol Emerling said the notes would be
deleted within about two weeks in response to an unspecified number
of complaints.
   ``Taps is a symbol,'' said Korean War veteran Bill Temple of Bryn
Mawr, who called the company Wednesday to complain. ``It represents
the finality of someone's incredible sacrifice.
   ``To trivialize it by playing it after blasting a bunch of ants
and roaches away is terrible,'' he said.
   Ms. Emerling wouldn't say who prepared the commercial or how many
complaints it drew.
   ``It was not a large response, but when we heard from a couple of
people we took another look at it,'' she said.
   American Home Products usually examines ad content before airing
them to ensure they won't offend viewers, Ms. Emerling said.
   ``We really try to be quite careful, but every now and then
naturally judgments differ,'' she said.
   Temple has been behind drives to build a national Korean War
memorial and to have a 1986 Clint Eastwood film altered to reflect
that Army troops, not Marines, fought the monthlong battle at
Heartbreak Ridge, one of the bloodiest in the Korean War.
   ``I lost an awful lot of buddies during that time I was in
combat,'' he said. ``I know what taps means to the people who lost
friends and relatives.''
   Temple said a woman who answered the telephone at American Home
Products told him the company had received several other complaints
about the Black Flag ad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
