<DOCNO> AP890607-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1744EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     06-07 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures prices skidded Wednesday
despite OPEC's decision to restrain crude oil production more than
the market had expected.
   The contract for July delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, dropped 79 cents to $19.67 a
42-gallon barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange, following
Tuesday's decline of 6 cents.
   The selloff was most severe in the wholesale home heating oil
pits. The July contract for No. 2 heating oil settled at 48.71 cents
a gallon, a loss of 2.29 cents on the day.
   Among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange,
unleaded gasoline for July delivery fell 1.60 cents to 63.34 cents a
gallon.
   Madison Galbraith, an energy specialist with Merrill Lynch Energy
Futures, said the market reacted skeptically to the agreement
announced by the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries.
   The cartel's ministers, meeting in Vienna, decided to raise
OPEC's production ceiling to 19.5 million barrels a day for the July
to December period. The current output cap of 18.5 million barrels
daily expires at the end of this month.
   The agreement retains the cartel's benchmark price of $18 a
barrel for the last half of the year.
   But the OPEC ministers apparently didn't come up with a solution
to the problem of members exceeding their self-imposed output
quotas. The cartel has been pumping an estimated 21 million barrels
a day in recent weeks, energy analysts say.
   ``The market told OPEC today: `We don't believe in you ... We
don't believe your numbers','' said Galbraith.
   The market initially displayed some strength when it was
announced that the new OPEC production ceiling was lower than the 20
million to 21 million barrels a day some analysts had anticipated.
   But doubts about OPEC's ability to abide by its accord created an
opportunity for traders to sell and collect profits. Selling was
dominated by large commercial energy brokers, Galbraith said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
