<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-07 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted in a narrow range in
foreign-exchange trading Wednesday and gold gave up part of the big
gain made late in the previous session.
   Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $374 a
troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $376.70 an ounce late
Tuesday. Gold had jumped about $12 an ounce in late trading Tuesday.
   The dollar held its ground despite a decline in the federal funds
rate to 9] percent, which confirmed to traders that the Federal
Reserve was easing credit policy by injecting fresh reserves into
the banking system.
   The federal funds rate, the rate on overnight loans between
banks, had hovered at close to 9} percent for months. Lower interest
rates would tend to discourage global investors from owning
dollar-denominated securities, but dealers said interest in the
dollar remained healthy.
   ``It seems like the dollar is still comfortable at this level
even if the Fed eased by one notch,'' said Eishi Wakabayashi, head
of foreign-exchange trading at Nippon Kangyo Kakumaru International
Inc. in New York.
   Traders continued to speculate that the Federal Reserve was
secretly selling dollars, but there was no confirmation of that,
said Jose Gonzalez, foreign-exchange manager at National Bank of
Detroit.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5815 to buy one pound, compared to $1.5665 late Tuesday. In New
York the pound rose to $1.5730 from $1.5710 on Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.17 yen to a closing 142.80 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 142.45 yen. In New York the dollar rose to 142.84
yen from 142.67 on Tuesday.
   Other dollar rates in New York compared with late Tuesday's rates
included: 1.9735 West German marks, unchanged from Tuesday; 1.7100
Swiss francs, up from 1.7095; 1.1975 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2010; 6.6867 French francs, down from 6.7060; and 1,436.2 Italian
lire, up from 1,434.
   Other dollar rates in Europe compared with late Tuesday's rates
included: 1.6965 Swiss francs, down from 1.7240; 6.6600 French
francs, down from 6.7360; 2.2138 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2370;
1,441.00 Italian lire, down from 1,443.00; 1.1967 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.2015.
   Gold rose in overseas markets to catch up with the gains made
late Tuesday in the New York trading session.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose $11.17 a troy ounce to a bid $376.61.
Gold jumped in London to a late bid price of $375.65 from $365.25 In
Zurich, the late bid was $374.50, up from $365.30 late Tuesday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $376.10 a troy ounce from $379.90 on Tuesday.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.38 a troy ounce,
up from Tuesday's $5.28. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery rose to $5.464 an ounce from $5.431.
</TEXT>
