<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru,0711</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Prices Rise on Fears of Supply Disruption</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RESTORES dropped words in 1st graf; deletes extraneous words
in 6th and 11th grafs; picks up 12th graf pvs, The ceiling ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices rose sharply Wednesday on New York's
Commodity Exchange on speculation that labor contract negotiations
at major U.S. copper producers will be accompanied by strikes.
   On other futures markets, precious metals were mixed, grain and
soybean prices fell, livestock and meat prices were higher and
energy futures declined.
   Copper rallied on word that officials of Magma Copper Inc.
expected labor contract talks to be difficult and expected a strike.
   Copper settled 2.25 cents to 2.45 cents lower with the contract
for delivery in June at $1.0885 a pound.
   Supply concerns were fueled by reports that Bougainville Copper
Ltd.'s supply contracts were delayed by the shutdown of its Papua,
New Guinea mine, said John O'Connell, an analyst with Refco Inc. in
New York. The mine has been damaged by attacks from native rebel
landowners.
   O'Connell said the rise in copper prices also could be attributed
partly to a comeback from a selloff spurred by the turmoil in China.
The nation is a big copper importer and traders reacted to the
upheaval there with a big selloff Tuesday due to speculation the
troubles would disrupt commerce and industry there.
   ``The markets are beginning to believe that the liquidation was
overdone,'' O'Connell said.
   Precious metal prices closed mixed on New York's Commodity
Exchange, following a runup of as much as $13 an ounce for gold on
Thursday. Silver continued the price rise that began Tuesday as the
dollar showed weakness.
   Gold was $2.40 to $3.80 lower with June at $376.10 a troy ounce;
silver was 3.3 cents to 3.6 cents higher with June at $5.464 a troy
ounce.
   Energy futures fell sharply in volatile trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange in the wake of OPEC's new production agreement.
   Oil ministers of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, meeting in Vienna, agreed to boost output to 19.5 million
barrels a day for the last half of the year, up 1 million barrels a
day from the current ceiling.
   ``The ceiling is not high enough,'' said Robert Baker, an analyst
wtih Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York. ``How many
nations will overproduce to get to higher level, the market just
doesn't know.''
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 53 cents to 79 cents lower
with July at $19.67 a barrel; heating oil was 2 cents to 2.29 cents
lower with July at 48.71 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was 1.32
to 1.60 cents lower with July at 63.34 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures prices were lower on the Chicago Board
of Trade.
   There is some doubt among traders that the 1.85 million metric
tons of wheat sold to China, which was announced earlier this week,
will be shipped or paid for, said Ted Mao, an analyst with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Corn prices were down despite the announcement Tuesday of the
sale of 300,000 metric tons of corn to the Soviet Union.
   Forecasts for drier weather are expected to promote soybean
planting in eastern crop areas, while wetter weather in other areas
is expected to spur growth, forcing down soybean prices, analysts
said.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 6\ cents lower with July at $3.82 a
bushel; corn was 1} cents to 4 cents lower with July at $2.57\ a
bushel; oats were unchanged with July at $1.62{ a bushel; soybeans
were 3 cent lower to 1 cent higher with July at $7.11 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were higher on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .25 cent higher with June at 68.82
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .30 cent higher with
August at 79.02 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .45 cent higher
with June at 48.52 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .45 cent
lower to 1.32 cents higher with July at 31.77 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
