<FIRST>r f AM-PenneyInsuranceSale     06-07 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Penney Insurance Sale,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Metropolitan Buys J.C. Penney Casualty Insurance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARWICK, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Metropolitan Property and Casualty Insurance
Co. announced Wednesday it would buy Ohio-based J.C. Penney Casualty
Insurance Co., which the retailing giant had said it wanted to
unload.
   The price was undisclosed. ``We don't anticipate it being a
significant loss or gain for us,'' said J. Duncan Muir, a spokesman
for J. C. Penney Co. at the retailer's Texas headquarters.
   The casualty insurance subsidiary, headquartered in Westerville,
Ohio, lost $7 million on premiums of $168 million last year, about
80 percent of it in auto insurance, Muir said. It had about 350,000
policies in force.
   Metropolitan Property and Casualty, a subsidiary of Metropolitan
Life Insurance Co. of New York, earned $40 million on premium income
of $543 million last year. It had 1.1 million policies, said
spokeswoman Liz Ostrowski.
   J.C. Penney will keep its life insurance subsidiary, Muir said.
Unlike rival Sears, Roebuck and Co., Penney had been unable to
produce a satisfactory package of financial services to sell through
its stores, Muir said.
   ``The direction of our company is to become a department store.
We found that people did not choose to make financial decisions at
the same time they were shopping for apparel,'' he said.
   Ms. Ostrowski said Metropolitan would probably keep Penney's
over-the-counter insurance sales force in place for up to 18 months
after the expected closing of the sale later this summer, then fold
those operations into Metropolitan's existing sales force of agents,
direct-marketing specialists and Century 21 real estate agents.
   Less certain was the future of 770 employees at Penney Casualty's
headquarters in suburban Columbus. Metropolitan would keep a service
center there, but staffing levels had not been decided, Ms.
Ostrowski said.
   Metropolitan, which writes most of its business in the Northeast,
wants to expand to the Midwest and South, Ms. Ostrowski said. Penney
Casualty wrote nearly half its premiums in 1987 in Ohio and
California, with other significant amounts in Pennsylvania and
Georgia, according to A.M. Best Co., an industry rating service.
   Best gave Penney's insurance operations a B-plus rating last
year, which one expert said is generally the lowest rating accepted
by insurance brokers. Metropolitan improved from B-plus to A-minus.
</TEXT>
