<DOCNO> AP890607-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 2301EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-IMF-ThirdWorldDebt     06-07 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-IMF-Third World Debt,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third World Debt Dropped $12.4 Billion in 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debts of the Third World to commercial banks
dropped by $12.4 billion last year, partly because banks used the
money to buy local assets, according to new figures from the
International Monetary Fund.
   The fund did not give totals in its monthly IMF Memorandum,
distributed this week, or the debts of individual countries. It
classes 130 countries in the Third World as ``developing.''
   According to the World Bank, its sister organization, Third World
debt now comes to $1.3 trillion. Michel Camdessus, the fund's
managing director, said banks hold about 60 percent of it. Most of
the rest is owed to governments and intergovernment bodies such as
the fund itself.
   Both organizations, owned by the same 151 governments, have
pledged to help reduce the debt further, as urged by Treasury
Secretary Nicholas F. Brady. They are pressing private banks to go
along by forgiving some of the debt in return for assurances that
interest will be paid promptly on what is left.
   There was a drop of $17.3 billion in the amount owed by the 15
countries singled out as specially troubled by Secretary of State
James A. Baker III when he was secretary of the Treasury in 1985.
The World Bank calculates that they owe about $520 billion. They
include Argentina and Venezuela, where price rises linked to debt
have brought bloody rioting recently.
   According to the fund, the reduction in the debt owed to the
banks is not due to repayments but to other operations.
   The banks disposed of $8.7 billion worth by using what the fund
calls official conversions. These include conversion of the debt
from dollars or other hard currency into the money of the debtor
country, and then buying shares of stock in local industry.
   Chile has taken the lead in these ``debt-equity swaps.'' In
Mexico, Brazil and other countries the swaps have been criticized as
contributing both to inflation and to the sale of too many important
assets to foreigners.
   The banks also sold off at a discount debts with a face value of
$8 billion. Some Third World debt brings as little as 10 cents on
the dollar in the market. After a sale, the debtor country still
owes the full face value to the new purchaser, but nothing to the
bank.
   In addition to the 15, more than 100 other Third World countries
are classified by the fund as ``developing.'' In 1987, the debts of
all of them to the banks increased by $18.7 billion.
   Debtor countries complain mostly about the burden of interest
payments. Camdessus reported last week that debtors fell another $11
billion behind on their payments in 1988. These are largely interest
payments, since few debtors have paid back much principal since 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890607-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 2309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-PrimeComputer     06-07 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Prime Computer,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>MAI Basic Says Prime Computer Has Beefed Up Its `War Chest'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MAI Basic Four Inc. said Wednesday it had filed a
lawsuit opposing the postponement of Prime Computer Inc.'s annual
meeting, where it plans to wage a proxy battle for control of the
company.
   The suit, filed in Delaware Chancery Court, seeks to compel the
Natick-based computer maker to hold the meeting June 14, as
previously scheduled.
   Prime announced Tuesday that it would delay the meeting until
July 26 to give its stockholders time to consider MAI's recent
reduction in its hostile tender offer, from $20 a share in cash to
approximately $19 a share in a mixture of cash and securities.
   MAI is a Tustin, Calif.-based computer company controlled by New
York investor Bennett S. LeBow. It has been pursuing Prime, a maker
of minicomputers and computer-aided design equipment, since November.
   On June 1, MAI cut its bid to $19.50 in cash for about 75 percent
of the shares on a fully diluted basis, plus securities with a face
value of $21 per share for the remaining 25 percent of Prime's stock.
   Since the securities are likely to trade at less than face value,
many analysts have valued the new offer at $18 to $19 a share.
   MAI also said Wednesday that Prime has put an additional $5
million into a war chest to oppose MAI's hostile takeover bid and
defend ``tin'' and ``golden'' parachute arrangements.
   Prime previously announced charges totaling $15.4 million for
legal, investment banking and other costs associated with fighting
MAI's tender offer.
   In a filing Monday with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
Prime said its board authorized a $5 million letter of credit to
cover legal costs for defending its employee protection and
executive retention agreements.
   Those agreements, known generically as tin and golden parachutes,
provide payments ranging from a few hundred to many thousands of
dollars to soften the landing for ordinary workers and top
executives who bail out of the company after a takeover.
   MAI has claimed the arrangements could cost the company up to
$170 million and has pledged to fight them in court.
   MAI charged Wednesday that Prime has ``apparently deliberately
chosen not to publicize this new $5 million commitment.''
   Prime spokesman Joseph Gavaghan declined to comment directly on
MAI's statement.
   Prime stock closed unchanged at $16.50 a share in composite
trading Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
